<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This report contains forward-looking statements.&nbsp; Statements in the "Business,&rdquo; &ldquo;Risk Factors,&rdquo; "Properties" and "Management's Discussion and
Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operation" sections of this report, together with other statements including words such as "believes," "intends," "plans," "anticipates, &ldquo;estimates," "projects," "expects" or similar expressions represent
forward-looking statements that are based on our expectations in light of facts known by management on the date this report was filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission (&ldquo;SEC&rdquo;).&nbsp; Specifically, statements regarding our future results of
operations, operating costs, business prospects, growth and capital expenditures, including plans with respect to our fleet, are forward-looking statements.&nbsp; These statements reflect our plans and assumptions about future events and are subject to uncertainties,
many of which are outside our control.&nbsp; Important factors that could cause actual results to differ materially from the expectations expressed or implied in the forward-looking statements include known and unknown risks.&nbsp; The five key areas of the known
risks that could significantly impact our revenues, operating results and capacity include:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p align="center"><b><font size="2" face="Arial">PART I</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="item1business"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Item 1. Business</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="general"></a><b><u><font size="2" face="Arial">General</font></u></b></p>

<p><u><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></u></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> <font size="2">ExpressJet Holdings, Inc. (&ldquo;Holdings&rdquo;) is engaged in the business of transporting people.&nbsp; Our principal asset is all of the
issued and outstanding shares of stock of XJT Holdings, Inc., the sole stockholder of ExpressJet Airlines, Inc. (referred to in this report as &ldquo;Airlines&rdquo; and, together with Holdings, as &ldquo;ExpressJet&rdquo;, &ldquo;Company&rdquo;, &ldquo;we&rdquo; or
&ldquo;us&rdquo;).&nbsp; Airlines currently operates a fleet of 244 aircraft.&nbsp; <font color="black">As of December 31, 2008, our fleet was assigned as follows:</font></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">214 aircraft operating for Continental as Continental Express pursuant to the Continental CPA; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">30 aircraft operating in our Corporate Aviation division, which is dedicated to charter contracts and ad-hoc charter service.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>
</div>

<font size="2" color="black" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<div>
<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> Our primary business is flying 244 aircraft under contractual arrangements for network carriers and entities desiring cost-effective and fully
customizable group travel.&nbsp; <font color="black">During 2008, we dramatically reshaped our business to adapt to unprecedentedly high fuel costs, recessions in the global economy, reductions in air-travel capacity, and other uncertainties facing the regional
airlines.&nbsp; We completed most of our transition to the contractually-arranged flying during the fourth quarter ending December 31, 2008.&nbsp; Additionally, we strengthened our balance sheet through the completion of the refinancing of our convertible debt,
reducing the debt from $134.7 million as of December 31, 2007 to $60.8 million as of December 31, 2008.&nbsp; We stabilized the use of operating cash as a result of the suspension of our Branded Flying (defined below) operations.</font> &nbsp; Furthermore, we
mutually agreed with Delta Air Lines (&ldquo;Delta&rdquo;) to suspend our capacity purchase agreement (the &ldquo;Delta CPA&rdquo;) and pro-rate flying arrangement&nbsp; (the &ldquo;Delta Prorate&rdquo;) effective September 2, 2008.&nbsp; With the suspension of these
flying operations, we anticipate generating cash from our contractual arrangements with Continental and our Corporate Aviation division.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We also provide aviation services, such as ground-handling at airport locations across the United States, as well as aircraft repair, overhaul, interior
refurbishments and paint, through our three wholly owned subsidiaries, which include ExpressJet Services, LLC (&ldquo;ExpressJet Services&rdquo;), American Composites, LLC (&ldquo;American Composites&rdquo;) and InTech Aerospace Services, LP (&ldquo;InTech&rdquo;)
and our and majority owned subsidiary, Saltillo Jet Center (&ldquo;Saltillo&rdquo;).&nbsp; During the first half of 2007, we rebranded American Composites, InTech and Saltillo so that each now goes under the &ldquo;ExpressJet Services&rdquo; trade name.&nbsp; These
entities are collectively referred to herein as &ldquo;Services.&rdquo;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Holdings was incorporated in Delaware in August 1996.&nbsp; Airlines is one of the largest regional airlines in the world, based on 2008 available seat miles, number of
regional jets and passengers transported.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We compete with a number of regional airlines for the service we provide to other airlines.&nbsp; We believe that our continuing success depends on our ability to
provide our charter customers and Continental outstanding operational performance and exceptional customer service while effectively managing costs.&nbsp; Our ability to do this depends on over 5,400 employees executing efficiently on a daily basis.&nbsp; Being
successful will allow us to improve our competitive position and provide value to our stockholders.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="ourbusinesssegments"></a><b><u><font size="2" face="Arial">Our Business Segments</font></u></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><u>Business Segments as of December 2008</u></b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; For the year ended December 31, 2008 and prior, <font color="black">ExpressJet had three reportable segments which are the basis of our internal financial reporting:
Contract Flying, Branded Flying and Aviation Services.</font></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Contract Flying includes our Corporate Aviation (charter) division and our capacity purchase agreements with Continental and Delta.&nbsp; Under Contract
Flying, revenues are contractually determined, eliminating our exposure to fluctuations in fuel prices, fare competition and passenger volumes.&nbsp; Under these arrangements, our partners bear the revenue risk and cost of marketing and distribution on our aircraft
while we are responsible for the operation and maintenance of the aircraft.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Branded Flying includes operations under the ExpressJet brand and the Delta Prorate.&nbsp; Revenues for this flying were derived from passengers flying on
scheduled air service.&nbsp; We were responsible for local market pricing, scheduling and revenue management, and the operation and maintenance of the aircraft.&nbsp; Our flying under the Delta Prorate provided us with a prorated portion of the airfare plus an
incentive for passengers connecting onto Delta's network.&nbsp; In September 2008 we suspended Branded Flying in response to high fuel costs and falling demand.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aviation Services includes our ground-handling services pursuant to contracts with Continental and other airlines at airport locations across the United
States, as well as those performed by Services.&nbsp; These entities provide composite, sheet metal, paint, interior (including seat refurbishment) and thrust reverser repairs throughout our five facilities in the United States and Mexico.&nbsp;</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="productsservices"></a><b><u><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">Our Products and Services</font></u></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Prior to 2007, virtually all of our revenue came from the Continental CPA and our entire fleet of 274 aircraft was flown in support of Continental&rsquo;s network.&nbsp;
In recent years, our products and services were focused on delivering cost-effective and reliable travel experience across the various business platforms for all of our customers.&nbsp; The result was an infrastructure that afforded us the ability to:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">continue our capacity purchase flying with Continental;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">develop our own brand through scheduled flying as ExpressJet Airlines;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">commence capacity purchase and prorate flying for Delta;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">establish a niche in the corporate and ad-hoc charter service market; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">broaden the scope of our maintenance and ground handling capabilities.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During the last half of 2008, due to external factors beyond our controls, this same infrastructure afforded us the ability to reshape our products and services.&nbsp;
We suspended our Branded Flying operations, focused on Contract Flying and reduced the number of aircraft in our fleet from 274 at the beginning of 2008 to 244 by the end of 2008.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our transition continues in 2009 as we seek additional opportunities to provide unique group travel experiences and to further leverage our capabilities with the
increasing number of aircraft dedicated to contractual flying outside of the Continental CPA.&nbsp; This is a dynamic process and will remain so for the foreseeable future as we seek to optimize revenue generation from our assets.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><u>Contract Flying</u></b></font></p>

<p><u><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></u></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, we averaged over 950 daily Contract Flying flights, offering passenger service to over 130 scheduled destinations in North America, including
Mexico as well as the Caribbean.&nbsp; We generated $1.1 billion of revenue (80.3% of our total consolidated revenue) in this segment.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="cappurch"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Continental Capacity Purchase and Other Agreements</i></font></b></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i></b> A significant portion of our revenue and cash flows is attributable to the Continental CPA.&nbsp; Under the Continental CPA, Airlines operates
flights on behalf of Continental as Continental Express.&nbsp; Continental controls and is responsible for scheduling, pricing and managing seat inventories and is entitled to all revenue associated with the operation of the aircraft.&nbsp; We also have various other
agreements with Continental that govern our relationship.&nbsp; For a detailed discussion of the Continental CPA, see Item 7. &ldquo;Management&rsquo;s Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations - - Contract Flying &ndash; Continental
CPA of this report.&rdquo;</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> <b><i>Delta CPA</i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During 2008, we averaged over 35 daily departures and offered scheduled passenger service to over 20 destinations in North America under the Delta CPA.&nbsp; We
generated $43.8 million of revenue during 2008 from this arrangement.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Delta CPA was scheduled to end on the second anniversary of each aircraft&rsquo;s in-service date (June 2009); however, Delta and ExpressJet mutually agreed in July
2008 to suspend this agreement effective September 2, 2008.&nbsp; Delta agreed to compensate us in August 2008 for costs incurred as a result of the early termination.&nbsp; On October 2, 2008, we transitioned the 10 aircraft previously operating within the Delta CPA
back to our current fleet.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" color="black" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Corporate Aviation</i></b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i></b> We expanded our Corporate Aviation division to 30 aircraft.&nbsp; These aircraft are now dedicated to existing and new long-term
agreements and ad-hoc charter service arrangements.&nbsp; Our Corporate Aviation division continues to focus on corporate shuttles, entertainment / sports, and government businesses.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, our Corporate Aviation division has contracted with
seven customers with long-term agreements spanning the next 12 months<b>.</b>&nbsp; Certain Corporate Aviation customers typically prepay deposits for flights based on a percentage of estimated charges to be incurred.&nbsp; These prepayments are held in escrow and
recorded as restricted cash and deferred revenue until the flights are completed.&nbsp; At that time we recognize the associated revenue and release the funds from escrow into our cash account.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Corporate Aviation&rsquo;s goal is to provide group travelers a comfortable, cost-effective and fully customizable travel experience that is unmatched by our
competitors.&nbsp; Additionally, our objective is to make jet charter the ultimate and most satisfying solution to getting people where they need to be.&nbsp; We are providing such travel solutions to corporations, including other air carriers from time to time,
collegiate athletic departments, sports franchises, government entities, hospitality companies and others.&nbsp; Our pricing structure is based on a contracted fee plus reconciliation payments for uncontrollable costs (including items such as fuel and deicing) for
the full amount from which actual costs differ from estimates.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The aircraft are flown under Airlines&rsquo; operating certificate issued by the Federal Aviation Administration (the &ldquo;FAA&rdquo;).&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We understand that every group travel situation is different.&nbsp; Therefore, we have reconfigured our aircraft and are currently offering two different
seat-configurations on our Corporate Aviation division fleet.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Our 41-seat passenger jet provides additional space for the customer.&nbsp; The seats in this configuration provide a 38-inch pitch, which is equivalent to a first class seat in a Boeing 737-800.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Our 50-seat passenger jet allows for larger groups, which helps maximize travel efficiency.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All of our seats are leather, memory foam cushioned seats and include XM Satellite Radio with over 100 channels of audio entertainment.&nbsp; In addition to our basic
amenities (such as providing blankets to each passenger and standard catering) customized flight service options give customers an opportunity to create a unique flight experience.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We generated $39.8 million in revenue as of December 31, 2008, and anticipate that revenues will continue to grow in this division as we continue to establish long-term
relationships which should result in greater predictability in this operation.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> <u>Branded Flying</u></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As of August 31, 2008, we averaged just under 250 daily departures by offering scheduled passenger service to over 30 destinations in North America with our ExpressJet
brand and Delta Prorate operations.&nbsp; Within this segment, we generated $222.0 million of revenue from January through December 2008.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During the last half of 2008, we dramatically reshaped our business in order to adapt to the then unprecedented high fuel costs and other challenges facing
the industry.&nbsp; As part of the transition, we suspended our ExpressJet Flying operations.</font> &nbsp; Furthermore, we mutually agreed with Delta to terminate the Delta Prorate effective September 2, 2008. <font color="black">&nbsp; We completed most of our
transition to Contract Flying during the fourth quarter of 2008.&nbsp;</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<b><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial"><font size="2"><br clear="all" />
</font></font></b>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>Fuel</u></font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We were fully exposed to the availability of fuel and fuel price increases during 2008 in operating aircraft in Branded Flying.&nbsp;</font> Our fuel
management strategy was to enter into fixed forward price contracts with our fuel provider using a systematic method for determining the volume and the price for which to enter into the contracts for a rolling 12-month period on a quarterly basis. <font color=
"black">&nbsp; For the year ended December 31, 2008, approximately 52.7% of our fuel expense was associated with our Branded Flying.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; With our transformation during the last quarter of 2008 from Branded Flying, including the terminations of our Delta CPA and prorate flying, we have also terminated our
fuel fixed forward price contracts.&nbsp; With the decision to suspend our Branded Flying operations, we sold our fixed forward purchase contracts for periods subsequent to September 2, 2008, which resulted in a non-operating gain of approximately $23
million.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Under the Continental CPA and various charter agreements, we are protected from the volatility of fuel prices; however, if the unavailability of fuel caused us to cancel
flights, our revenues would be reduced.&nbsp; We continue to work diligently with Continental and our fuel provider to ensure that fuel is available and ready for all our flights as part of our reliability and on-time performance program.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> <u>Aviation Services</u></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Revenues generated by Aviation Services totaled $43.8 million in 2008.&nbsp; This segment includes our ground-handling services pursuant to contracts with Continental
and other airlines at airport locations across the United States, as well as those performed by Services.&nbsp; Ground-handling services include departure management, baggage handling and ticket counter services for several airlines including Continental, American
Airlines, Inc. (&ldquo;American Airlines&rdquo;) and Allegiant Air at locations across the United States.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our Aviation Services segment also includes Services.&nbsp; These entities are the North American partner to three major European original equipment manufacturers and
provide composite, sheet metal, paint, interior (including seat refurbishment) and thrust reverser repairs throughout our five facilities in the United States and Mexico.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As a result of the reshaping of our business, we determined that certain entities under the Services, including the real estate holdings, are non-core assets to
Holdings.&nbsp; Therefore, we have been pursuing the monetization of some of these non-core assets and some or a portion of such assets may be sold in 2009.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="acfleet"></a><b><u><font size="2" face="Arial">Aircraft Fleet</font></u></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><u>Our Fleet</u></b></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We operate a fleet of 244 aircraft which includes Embraer ERJ-145 and ERJ-145XR aircraft.&nbsp; The Continental CPA provides for the continued lease or sublease of our
244 Embraer regional jets.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, 214 aircraft were operating under our Continental CPA and the remaining 30 aircraft were operating within our Corporate Aviation division.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The operational capability of the ERJ-145 is 1,100 miles.&nbsp; The ERJ-145XR, with a 1,600 mile range, continues to create potential expansion opportunities for us
whether under our network or other carriers&rsquo; networks to more economically serve cities that are the right size for our aircraft.&nbsp; We are currently the only operator of the ERJ-145XR in the world.&nbsp; Each aircraft is equipped with advanced technology
and certifications that aid our operation in challenging weather conditions and flying efficiently at higher flight altitudes.&nbsp;</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The aircraft dedicated to Continental offer a seamless jet service experience to Continental&rsquo;s passengers.&nbsp; The planes feature overhead baggage compartments,
under-seat baggage storage, leather seating, lavatories, in-flight meal and beverage service capabilities and jet-bridge loading in most locations.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aircraft dedicated to corporate charters have redesigned seats for enhanced comfort and feature complimentary XM Satellite Radio with over 100 channels of
entertainment.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We have options for 50 ERJ-145XR aircraft that may be exercised for other types of aircraft within the ERJ-145 Family.&nbsp; Our next option exercise date is April 1,
2009.&nbsp; If we do not exercise or extend our option as of this date, 25 options will expire.&nbsp; In 2005, Continental declined the right to include any of our option aircraft in the Continental CPA; consequently, Continental is not required to participate in the
financing for any option aircraft that we acquire.&nbsp; We currently have no firm orders for additional aircraft.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><u>Maintenance of Our Aircraft</u></b></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We maintain our aircraft primarily using our own trained and FAA-certified personnel and facilities.&nbsp; We perform routine maintenance in addition to the inspection
of our aircraft engines and airframes at intervals required by the FAA.&nbsp; We perform line and heavy maintenance at our facilities in Cleveland, Ohio; Houston, Texas; Knoxville, Tennessee; Ontario, California; Newark, New Jersey; Richmond, Virginia; and
Shreveport, Louisiana.&nbsp; We also perform line maintenance at our satellite maintenance stations.&nbsp; We maintain an inventory of aircraft spare parts to ensure the reliability of our operations and utilize a computerized tracking system to increase maintenance
efficiency and avoid excess inventory of spare parts.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We have a power-by-the-hour agreement with Rolls Royce to maintain the engines on our aircraft through April 2015.&nbsp; Under the agreement, we are charged a fixed rate
based on flight hours incurred during a month.&nbsp; The rates are subject to annual revisions based on specific labor and materials indices.&nbsp; We also have power-by-the-hour agreements with other key vendors to cover various high value components and systems on
the aircraft, such as auxiliary power units, avionics, environmental controls, tires, wheels and brakes.&nbsp; For 2008, 71% of our maintenance, materials and repairs cost consisted of power-by-the-hour expenses.&nbsp; We believe that these agreements, coupled with
our ongoing maintenance program, reduce the likelihood of unexpected maintenance expense during the aircraft lease terms and greatly mitigate accelerating maintenance costs commonly associated with aging aircraft.</font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></p>

<p><a name="copetitors"></a><b><u><font size="2" face="Arial">Competitors</font></u></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The airline industry is highly competitive.&nbsp; ExpressJet competes principally with other regional airlines providing long-term service to legacy carriers, aircraft
operators providing customized on-demand charter services, and companies who offer aircraft ground handling services.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We are one of several competitors in the commercial airline market.&nbsp; Our competitors include Chautauqua Airlines (&ldquo;Chautauqua&rdquo;), Mesa Airlines
(&ldquo;Mesa&rdquo;), Mesaba Airlines, Pinnacle Airlines (&ldquo;Pinnacle&rdquo;), Republic Airways (&ldquo;Republic&rdquo;) and SkyWest Airlines (including Atlantic Southeast Airlines) (&ldquo;SkyWest&rdquo;).&nbsp; We also compete with other airlines, such as
American Eagle, Comair, Compass and Horizon Airlines, which are wholly owned subsidiaries of major airline holding companies.&nbsp; One of the principal challenges for airlines operating regional jets under either fixed-fee or revenue-sharing arrangements, in
addition to depending on the financial health of their partners, is the ability to maintain reliable and seamless operations with a competitive cost structure.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Due to variations among the contracts under which regional airlines operate, cost comparisons between regional airlines are difficult.&nbsp; However, we believe
ExpressJet is the best operator in the industry with one of the most competitive capacity purchase agreements.&nbsp; After entering into the Amended Continental CPA, we significantly cut our operating cost structure &ndash; removing $100 million (annualized) in
expenses during 2008 &ndash; and continue to focus on the efficiencies of operating a single fleet type as well as utilizing technology to streamline and improve our operation.&nbsp; Finally, our position as the launch customer for the ERJ-145 family and our Amended
Continental CPA provides us some of the most favorable fleet financing in the industry.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our Corporate Aviation division competes in varying degrees with corporate aviation departments, non-scheduled aircraft operators and scheduled air carriers offering
non-scheduled service.&nbsp; We are the largest on-demand 41 and 50-seat aircraft operator and compete primarily with operators offering fewer seats.&nbsp; We operate under a part 121 certificate (complete commercial airline operator certificate from the FAA), which
requires higher standards than operators flying under a part 135 certificate (private airline operator certificate from the FAA).&nbsp; Some regional airlines, such as SkyWest and Chautauqua, offer similar products directly to customers or through subcontract
agreements with legacy carriers such as Continental or Delta.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During 2008, several charter companies ceased flying due to increasing costs, operating less efficient equipment, and increased competition.&nbsp; These events created
opportunities for us to leverage our experience and infrastructure.&nbsp; Growing awareness of our brand as a high quality product is enabling us to achieve continued market penetration.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our Aviation Services division competes with both airlines and non-airlines for long-term ground handling contracts.&nbsp; Some of these entities include SkyWest, Air
Wisconsin, American Eagle, Pinnacle, Delta Global Services, PrimeFlight, Servisair, Aircraft Service International, and Worldwide Flight Services.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="industry"></a><b><u><font size="2" face="Arial">Industry</font></u></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The United States airline industry has been very competitive since it was deregulated in 1978, and various business models have been developed to offer commercial air
service.&nbsp; The industry has traditionally been led by airlines, such as American Airlines, United Air Lines (&ldquo;United&rdquo;), Delta and Continental, which schedule flight service to most major U.S. cities, numerous smaller U.S. cities, and cities throughout
the world via a hub-and-spoke model.&nbsp; Other airlines, such as Southwest Airlines and JetBlue, offer scheduled flights to many of the same domestic markets, but at lower prices and with fewer amenities to travelers; they have competed effectively in the U.S.
market previously due to their lower cost structures.&nbsp; Another group, including ExpressJet, Mesa, Republic and SkyWest, has evolved to provide feeder service to the hub-and-spoke network or point-to-point service for smaller and medium-sized airports through
fixed-fee or revenue-sharing agreements.&nbsp; The development of the regional jets operated by this group has given legacy carriers the ability to connect markets in the United States, Mexico and Canada more economically than with larger aircraft.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Commercial airline strategies typically include:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">minimizing operating costs;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">broadening their networks to spread fixed costs over more flights;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">emphasizing international expansion to seize opportunities in the more regulated capacity controlled international market;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">focusing on business travelers, who historically have paid higher fares;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">formalizing code-sharing alliances (i.e., OneWorld, SkyTeam, etc.) in order to maximize marketing and network scheduling;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">maintaining capacity and market share;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">bringing additional connecting traffic into their networks through new alliances;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">adjusting fares to offset higher costs (such as fuel);</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">unbundling product features to increase revenue; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">differentiating product features from competitors.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Commercial airlines have faced unprecedented challenges over the last few years including volatile fuel prices and an economy in recession.&nbsp; Higher fuel costs have
resulted in upward pricing pressures, lower demand and capacity reductions.&nbsp; As fuel prices recede and the economy weakens, the economics of regional aircraft become more favorable for some legacy carriers.&nbsp; Lower demand necessitates equipment substitutions
from higher capacity aircraft to regional jets.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="industryregulation"></a><b><u><font size="2" face="Arial">Industry Regulation</font></u></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We operate under a certificate of public convenience and necessity issued by the Department of Transportation (&ldquo;DOT&rdquo;).&nbsp; This certificate may be altered,
amended, modified or suspended by the DOT if public convenience and necessity so require.&nbsp; The DOT has jurisdiction to prohibit certain unfair or anti-competitive practices, determine carrier fitness to serve and mandate certain conditions of carriage.&nbsp; The
DOT can bring proceedings for the enforcement of its regulations under applicable federal statutes, which proceedings may result in civil penalties, revocation of certificate authority or criminal sanctions.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We also operate under an air carrier operating certificate issued by the FAA which may be amended, modified, suspended or revoked if safety in air commerce or air
transportation and the public interest so require.&nbsp; The FAA regulates airlines, primarily in the areas of flight operations, maintenance, ground facilities, hazardous materials and goods handling and other technical matters.&nbsp; Under these regulations, we
have established, and the FAA has approved, proper cargo training and handling programs and maintenance program for the aircraft that ExpressJet operates, which provides for the ongoing maintenance of these aircraft, ranging from frequent routine inspections to major
overhauls.&nbsp; The FAA enforces its regulations by the imposition of civil penalties or revocation of certificate, which can result in adverse financial impact to our operations.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Based on conditions in the industry, or as a result of Congressional directives or statutes, the DOT and the FAA from time to time propose and adopt new regulations or
amend existing regulations, such as the air service delivery regulation currently being discussed between U.S. Congress and the DOT, which may impose additional regulatory burdens and costs on us.&nbsp; Imposition of new laws and regulations on air carriers could
increase our cost of operation or limit our operating discretion.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Aviation and Transportation Security Act of 2001 (the &ldquo;ATSA&rdquo;) federalized substantially all aspects of civil aviation security and created the
Transportation Security Administration (&ldquo;TSA&rdquo;) under the Department of Homeland Security.&nbsp; The implementation of the requirements of the ATSA and other security laws and regulations resulted in increased costs for airlines and passengers, as well as
delays and disruptions in air travel.&nbsp; The TSA issued regulations implementing the ATSA, including a requirement that we adopt an air carrier security program.&nbsp; Failure to comply with TSA rules or with our security program may result in the imposition of
substantial civil penalties.&nbsp; The law also requires that checked baggage be screened by explosives detection systems, which has required significant equipment acquisition by the government and the implementation of facility and baggage process changes.&nbsp;
Further implementation of the requirements of the ATSA and other security laws and regulations have resulted in increased costs for airlines and passengers, delays and disruptions to air travel and reduced demand.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the maintenance of our aircraft and ground equipment, we handle and use many materials that are classified as hazardous.&nbsp; The Environmental Protection Agency and
similar local agencies have jurisdiction over the handling and processing of these materials.&nbsp; We are also subject to the oversight of the Occupational Safety and Health Administration concerning employee safety and health matters.&nbsp; We are subject to the
Federal Communications Commission&rsquo;s jurisdiction regarding the use of radio frequencies. Federal law establishes maximum aircraft noise and emissions limits.&nbsp; All of our aircraft comply with currently applicable federal noise and emissions
regulations.&nbsp; Federal law generally preempts airports from imposing unreasonable local noise rules that restrict air carrier operations.&nbsp; However, under certain circumstances, airport operators may implement reasonable and nondiscriminatory local noise
abatement procedures, which could impact our ability to serve certain airports, particularly in off-peak hours.<a name="employees"></a></font></p>

<p><b><u><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></u></b></p>

<p><b><u><font size="2" face="Arial">Employees</font></u></b></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our past and continuing success depends on the ability of our employees to execute effectively on a daily basis. As of December 31, 2008, we had over 5,400 employees,
comprised of 2,125 pilots and instructor pilots, 1,022 flight attendants, 519 customer service personnel, 920 mechanics, 68 dispatchers and 749 supervisors, management and support personnel.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Labor costs are a significant component of airline expenses and can substantially impact our results.&nbsp; While there can be no assurance that our generally good labor
relations and high labor productivity will continue, a crucial component of our business strategy is the preservation of good relations with our employees, approximately 77% of whom are represented by unions.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

practices to our Director of Internal Audit and to our Corporate Compliance Officer.&nbsp; Our employees may report concerns through an employee hotline and the following email address: xjtinternalaudit@expressjet.com<i>.&nbsp;</i> Persons desiring to communicate
with the independent members of our Board of Directors may also do so through this email address.</font></p>

Exchange's corporate governance listing standards.&nbsp; In addition, our Chief Executive Officer and Chief Financial Officer have made the certifications required under Section 302 of the Sarbanes-Oxley Act, which are included as exhibits to this report.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="item1a"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Item 1A.&nbsp; Risk Factors</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our business, results of operations and financial condition may vary materially from those we anticipate, estimate or project due to risks arising primarily in five key
areas:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">our operations under the Continental CPA may no longer be profitable;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">our Corporate Aviation operation and other aviation services may affect our ability to operate profitably;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">our covenants under the amended indentures of our convertible notes and the profile of our current shareholders;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">rising costs, the global economic recession and the highly competitive nature of the airline industry; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">regulations, including listing regulation for publicly-traded companies, and other factors.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></b></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i></b> Additionally, we may encounter risks in addition to those described in this report.&nbsp; Additional risks and uncertainties not currently known to
us, or that we currently deem to be immaterial, may also adversely impair or offset our business, results of operation and financial condition.</p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></b></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i></b> <b><i><u><font size="2">Our operations under the Continental CPA may no longer be profitable.</font></u></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We amended and restated the Continental CPA on June 5, 2008.&nbsp; The amendments became effective on July 1, 2008. In contrast to the Continental CPA in effect before
the amendments, which had provided for us to earn a 10% margin on our expenses incurred flying as a regional carrier for Continental, the agreement now has fixed block hour rates, which are subject to an annual adjustment tied to a consumer price index (capped at
3.5% per annum).&nbsp; Under the Amended Continental CPA, the ceiling for the annual adjustment noted above is 3.5%; however, there is no floor; therefore, in prolonged deflationary periods, the annual adjustment can be a negative percentage. The rates under the
Amended Continental CPA are considerably lower than the pre-amendment rates and will result in lower overall revenues.&nbsp; At this time, it is difficult to quantify the overall financial impact of the changes because the pre- and post-amendment agreements are
substantially different, including with respect to the services covered.&nbsp; Our results will depend, in part, on the timing of our fleet changes and how successful we are in reducing our operating costs.&nbsp; We originally derived significant amounts of revenue
from the reimbursement, plus the 10% margin, for aircraft rent, fuel and other expenses.&nbsp; Those expenses, and the corresponding revenue, will no longer be reflected on our financial statements as they will be incurred directly by Continental.&nbsp; Moreover, the
rates we earn will be fixed and not tied to our expenses; consequently, we could be unprofitable if we do not manage our costs effectively.&nbsp; We would need to aggressively reduce managed expenses under the agreement if aircraft are removed from service and
returned to Continental.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i><u>Our charter operation and other aviation services may affect our ability to operate profitably.</u></i></b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The aircraft transitioned in 2006 from the Continental CPA and in 2008 from our Branded Flying operation to our Corporate Aviation division have been unprofitable to
date.&nbsp; Currently the aircraft deployed outside of the Continental CPA and the associated risks relate to over 12% of our fleet; however, if the Continental CPA were terminated, our fleet could be significantly reduced or these risks could extend across our
entire fleet. The risks affecting our Corporate Aviation operations include:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">

</td>

<p><u><font size="3" face="Times New Roman"></font></u></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>We remain dependent on Continental for the majority of our revenue and cash flows.</u></font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We currently operate more than 87% of our fleet (214 aircraft) under the Continental CPA and so rely heavily on the financial and operational stability of
Continental.&nbsp; The domestic airline environment in the United States continues to be extremely challenging for all carriers and Continental experienced a loss in the fourth quarter and for the full year of 2008.&nbsp; Continental has indicated that its own
business and financial results are subject to a number of risk factors, many of which are uncontrollable, including the amount of debt it carries, volatile fuel prices, delays in scheduled aircraft deliveries, its high labor and pension costs, service interruptions
at one of its hub airports, disruptions to the operations of any of its regional operators, disruptions in its computer systems, and industry conditions, including the airline pricing environment, an economic downturn in the U.S. and global economies, industry
capacity decisions, industry consolidation, terrorist attacks, regulatory matters, excessive taxation, the availability and cost of insurance, public health threats and the seasonal nature of the airline business.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We cannot predict the future impact of these factors on Continental.&nbsp; Moreover, changes in fare structures (most importantly in relation to business fares), booking
patterns, low-cost competitor growth, customers&rsquo; direct booking on the internet, volatile fuel prices, competitors emerging from bankruptcies with reduced cost structures, rumored industry consolidation and other changes in the industry cannot be predicted at
this time, but could have a material adverse effect on both Continental&rsquo;s and our financial condition, liquidity and results of operations.</font></p>

<p><i><u><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></u></i></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>Our Continental CPA could be terminated.</u></font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We currently operate 214 aircraft for Continental under the Continental CPA.&nbsp; Although Continental no longer has the unilateral right to remove aircraft from the
Continental CPA, Continental is permitted to reduce that number to a minimum of 190 aircraft after June 30, 2009. In the event that Continental exercises this right, the 190 aircraft will remain covered by the agreement through its scheduled June 30, 2015
expiration.&nbsp; After a term of seven years, the Amended Continental CPA is scheduled to expire with no renewal or extension options.&nbsp; Additionally, Continental can also terminate the agreement:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr height="17">
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">for cause, at any time without giving us notice or an opportunity to cure;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr height="17">
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">at any time upon our material breach that does not constitute cause, including our failure to complete a specified percentage of our scheduled flights, if the breach continues for 90 days after we receive notice of the
breach;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr height="17">
<td height="17" valign="top"></td>

<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">at any time, upon two business days notice, and with no opportunity to cure, if Continental reasonably and in good faith determines, using recognized standards of safety, that there is a material safety concern with our operation of any
flights under the agreement; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr height="17">

</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">at any time, without giving us notice or an opportunity to cure, if a change of control occurs as described in &ldquo;&mdash;Continental Capacity Purchase and Other Agreements.&rdquo;</font></p>
</td>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>We could lose access to our aircraft, facilities and regulatory authorizations if the Continental CPA were terminated.</u></font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We currently lease or sublease almost all of our aircraft from Continental.&nbsp; If Continental terminated the Continental CPA for cause, it would have the right to
terminate our leases and subleases for aircraft covered by the agreement at the time of termination.&nbsp; Additionally, if Continental&rsquo;s financial condition deteriorated and it filed for bankruptcy protection, it would have the ability to reject the leases or
subleases on our aircraft.&nbsp; There can be no assurance that Continental will have sufficient liquidity to fund its future operations and other financial obligations, especially in the event additional adverse factors beyond its control occur, such as declining
passenger revenue mix from global economic recessions, volatile fuel prices, terrorist attacks or adverse regulatory rulings.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Additionally, if the Continental CPA were terminated for any reason, including termination at the end of its term on June 30, 2015, we could lose access to some or
substantially all of our airport facilities and other services that Continental currently provides to us, as well as our take-off and landing slots and route authorities.&nbsp; Continental leases most of the airport facilities that we use.&nbsp; We could be required
to vacate the terminal facilities (or all facilities if the termination resulted from our material breach of the Continental CPA) that are subleased to us by Continental, and to use commercially reasonable efforts to assign to Continental or its designee any lease in
our name where we fly for Continental.&nbsp; Consequently, to offer commercial airline services in the same markets, we would have to arrange to use the same or other airport facilities, take-off or landing slots, route authorities and other regulatory authorizations
used for scheduled flights at potentially higher rates.&nbsp; We cannot provide any assurance that we would be able to gain appropriate access to airport facilities, slots or other authorizations, or would not incur a significant increase in our costs to do
so.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i><u>We may not be successful in retaining qualified personnel to maintain the current level of customer service and reliability.</u></i></font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Labor costs constitute a significant percentage of our total operating costs, and wage rates, in general, are increasing.&nbsp; To return to profitability, we reduced
our work force significantly and obtained wage and salary concessions from each of our employees that remain.&nbsp; Because of this, our employees may elect to seek other employment opportunities, thereby increasing our recruiting and training costs.&nbsp; We cannot
guarantee that we will be able to continue to find qualified personnel to fill our vacancies.&nbsp; As our workforce matures, we may not be able to cover the resulting higher wage rates if competition or other conditions do not permit us to achieve sufficient
revenues.&nbsp; Approximately 77% of our employees are covered by collective bargaining agreements.&nbsp; Deterioration in our labor relationships could significantly impact our operations and financial results.</font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></b></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i><u>Consolidations in our industry can adversely impact our current business strategy.</u></i></font></b></p>

<p><b><i><u><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></u></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There have been numerous mergers and acquisitions within the U.S airline industry since its deregulation in 1978, and there may be additional mergers and
acquisitions in the future.&nbsp; Any airline industry consolidation could substantially alter the competitive landscape and may result in changes in our business strategy.&nbsp; Although the majority of our current flying is under contractual obligations and, thus,
is insulated somewhat from the immediate impact of any change of control, consolidation involving legacy carriers in our industry could, in the long run, result in the reduction of capacity for network-feed services to be provided by the regional carriers, which
could have a material adverse effect on us.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><i><br clear="all" />
</i></font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> <b><i><u><font size="2">Amendments to the terms of the convertible notes increased our obligations and put our assets at risk.</font></u></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As a result and pursuant to the terms of the exchange offer, the Company issued 163,824,975 shares (pre-Reverse Split) of common stock in payment of the repurchase price
for the principal amount of the 4.25% convertible notes due 2023 (the &ldquo;Original 4.25% Convertible Notes due 2023&rdquo;) validly tendered.&nbsp; Following the completion of the tender offer, the Company had $68.5 million aggregate principal of its Original
4.25% Convertible Notes due 2023 remaining outstanding.&nbsp; As previously disclosed, we have unilaterally amended the indenture governing our convertible notes in order to provide improved terms and additional flexibility for the noteholders remaining after the
exchange offer, including:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">

</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">The obligations under the remaining notes are secured with a pro-rata portion (based on the portion that the remaining notes represent of the total convertible notes that were issued) of assets with an appraised value of approximately
as of December 31, 2008 of $180.4 million, including approximately $96 million in spare parts and $85 million of spare engines;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
