<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Noteholders of record on August 2, 2008, automatically began to receive the benefits of the supplemental indenture that become effective the same day.&nbsp; From August
2 forward, the notes will be referred to as the &ldquo;11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023.&rdquo;&nbsp; The terms of the 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023 could have important consequences by adversely affecting our financial condition and making it
more difficult to satisfy our obligations under the notes and our other contractual and commercial commitments.&nbsp; The amendments also increased the cash required to service the interest on the notes.&nbsp; If our business does not generate sufficient cash flow
from operations in the future, we may be required to take actions such as curtailing our business activities, reducing capital expenditures, selling assets, incurring additional debt or seeking bankruptcy protection.&nbsp; We may not be able to accomplish any of
these actions on terms acceptable to us, or at all.&nbsp; In addition, if we are unable to repay our obligations under the notes, the trustee could seek to foreclose on the assets securing the notes.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><u>A significant percentage of our common stock outstanding is held by a small number of institutional stockholders.&nbsp; These institutional stockholders may be
able to exert significant control over the election of our Board of Directors and the management of our business and their interests may differ from those of our other stockholders.&nbsp;&nbsp;</u></b></font></i></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As reported in their filings with the SEC, four large, institutional investors currently own or control a significant amount of our common stock.&nbsp; By virtue of the
number of shares they control, these&nbsp;stockholders&nbsp;may be able to significantly influence or control our management and affairs, and initiate or effect corporate transactions such as mergers, consolidation or the sale of all or substantially all of our
assets.&nbsp; The interests of these institutional investors may differ from that of other stockholders, with the result that&nbsp;the institutional investors may cause us to change our business strategy or objectives in ways that may not be viewed favorably by us,
our strategic partners or other stockholders and may lead to increased costs.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> <b><i><u><font size="2">Our common stock could be delisted from the NYSE.</font></u></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our common stock could be delisted from the NYSE if we fail to maintain the continued listing standards applicable to our Company.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<i><font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font></i>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We were notified in July 2008 from NYSE Regulation, Inc. that we were not in compliance with the NYSE $1.00 average share price continued listing standard.&nbsp; We
immediately pursued various solutions and worked closely with the NYSE to maintain our current listing.&nbsp; As of January 20, 2009, we received a letter from the NYSE stating that we have cured such non-compliance and returned to good standing for our listing at
the NYSE.&nbsp; No further adverse actions will be taken by the NYSE at this time; however, considering the current global economic recession, the volatility of the stock market and the make-up of our current stockholders, we cannot provide assurance that we will
continue to meet all the continued listing standards.&nbsp; If we do not meet the standards, we could be subject to delisting, which would constitute a default under our convertible notes and could result in the obligation to repay the notes in cash at
par.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>We may be responsible for additional taxes as a result of our tax agreement with Continental.</u></font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We have a tax agreement with Continental that provides, among other things, for our payment to Continental of all or a significant portion of the tax benefits we realize
as a result of an internal reorganization done prior to our initial public offering in 2002.&nbsp; Since that time, we have made net payments of approximately $122.5 million to Continental under the agreement and could pay Continental as much as an additional $234.6
million through 2017.&nbsp; See Item 8. &ldquo;Financial Statements and Supplementary Data &ndash; Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements &ndash; Note 10 Income Taxes&rdquo; for a detailed discussion of our income taxes and the tax agreement.&nbsp; If it were
determined, as a result of an income tax audit or examination, that a significant amount of these tax benefits should not have been available, thus requiring us to pay additional taxes, interest and penalties to one or more tax authorities, and if at that time
Continental were unable to indemnify us for these amounts as contemplated in the tax agreement, then we could be responsible for such tax payments, interest and penalties.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>We may be unable to obtain all of the parts or related support services we expect from Embraer to operate our aircraft.</u></font></i></b></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We operate a single fleet type produced by a single manufacturer; consequently, our operations could be materially adversely affected by:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Embraer&rsquo;s inability to provide sufficient parts or related support services on a timely basis-- especially in light of its announcement to cease the production of our current fleet type;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">the issuance of FAA directives restricting or prohibiting the use of Embraer regional jets or parts;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">unscheduled or unanticipated maintenance requirements; or</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">force majeure events that prevent Embraer from performing under the lease agreement.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Conversely, if we choose to operate another aircraft type in the future, for a time we will not have the maintenance expertise we have acquired with our current fleet, training costs would increase, and parts and inventory costs would
rise.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>Maintenance costs will likely increase as the average age of our fleet increases.</u></font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Similar to other air carriers in our industry, as the average age of our fleet increases, our aircraft maintenance costs will likely increase.&nbsp; We emphasize routine
maintenance in addition to the inspection of our aircraft engines and airframes at intervals required by the FAA.&nbsp; We perform line and heavy maintenance at our maintenance facilities and satellite stations located throughout the United States.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Additionally, we have a &ldquo;power-by-the-hour&rdquo; agreement with Rolls Royce to maintain the engines on our aircraft through April 2015.&nbsp; Under the agreement,
we are charged a fixed rate based on flight hours incurred during a month.&nbsp; The rates are subject to annual revisions based on specified labor and material indices.&nbsp; We also have power-by-the-hour agreements with other vendors to cover various components
and systems on our aircraft, and will continue to evaluate and implement similar agreements when the terms are favorable.&nbsp;</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; However, our average maintenance costs could increase and adversely impact our results of operations in the event that we have to address any new FAA or Embraer
maintenance directives.&nbsp; We are not aware of any such directives at this time that will adversely affect our maintenance costs.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>Reductions in insurance coverage or increases in rates could adversely impact our operations and financial results.</u></font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The terrorist attacks of 2001 led to a significant increase in insurance premiums, as well as a decrease in the coverage available to commercial air carriers. We carry
insurance for public liability, passenger liability, property damage and damage to our aircraft.&nbsp; The Homeland Security Act of 2002 currently requires the federal government to provide third party, passenger, and hull war-risk insurance coverage to commercial
air carriers through March 31, 2009.&nbsp; If any of our insurance programs terminated, the Company would likely face a material increase in the cost of war-risk insurance.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>Our cost structure may not be competitive with some of our competitors.</u></font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our costs are mainly driven by the flight schedule determined by Continental, Continental&rsquo;s own cost structure or factors that are outside our control, or in some
instances even Continental&rsquo;s control (such as aircraft rent, fuel, insurance, property taxes, etc.).&nbsp; As a significant portion of our costs are wages that are contractually agreed with our labor work groups, we may not be able to restructure our costs
effectively to compete with other carriers even though in the past we have been successful in our concessionary discussions.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>Our business is subject to extensive government regulation and we may incur additional costs to comply with such regulations.</u></font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our business is subject to extensive government regulation.&nbsp; As evidenced by the enactment of the ATSA, airlines are subject to extensive regulatory and legal
compliance requirements that can or may result in significant costs.&nbsp; The FAA and other governmental agencies such as the EPA from time to time issue directives and other regulations relating to the maintenance and operation of aircraft that require significant
expenditures.&nbsp; Some requirements cover, among other things, security measures, collision avoidance systems, potable water standards, noise abatement and other environmental matters, commuter aircraft safety and increased inspections and maintenance procedures
conducted on older aircraft.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We expect to continue incurring expenses to comply with these regulations.&nbsp; In addition, if any of these regulations caused us to cancel flights, it would result in
a reduction in our revenue.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Additional laws, regulations, taxes and airport rates and charges are proposed from time to time that could significantly increase the cost of airline operations or
reduce revenue.&nbsp; Such laws, taxes and regulations have affected all facets of our operations from security at airports, restrictions on landing, take-off, routes, restrictions on international routes (which can change suddenly depending on the current
arrangements between the United States and the foreign governments), and increases in landing fees and other airport facility charges.&nbsp; We cannot be certain that current laws or regulations, or laws or regulations enacted in the future, will not adversely affect
us.</font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i><u>We may be adversely affected by factors beyond our control, including weather conditions and the availability and cost of fuel</u></i></b>.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During periods of fog, icy conditions, storms, hurricanes or other adverse weather conditions, flights may be cancelled or significantly delayed.&nbsp; Under the Amended
Continental CPA, we are not protected against cancellations due to weather or air traffic control restrictions, which could adversely affect our operating results and our financial condition.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Additionally, in operating our aircraft for other airlines or under charter contracts we may be exposed to the volatility of fuel prices.&nbsp; Both the cost and
availability of fuel are subject to various economic and political factors and events occurring throughout the world.&nbsp; Significant changes or extended periods of high fuel cost or fuel supply disruptions could materially affect our operating results.&nbsp; Our
ability to pass on increased fuel costs through contract pricing is limited by several factors, including economic and competitive conditions.&nbsp; Additionally, under the Continental CPA, if the unavailability of fuel caused us to cancel flights, our incentive
revenue would be reduced.&nbsp; The cost and availability of adequate supplies of fuel could have a material adverse effect on our operating results and our financial condition in the future.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>Our reliance on technology could be harmful in the event of system failure.</u></font></i></b></p>

<p><u><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></u></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Like other air carriers, we rely heavily on automated systems and technology to operate our business, including flight operations and
telecommunications.&nbsp; Any disruptions in these systems due to internal failures of technology or external interruptions, such as power outages, could result in the loss of critical data and/or cancellation of flights and have an adverse effect on our results of
operations.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>Our operations and financial condition could be adversely affected as a result of an aviation accident.</u></font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An accident or incident involving one of our aircraft could involve repair or replacement of a damaged aircraft and its consequential temporary or permanent loss from
service, as well as significant potential claims of injured passengers and others.&nbsp; We are required by the DOT to carry liability insurance.&nbsp; In the event of an accident, our liability insurance may not be adequate and we may be forced to bear substantial
losses from the accident.&nbsp; Substantial claims resulting from an accident in excess of our related insurance coverage would harm operational and financial results.&nbsp; Moreover, any aircraft accident or incident, even if fully insured, could create a public
perception that we are less safe or reliable than other airlines.</font></p>

<p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman"></font></p>

<p><a name="item1b"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Item 1B.&nbsp; Unresolved Staff Comments</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We do not have any unresolved comments from the SEC&rsquo;s staff as of the date of this filing.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

ERJ-145 Family.&nbsp; Our next option exercise date is April 1, 2009.&nbsp; If we do not exercise or extend our option as of this date, 25 options will expire.&nbsp; During 2005, Continental declined the right to include any of our option aircraft in the Continental
CPA; consequently, Continental is not required to participate in the financing for any option aircraft that we acquire.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="facilities"></a><b><u><font size="2" face="Arial">Facilities</font></u></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><u>Airports</u></b></font></p>

<p><u><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></u></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We lease all of our airport passenger facilities either directly with the airport authorities or in some cases, through arrangements with Continental, on a net-rental
basis.&nbsp; Our largest operational centers are at Houston&rsquo;s George Bush Intercontinental Airport, which is approximately 155,000 square feet, with 31 gates in Terminal B, Cleveland&rsquo;s Hopkins International Airport, of which we have approximately 106,000
square feet and 12 gates in Terminal D, and Newark Liberty International Airport, where we operate out of Continental&rsquo;s Terminal A with up to 14 passenger loading bridges and 16 aircraft parking positions.&nbsp; In addition, at each of Continental's three
domestic hubs and many other locations, our passenger and baggage handling space is provided by Continental on varying terms dependent on the prevailing practice at each airport.&nbsp; If the Continental CPA were terminated, we might be required to vacate the
terminal facilities (or all facilities if the termination resulted from our material breach of the agreement) that are subleased to us by Continental, and to use commercially reasonable efforts to transfer to Continental or its designee any lease in our name.&nbsp;
See Item 7. &ldquo;Management&rsquo;s Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations &ndash; Our Business &ndash; Contract Flying &ndash; Continental CPA - Airport Facilities, Slots and Route Authorities."&nbsp; For a period of five years
following the termination of the Continental CPA, if we wanted to transfer our interests in any of our facilities used to fulfill our obligations under the agreement, Continental would need to consent to the transfer (where Continental is the sublessor) and has a
right of first refusal to acquire our interests in those facilities that we lease from parties other than Continental.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, we continue to lease approximately 54,712 square feet of terminal space including two gates at LA/Ontario International airport, as well as
approximately 11,900 square feet of terminal space, including approximately 14 gates at an additional 16 airports previously associated with our ExpressJet branded network.&nbsp; Our facilities team is aggressively working to sublease or terminate those leases, some
of which extend to 2010.&nbsp; All expenses associated with the leases were recorded in our consolidated statement of operations for the year ended December 31, 2008 after Branded Flying operations were suspended on September 2, 2008.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> <u>Corporate Offices and Other</u></b></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our Houston headquarters building is comprised of executive, administrative and operations control departments, occupying approximately 42,000 square feet of leased
space.&nbsp; We also lease a second building that consists of 18,000 square feet for executive and administrative staff and 50,000 square feet of production and warehouse space utilized by InTech.&nbsp; Additionally, we lease a 57,000 square foot training center
containing numerous simulators, training devices and corresponding training and administrative staff.&nbsp; To reduce overhead expenses, we moved a majority of our executive and administrative staff to our headquarters building and are working to sublease the
space.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> <u>Maintenance Facilities</u></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In addition to our airport passenger facilities, we currently operate seven major maintenance facilities (hangars/shops) in Houston, Cleveland, Newark, Knoxville,
Shreveport, Ontario and Richmond, as well as four satellite line maintenance facilities in other cities.&nbsp; Continental is the primary sublessor for these facilities, with the exception of the Ontario hangar and a shop and satellite maintenance station facility
located in Lake Charles.&nbsp; XJT Florida, Inc., a wholly owned subsidiary of Holdings, owns an approximately 74,000 square foot building in Miami, Florida that is leased to American Composites for use as a maintenance shop.&nbsp; Additionally, XJT Mexico, Inc., a
wholly owned subsidiary of Holdings, owns three buildings consisting of approximately 96,000 square feet of hangar space and 3,000 square feet of administrative space in Saltillo, Mexico that is leased to Saltillo Jet Center for use in its aircraft painting
business.&nbsp; We are responsible for maintenance, taxes, insurance and other facility-related expenses and services at these facilities.&nbsp;</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><b><br clear="all" />

<p><a name="item3"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Item 3.&nbsp; Legal Proceedings</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We are a defendant in various lawsuits arising in the ordinary course of our business.&nbsp; While the outcome of these lawsuits and proceedings cannot be predicted with
certainty and could have a material adverse effect on our financial position, results of operations or cash flows, we believe that the ultimate disposition of these suits will not have a material adverse effect on our financial position, results of operations or cash
flows.</font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><a name="environm"></a><b><u><font size="2" face="Arial">Environmental Proceedings</font></u></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We are and may from time to time become involved in environmental matters, including the investigation and/or remediation of environmental conditions at properties we
use or were previously used by us.&nbsp; We are not, however, currently subject to any environmental cleanup orders imposed by regulatory authorities, nor do we have any active investigations or remediation at this time.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; None.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our certificate of incorporation provides that no shares of capital stock may be voted by or at the direction of persons who are not United States citizens unless they
are registered on a separate stock record.&nbsp; Our bylaws further provide that no shares will be registered on this foreign stock record if the amount to be registered would exceed United States foreign ownership restrictions.&nbsp; United States law currently
limits the voting power in us (or any other U.S. airline) by persons who are not citizens of the United States to 25%.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In July 2005, our board of directors authorized the expenditure of up to $30 million to repurchase shares of our common stock.&nbsp; In February 2006, the board
authorized the inclusion of our 4.25% convertible notes due 2023 within the previously announced $30 million program.&nbsp; On November 4, 2008, the Board authorized an additional $5 million to be utilized under the existing program. On November 20, 2008, the Board
authorized an additional $10 million to be utilized under the program.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We did not make any purchases of stock or notes under this program during 2006.&nbsp; During 2007, we purchased 2.7 million shares of our common stock for $8.0 million
and $2.5 million of our Original 4.25% Convertible Notes at par value.&nbsp; In 2008, we purchased 4.0 million shares (Reverse Split adjusted) of our common stock, $6.5 million par value of our 4.25% convertible notes and $7.6 million par value ($4.5 million book
value) of our 11.25% convertible notes for $10.8 million leaving a current balance of $10.1 million within the program for additional purchases.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="Item6"><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Item 6.&nbsp; Selected Financial Data</font></b></a></p>



<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This selected financial data should be read together with the consolidated financial statements and related notes and Item 7.&nbsp; &ldquo;Management&rsquo;s Discussions
and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations&rdquo; included elsewhere in this report.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our current primary business is providing air transportation services utilizing our fleet of 244 aircraft.&nbsp; During 2007, we diversified our business from flying
solely for one corporate customer to flying for several, including the general public under our own brand.&nbsp; Prior to 2007, we derived substantially all of our revenues from our Continental Express operations.&nbsp; During 2008 we dramatically reshaped our
business as we suspended our Branded Flying operations and mutually terminated agreements with Delta due to record fuel prices to focus on our contractual arrangements with Continental and our Corporate Aviation division.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />

in this report is not necessarily indicative of our future results of operations, financial position and cash flows.&nbsp; For a discussion of some of the key factors that could have an adverse effect on our results of operations, financial position and cash flows,
please refer to Item 1A. &ldquo;Risk Factors."</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="682">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(1)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Revenue passenger miles are the number of scheduled miles flown by revenue passengers.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(2)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Available seat miles are the number of passenger seats available multiplied by the number of scheduled miles those seats are flown.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(3)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Passenger load factor equals revenue passenger miles divided by available seat miles.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(4)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Operating cost per available seat mile is operating costs divided by available seat miles.&nbsp; The reimbursable expenses are different under the terms of the Amended Continental CPA versus the Original Continental CPA, and therefore
costs are inconsistent with prior periods, beginning July 2008.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(5)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Block hours are the hours from gate departure to gate arrival.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(6)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Operating cost per block hour is operating costs divided by block hours.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(7)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Under the Amended Continental CPA, Continental is responsible for the cost of providing fuel for all flights and, therefore, effective July 1, 2008, fuel expense is no longer included in our statements of operations for our Continental
Express flying.&nbsp; Prior to July 1, 2008 under our fuel purchase agreement with Continental, fuel and fuel tax expense were reconciled to the lower of the actual costs or the agreed-upon caps.&nbsp; Since 2003, our caps on fuel and fuel taxes, for aircraft
operating under the Continental CPA, have been 66.0 cents and 5.2 cents per gallon, respectively.&nbsp; In 2007, our fuel activity included purchases to support our various business platforms outside of the Continental CPA.&nbsp; These purchases were executed through
an agreement with an independent third party at an average price per gallon of $2.43, which represents 16.7% of our total fuel consumption for 2007.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(8)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Average daily utilization of each aircraft is the average number of block hours per day that an aircraft in revenue service is operated.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p><a name="item7"></a><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Item 7.&nbsp; Management's Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The information contained in this section has been derived from, is provided as a supplement to, and should be read in conjunction with our consolidated financial
statements and the accompanying notes thereto contained in &ldquo;Item 8.&nbsp; Financial Statements and Supplementary Data&rdquo; of this report.&nbsp; This section contains forward-looking statements that involve risks and uncertainties.&nbsp; Our actual results
may differ materially from those expressed or implied in these forward-looking statements as a result of various factors, including those described in &ldquo;Forward-Looking Statements&rdquo; and in Item 1A.&nbsp; &ldquo;Risk Factors.&rdquo;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

and our current business environment.&nbsp; MD&amp;A is provided as a supplement to&mdash;and should be read in conjunction with&mdash;our consolidated financial statements and the accompanying notes thereto contained in "Item&nbsp;8.&nbsp; Financial Statements and
Supplementary Data" of this report. This overview summarizes MD&amp;A, which includes the following sections:</font></p>

<p><b><u><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></u></b></p>

<p><a name="ourbusiness"></a><b><u><font size="2" face="Arial">Our Business</font></u></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> <u>General</u></b></p>

<p><u><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></u></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> <font size="2">Holdings is engaged in the business of moving people.&nbsp; Our principal asset is all of the issued and outstanding shares of stock of XJT
Holdings, Inc., the sole stockholder of ExpressJet Airlines, Inc. (referred to in this report as &ldquo;Airlines&rdquo; and, together with Holdings, as &ldquo;ExpressJet&rdquo;, &ldquo;we&rdquo; or &ldquo;us&rdquo;).&nbsp; Airlines currently operates a fleet of 244
aircraft.&nbsp; <font color="black">As of December 31, 2008, our fleet was assigned as follows:&nbsp;</font></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">214 aircraft for Continental as Continental Express pursuant to the Continental CPA; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">30 aircraft in our Corporate Aviation division, which is dedicated to charter contracts and ad-hoc charter service.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> Our primary business is flying 244 aircraft under contractual arrangements for network carriers or entities desiring cost-effective and fully
customizable group travel.&nbsp; <font color="black">During 2008 we dramatically reshaped our business in order to adapt to the unprecedented high fuel costs, recessions in the global economy, air-travel capacity cuts worldwide, and other uncertainties facing the
regional airlines.&nbsp; We completed most of our transition to the contractually-arranged flying during the fourth quarter ending December 31, 2008, under the terms of the Amended Continental CPA which provides for lower block hour rates and various costs, primarily
fuel and aircraft rent, are no longer reimbursable.&nbsp; Additionally, we strengthened our balance sheet through the completion of the refinancing of our convertible debt, reducing the debt from $134.7 million as of December 31, 2007, to $60.8 million as of December
31, 2008.&nbsp; We have stabilized the use of operating cash, as results of the termination of our Branded Flying operations.</font> &nbsp; Furthermore, we mutually agreed with Delta to terminate the Delta CPA and the Delta Prorate effective September 2, 2008.&nbsp;
As a result of the Amended Continental CPA, the cessation of Branded Flying and our restructuring efforts, the results of operations for fiscal 2008 are not comparable with prior periods.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We also provide aviation services, such as ground-handling at airport locations across the United States, as well as aircraft repair, overhaul, interior
refurbishments and paint, through Services, our wholly owned subsidiary, and a majority owned subsidiary, Saltillo.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Holdings was incorporated in Delaware in August 1996.&nbsp; Airlines is one of the largest regional airlines in the world, based on 2008 available seat miles, number of
regional jets and passengers transported.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We compete with a number of regional airlines for the service we provide to other airlines.&nbsp; We believe that our continuing success depends on our ability to
provide our charter customers and Continental outstanding operational performance and exceptional customer service through our commitment to detail, quick responses and follow-through.&nbsp; Our ability to do this depends on our over 5,400 employees executing
effectively on a daily basis.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our goal is to use our assets, including our operational and financial strength and the strong commitment of management and employees, to continuously move people
cost-effectively and efficiently for our clients, improve our competitive position and provide value to our stockholders.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><u>Liquidity</u></b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="#777777" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> With the significant savings provided to Continental under the Amended Continental CPA, aircraft withdrawals, dramatically lower utilization, the
global economic recession and the difficulties in obtaining any financing in the current banking environment, we believe that cost savings and cash preservation are crucial to sustain our liquidity and meet our financial obligations throughout 2009.&nbsp; In January
2008, we purchased $65 million (par value) of auction rate securities (&ldquo;ARS&rdquo;).&nbsp; Since that time these auctions have been failing and accordingly, we have been unable to sell these securities and convert them to cash due to the general illiquidity in
the ARS market.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008 the fair value of these securities was $41.4 million.&nbsp; Additional cost savings initiatives are essential at this time to maintain an appropriate operating margin and preserve our cash.&nbsp; These include,
individually or in combination, if required:</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">continue to measure and deliver a full year of benefits from prior wage and benefit concessions from all of our employees;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">evaluate necessary reduction-in-force to match reduction-in-capacity;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">collaborate with third-party vendor to cut supply costs;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">manage working capital effectively (i.e., accounts payable, accounts receivable, and inventory);</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>

</td>
</tr>

<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">sell unencumbered assets, tangible or intangible, or subleasing the aircraft we lease from Continental; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">manage capital expenditures to only those required by law or operational necessities.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="#777777" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> We believe that our existing liquidity and projected 2009 cash flows, including the incremental sources of liquidity described above will be
sufficient to fund current operations and our financial obligations through December 31, 2009.&nbsp; However, as noted in Item 1A. &ldquo;Risk Factors&rdquo;, factors outside of our control may dictate that we alter our current plans and expectations and could have a
material adverse impact on our ability to sustain operations over the long term.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><u>Our Business Segments</u></b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; For the year ended December 31, 2008 and prior, <font color="black">ExpressJet had three reportable segments which are the basis of our internal financial
reporting:&nbsp; Contract Flying, Branded Flying and Aviation Services.</font></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Contract Flying includes our Corporate Aviation division and our capacity purchase agreements with Continental and Delta.&nbsp; Under Contract Flying,
revenues are contractually determined, eliminating our exposure to fluctuations in fuel prices, fare competition and passenger volumes.&nbsp; Under these arrangements, our partners bear the revenue risk and cost of marketing, distributing and selling seats directly
to passengers on our aircraft while we are responsible for the operation and maintenance of the aircraft.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Branded Flying includes operations under the ExpressJet brand and the Delta Prorate.&nbsp; Revenues for this flying are derived from passengers flying on
scheduled air service.&nbsp; We are responsible for local market pricing, scheduling and revenue management, and the operation and maintenance of the aircraft.&nbsp; Our flying under the Delta Prorate provides us with a prorated portion of the airfare plus an
incentive for passengers connecting onto Delta's network.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aviation Services includes our ground-handling services pursuant to contracts with Continental and other airlines at airport locations across the United
States, as well as those performed by Services.&nbsp; These entities provide composite, sheet metal, paint, interior (including seat refurbishment) and thrust reverser repairs throughout our five facilities in the United States and Mexico.&nbsp;</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> <b><u>Our Objective</u></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our goal is to use our assets and capabilities, including reliable operation performance, brand, financial strength, distribution system, and a strong commitment by our
management and employees to achieve long-term sustainable growth. Our plans for sustainable growth include the following:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr height="17">
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><b><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></b></p>
</td>

<p align="right"><b><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></b></p>
</td>

</td>

</td>

<p align="right"><b><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></b></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Delivering the best products and services to a diversified base of customers.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

</td>

<p align="right"><b><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></b></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Establishing a winning network of partners and develop ways to expand these relationships.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr height="17">
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><b><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></b></p>
</td>

<p align="right"><b><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></b></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Maximizing the return to our stockholders while being mindful of our overall responsibilities to all stakeholders<font color="#777777">.</font></font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Contract Flying &ndash; Continental CPA</i></b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i><u>General</u>.</i></b>&nbsp; A significant portion of our revenue and cash flows is attributable to the Continental CPA.&nbsp; Under the Continental CPA, Airlines
operates flights on behalf of Continental as Continental Express.&nbsp; Continental controls and is responsible for scheduling, pricing and managing seat inventories and is entitled to all revenue associated with the operation of the aircraft.&nbsp; We also have
various other agreements with Continental that govern our relationship.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Under the Continental CPA, all marketing-related costs normally associated with operating an airline are borne by Continental.&nbsp; These costs include:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">reservations and
sales;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">commissions;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">advertising;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">revenue accounting;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">fare and tariff filings; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">food and beverage service.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> <b><i><u><font size="2">2008 Amended Continental CPA (&ldquo;Amended Continental CPA&rdquo;)</font></u></i></b><font size="2">.&nbsp; Prior to July 1,
2008, Airlines was entitled to receive payment for each block hour that Continental scheduled it to fly pursuant to the terms of the Continental CPA.&nbsp; Payment was based on a formula designed to provide Airlines with a target operating margin of 10% before taking
into account variations in certain costs and expenses that were generally within our control.&nbsp; We had exposure for most labor costs and some maintenance and general administrative expenses if actual costs were higher than those budgeted in our block hour
rates.&nbsp; For the first six months of 2008, we recognized revenues using 2007 block hour rates, pursuant to our agreement with Continental reached in June 2008.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; At such time, we also reached an agreement with Continental to amend the existing Continental CPA.&nbsp; The Amended Continental CPA, which became effective July 1,
2008, allows us to continue flying, at minimum, 205 aircraft for Continental for seven years while providing Continental the right after one year to reduce the number of aircraft to a minimum of 190.&nbsp; The Amended Continental CPA significantly reduces
Continental&rsquo;s governance rights under the original agreement, including easing change-in-control limitations on ExpressJet, reducing restrictions on our flying into Continental&rsquo;s hub airports, and removing the most-favored-nation clause, allowing us the
option to fly for other carriers and to consider other strategic alternatives.&nbsp; The Amended Continental CPA also removes Continental&rsquo;s ability to terminate the agreement without cause.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Amended Continental CPA provides payments to us at a pre-determined rate based on block hours flown and reimburses us for various pass-through expenses including
passenger liability insurance, hull insurance, war risk insurance, landing fees and substantially all regional jet engine expenses under current long-term third-party contracts with no margin or mark-up.&nbsp; Under the Amended Continental CPA, Continental is
responsible for the cost of providing fuel for all flights and for paying aircraft rent for all aircraft covered by the Amended Continental CPA and, therefore, these items are not included in our consolidated statements of operations for periods subsequent to July 1,
2008.&nbsp; The fixed block hour rates are considerably lower than the rates under the original agreement and will be subject to annual escalations tied to a consumer price index (capped at 3.5%) at each anniversary date, July 1.&nbsp; During 2008, we returned
pursuant to our rights under the Amended Continental CPA, we returned 30 aircraft with Continental bearing the expense related to the aircraft following their return.&nbsp; <font color="black">We will continue to operate at least 205 aircraft for Continental through
June 30, 2009.&nbsp; Beginning on July 1, 2009, Continental can remove up to 15 aircraft making the new minimum aircraft requirement under the agreement 190.&nbsp; Therefore we will continue to focus on aggressively managing</font> costs in response to the Amended
Continental CPA and the economic difficulties facing the entire airline industry. <font color="black">&nbsp;</font></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In September 2008, we agreed with Continental on the first amendment to the Amended Continental CPA in order to compensate us for our fixed costs, considered in the
calculation of the pre-determined block hour rates, that cannot be reduced as a result of the unanticipated reduction in aircraft utilization by Continental&rsquo;s scheduling. We also agreed that if Continental, beginning in year two, increases its aircraft
utilization above a pre-determined threshold, then it may receive discounts on the agreed, pre-determined block hour rates.&nbsp; For the last six months of 2008, we recognized an additional $3.4 million in contract revenues as compensation for shortfalls in aircraft
utilization.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In December 2008, we agreed with Continental on the second amendment to the Amended Continental CPA in order to clarify certain issues related to our revenue
recognition, the fuel efficiency program in place in connection with the Amended Continental CPA and depreciation related to the aircraft we operate for Continental and excess inventory related thereto.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Concurrently with the execution of the Amended Continental CPA, we entered into a settlement agreement with Continental to release the parties&rsquo; claims relating to
certain identified payments under the Original Continental CPA, including disputes previously disclosed as possible matters for arbitration.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i><u>Prior Years&rsquo; Settlements of the Continental CPA.</u></i></b>&nbsp; Airlines was entitled to receive payment for each block hour that Continental scheduled
it to fly.&nbsp; Payment was based on a formula designed to provide Airlines with a target operating margin before taking into account variations in certain costs and expenses that were generally within our control.&nbsp; We had exposure for most labor costs and some
maintenance and general administrative expenses if actual costs were higher than those budgeted in our block hour rates.&nbsp; Prior years&rsquo; payment methodologies are described in the following paragraphs.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b>2005-2007.</b>&nbsp; As part of the 2005 rate negotiation, we agreed to cap Airlines&rsquo; prevailing margin at 10.0% in an attempt to ensure the long-term stability
of the Continental CPA.&nbsp; Airlines also began including previously unreconciled costs, as discussed above, within the margin band, although it was not reimbursed if these costs are higher and cause its prevailing margin to fall below the 8.5% margin floor.&nbsp;
Airlines remained entitled to receive incentive payments from Continental if its rate of controllable cancellations was lower than its historical benchmark, but was no longer required to pay Continental a penalty for controllable cancellations unless the rate rises
above 0.5%.&nbsp; Airlines continued to receive a small per-passenger fee and incentive payments for certain on-time departure and baggage handling performance.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

Continental CPA from January 1, 2005 to June 30, 2008.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2007, the fully reconciled costs and costs within the margin band under the Continental CPA represented approximately 59% and 40% of operating costs associated with
Continental CPA flying, respectively, in addition to 1% of costs related to the Continental CPA which could not be included in either reimbursable grouping such as certain labor and arbitration costs.&nbsp; In 2006, the fully reconciled costs and costs within the
margin band under the Continental CPA represented approximately 63% and 35% of operating costs associated with Continental CPA flying, respectively.&nbsp; The remaining 2% of operating costs in 2006 were incurred outside of the Continental CPA in order to support our
diversification strategies for the 69 aircraft released from the Continental CPA as well as the administrative operations we assumed from Continental in 2007.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>

the prevailing margin to be greater than 10.0%.&nbsp; However, if the differences cause the prevailing margin to be less than 8.5%, they remain unreconciled.&nbsp; These costs are:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> 2007 Arbitration<i>.</i></b>&nbsp; In 2006, Continental challenged our interpretation of the Continental CPA and sought to impose rates for 2007 that we
believed were inconsistent with the methodology established in the agreement.&nbsp; We were unable to agree on the 2007 rates and, in accordance with the terms of the Continental CPA, we submitted our dispute to binding arbitration.&nbsp; The arbitration panel
determined that the annual 2007 budgeted rates originally presented by Airlines should be reduced in the aggregate by $14.2 million (or less than 1.0% of our total Continental CPA operating revenue), which included the 10% target operating margin.&nbsp; Although we
believe our original rates were appropriate, we were pleased with the panel&rsquo;s decision.&nbsp; The 2007 scheduled block hour rates were finalized in October 2007, and w<font color="black">e recorded our passenger revenue under the Continental CPA using the block
hour rates determined by the panel for all of 2007.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>Scope of Agreement.</u></font></i></b>&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, the Amended Continental CPA covered 214 of Airlines&rsquo; existing fleet of 244
aircraft.&nbsp; Under the agreement, Continental is obligated to have a minimum of 205 aircraft covered under the Amended Continental CPA through June 30, 2009.&nbsp; Thereafter, the agreement calls for a minimum of 190 aircraft.&nbsp; The agreement permits us to fly
under our own code or on behalf of other airlines but prohibits our flying in certain markets under our own branded service.&nbsp; The Amended Continental CPA states that:</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">at Continental&rsquo;s hubs, we may not fly scheduled service under our own brand;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">at Continental&rsquo;s hubs, we are permitted to operate our charter service and fly on behalf of other airlines; and</font></p>
</td>

<tr>

<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
