</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our license from Continental to use the Continental Express name and other trademarks is non-exclusive.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Amended Continental CPA has a seven year term that is scheduled to expire on June 30, 2015.&nbsp; Continental does not have the ability to terminate the agreement
without cause prior to the termination date and cannot reduce the number of aircraft covered under the agreement below 190 aircraft.&nbsp; However, the Amended Continental CPA may cover less than 190 aircraft if there is an expiration of a Covered Aircraft head lease
and there are no fifty-seat replacement aircraft (among the original 274 aircraft) being stored on behalf of Continental.&nbsp; If, at any time prior to the end of the Amended Continental CPA term, Continental proposes to engage any third party to operate one of the
original 274 aircraft, we shall have the right of first opportunity to operate that aircraft.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; So long as scheduled flights under the Continental CPA represent at least 50% of all our scheduled flights, or at least 200 of our aircraft are covered by the agreement,
we are required to allocate our crews, maintenance personnel, facilities and other resources on a priority basis to scheduled flights under the agreement above all of our other flights and aircraft.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i><u>Aircraft Financing.</u></i></font></b>&nbsp; Airlines currently leases or subleases all of its existing aircraft from Continental.&nbsp; Under the Continental
CPA, Continental is required to purchase or lease from Embraer or its designee aircraft operated under the agreement, participate in the financing and to lease or sublease these aircraft to us.&nbsp; Under the Amended Continental CPA, Continental pays for the
aircraft rent for all aircraft covered by the Amended Continental CPA directly and therefore, we will not include this expense for Covered Aircraft in our statement of operations beginning July 1, 2008.&nbsp; Aircraft withdrawn from the Continental CPA become
&ldquo;Uncovered Aircraft&rdquo; as defined in the agreement.&nbsp;</p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Prior to the Amended Continental CPA, we were subleasing 69 Uncovered Aircraft from Continental.&nbsp; As part of the amendment, we returned 39 aircraft to Continental
and continue to sublease 30 aircraft from Continental at substantially reduced rental rates.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We have the option to purchase up to an additional 50 Embraer ERJ-145XR aircraft.&nbsp; Our next option exercise date is April 1, 2009.&nbsp; If we do not exercise or
extend our option as of this date, 25 options will expire.&nbsp; These aircraft would be Uncovered Aircraft since Continental has declined to include them under the Continental CPA.&nbsp; These options may be exercised for other types of aircraft within the ERJ-145
line of aircraft, which include the ERJ-135 and ERJ-145.&nbsp; We would need to finance our acquisition of these aircraft independently.&nbsp; Continental does not have any obligation to finance, arrange to finance or participate in the financing of any aircraft
acquired for operations outside the Continental CPA.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We do not have the right to retain any aircraft removed from the Amended Continental CPA for use in our other operations if (i) they are removed by Continental as the
result of its termination of the agreement for cause, (ii) we have already retained 150 aircraft, including the 30 being retained at reduced rent, or (iii) they are among aircraft owned by Continental, currently 18 aircraft.&nbsp; In all other events, we can elect to
retain any of the aircraft withdrawn from the Amended Continental CPA, most likely upon termination of the agreement, either at the end of seven years or upon early termination of the aircraft lease.&nbsp; In certain circumstances, in order to retain the aircraft we
will have to provide Continental with a full release from the head lease for such aircraft.&nbsp; Depending on the type of termination, there are procedures for notice and time for us to elect how many aircraft we will retain (with Continental selecting the
individual aircraft and engines), wind-down schedules of differing lengths, and maintenance reimbursements.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i><u>Airport Facilities, Slots and Route Authorities</u></i><u>.</u></font></b>&nbsp; Most of the airport facilities that Airlines uses in its Continental Express
operation are leased from airport authorities by Continental.&nbsp; Under Airlines&rsquo; master facility and ground handling agreement with Continental, Airlines is entitled to use these facilities to fulfill its obligations under the Continental CPA.&nbsp; However,
it is not permitted to use airport terminal facilities leased by Continental to service other carriers or operate flights under its own code without Continental&rsquo;s approval.&nbsp; Furthermore, we must use those facilities that are non-terminal facilities on a
priority basis to support the scheduled flights that Airlines flies on behalf of Continental so long as those flights constitute at least 50% of our total scheduled flights or at least 200 of our aircraft are covered by the Continental CPA.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Under the Continental CPA, all terminal facility rent at Continental-managed airports is borne by Continental.&nbsp; At locations Airlines manages, rent is allocated
between Continental and Airlines based on the number of each carrier&rsquo;s respective passengers.&nbsp; We are currently in the process of transitioning the station management of all stations under the Continental CPA to Continental.&nbsp; It is anticipated that
this transition will be complete by March 31, 2009.&nbsp; Under these scenarios, we may continue to provide ground handling and support services under an industry-standard ground handling agreement; however, Continental will be responsible for the station&rsquo;s
fixed expenses.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Continental is generally responsible for all capital and start-up costs for airport terminal facilities at its hub airports and at any other facilities where it elects
to provide ground handling services to Airlines.&nbsp; If Continental elects to provide ground handling services at any facility where Airlines previously did so, Continental is required to reimburse Airlines at the net book value for all fixtures and other
unremovable capitalized items Airlines funded at that facility.&nbsp; We are generally responsible for capital and start-up costs associated with airport terminal facilities where Airlines flies and any non-terminal facilities not regularly used by Continental.&nbsp;
If Airlines exits a market at the direction of Continental (and we do not re-enter that market within six months flying under our own code or that of an airline other than Continental), Continental will reimburse us for certain book and severance losses incurred in
connection with the closure of the related facility. If the Continental CPA is terminated, we may be required to vacate the terminal facilities (or all facilities if the termination results from our material breach of the agreement) that are subleased to Airlines by
Continental, and to use commercially reasonable efforts to assign to Continental or its designee any of the facility leases in our name.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i><u>Ground Handling.</u></i></font></b><i></i>&nbsp; Airlines provides ground handling and other support services, including baggage handling, station operations,
ticketing, gate access and other passenger, aircraft and traffic servicing functions for Continental at several of our airport locations.&nbsp; In exchange, Continental pays us an amount equal to Airlines&rsquo; incremental cost for providing these services.&nbsp;
Continental provides the same services for Airlines at its stations, including its hub airports.&nbsp; The cost for these services is based on the number of scheduled aircraft and the rates stipulated in the Continental CPA.&nbsp; Effective January 1, 2007, we began
providing ground handling and other support services at fixed rates for other Continental Airlines regional service providers including Republic and Colgan that operate under the Continental Express banner at 15 Continental/Continental Express stations.&nbsp;
Additionally, during 2008, Continental began transitioning our ground handling services at all of their airport locations to an all Continental managed program, with us providing specific ground handling services at a majority of these stations under an
industry-standard ground handling agreement at fixed rates, outside of the Continental CPA. These services will be reflected in our Aviation Services line of business.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i><u>Most Favored Nations.</u></i></font></b>&nbsp; As part of the Amended Continental CPA, the most favored nations clause was removed.&nbsp; We are free to
negotiate capacity purchase agreements with other airlines without any impact to our Continental CPA.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i><u>Change of Control.</u></i></b>&nbsp; If we experience a change of control without Continental&rsquo;s consent, Continental can terminate the Amended Continental
CPA for breach.&nbsp; Under the agreement, a change of control of our Branded Flying is defined as:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">our merger or consolidation with a Major Network Carrier other than Continental, which is defined as Alaska Airlines, American Airlines, Delta, Southwest Airlines, United and US Airways (or their successors)</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">the acquisition by a Major Network Carrier or any other entity, or group of entities acting in concert with a Major Network Carrier, other than Continental and its subsidiaries, of more than 25% of our capital stock or voting
rights;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">our acquisition of 25% or more of the capital stock of a Major Network Carrier (other than Continental and its successors and any subsidiaries);</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">our acquisition of all or substantially all airline assets of a Major Network Carrier;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">the sale or other disposition of all or substantially all of our airline assets to a Major Network Carrier other than Continental;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">our entering into definitive agreements relating to the foregoing matters.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i><u>Labor Disruption.</u></i></b>&nbsp; Upon the occurrence of a union-authorized labor strike, the Continental CPA provides that:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Airlines will be compensated only for the flights it completes;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">on each of the 2nd, 15th, 30th, 45th, 60th and 75th days of the strike, Continental will be entitled to terminate Airlines&rsquo; leases or subleases for, and take immediate possession of, up to 20 of Airlines&rsquo; aircraft covered by
the agreement, up to a maximum of 120 aircraft if the strike extends to the 75th day;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">we will be required to provide to Continental or its designee, for the duration of the strike and 180&nbsp;days thereafter, at market rates, first-priority access to all of our flight simulators, hangars, training and other facilities
and inventory to the extent necessary to enable Continental or their designee to operate any aircraft of which Continental takes possession as a result of the strike;&nbsp;and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">if the strike results in our failure to complete at least 75% of our scheduled flights for three consecutive days, Continental is entitled to terminate the agreement for breach.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In addition, a labor disruption other than a union-authorized strike may cause us to be in material breach of the Continental CPA.&nbsp; Under the agreement, whenever
Airlines fails to complete at least 90% of its aggregate scheduled flights (based on available seat miles) in three consecutive calendar months or at least 75% of its aggregate scheduled flights (based on available seat miles) in any 45-day period (in each case,
excluding flights cancelled due to union-authorized labor strikes, weather, air traffic control or non-carrier specific airworthiness directives or regulatory orders), we will be deemed to be in material breach of the agreement.&nbsp; In addition, if we have a
controllable completion factor for any two consecutive months of 97.5% or below, or a controllable on-time departure rate for any 60 consecutive days of 82.5% or below, we will be in material breach of the agreement.&nbsp; A labor disruption other than a
union-authorized strike could cause Airlines to fail to meet these operational requirements and, as a result, cause us to be in material breach of the agreement.&nbsp; See further discussions below regarding remedies for breach of the agreement by either Continental
or us.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i><u>Term and Termination of Agreement and Remedies for Breach</u></i><u>.</u></b>&nbsp; The Continental CPA is scheduled to terminate on June 30, 2015.&nbsp;
Continental may terminate the agreement for cause without notice.&nbsp; &ldquo;Cause&rdquo; is defined as:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">our bankruptcy;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">suspension or revocation of Airlines&rsquo; authority to operate as a scheduled airline;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">cessation of Airlines&rsquo; operations as a scheduled airline, other than as a result of a union-authorized labor strike or any temporary cessation not to exceed 14&nbsp;days;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">a union-authorized labor strike that continues for 90 days; or</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">our intentional or willful material breach that substantially deprives Continental of the benefits of the agreement, which is not cured within 90 days of notice of the breach.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Continental may also terminate the agreement at any time upon our material breach that does not constitute cause, but continues uncured for 90&nbsp;days after we receive
notice of the breach.&nbsp; In addition, Continental may terminate the agreement immediately without notice or giving us an opportunity to cure if it makes a reasonable and good faith determination, using recognized standards of safety, that there is a material
safety concern with our operation of any flights under the Continental CPA.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; If Continental materially breaches the agreement and fails to cure the breach within 60&nbsp;days after we notify it of the breach, we will be entitled to obtain our
payments directly from an airline clearing house from the 60th day for the duration of the default.&nbsp; In addition, Continental and we are each entitled to seek damages in arbitration and to reach equitable remedies.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i><u>Disposition of Aircraft upon Early Termination.</u></i></font></b>&nbsp; If Continental terminates the Continental CPA for cause or breach, it will also have
the right at that time to terminate Airlines&rsquo; leases or subleases for aircraft covered by the agreement and take possession of these aircraft.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i><u>Amendment of Embraer and Rolls Royce Contracts.</u></i></font></b>&nbsp; We are prohibited, without Continental&rsquo;s consent, from amending Airlines&rsquo;
aircraft purchase agreements with Embraer for the current 274 aircraft to change the pricing, financing or leasing arrangements, or to make any other changes that may be expected to adversely affect Continental&rsquo;s rights under the Continental CPA or our ability
to perform our obligations under the agreement.&nbsp; We have also agreed to acquire Continental&rsquo;s consent for any amendment of Airlines&rsquo; Embraer aircraft purchase agreements that reduce the financing or other obligations of Continental, provided that the
amendment does not increase Airlines&rsquo; obligations under these agreements.&nbsp; We are also prohibited, without Continental&rsquo;s consent, from amending our power-by-the-hour agreement with Rolls Royce Corporation (&ldquo;Rolls Royce&rdquo;) in any manner
that adversely affects Continental&rsquo;s or our engine maintenance costs for the aircraft subject to the Continental CPA.&nbsp;</p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><b><br clear="all" />
</b></font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i><u>Indemnification</u></i></font></b><u>.</u>&nbsp; In general, we have agreed to indemnify Continental and it has agreed to indemnify us for any damages caused by
any breach of our respective obligations under the Continental CPA or caused by our respective actions or inactions under the agreement.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i><u>Other Agreements with Continental.</u></i></b>&nbsp; Prior to 2007, under an administrative services agreement, Continental provided us with services such as
information technology support, transaction processing, insurance and risk management, treasury administrative services, corporate real estate and environmental affairs.&nbsp; In 2007, Continental stopped providing these services and, as a result, we transitioned
most information technology support, general ledger, accounts payable, payroll, and treasury administrative services from them to begin performing them independently.&nbsp; Airlines also has a fuel purchasing agreement with Continental, under which Continental
manages all of Airlines&rsquo; fuel purchasing requirements under the Continental CPA.&nbsp; Under the Amended Continental CPA, Continental no longer charges us for these services.&nbsp; Currently, our administrative services agreement with Continental is limited to
technology associated with the Continental infrastructure, minimal HR support related to some employee travel benefits and real estate services as necessary to support our Continental Express flying.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In addition, we have a tax agreement with Continental that provides, among other things, for our payment of all or a significant portion of the tax benefits we realize
as a result of an internal reorganization performed before our initial public offering in 2002.&nbsp; Since our initial public offering, we have made net payments of approximately $122.5 million to Continental under the tax agreement and could pay Continental as much
as an additional $234.6 million through 2017.&nbsp; See Item 8.&nbsp; "Financial Statements and Supplementary Data &ndash; Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements &ndash; Note 10 &ndash; Income Taxes" for a detailed discussion of our income taxes and our tax
agreement with Continental.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Contract Flying &ndash; Delta CPA</font></i></b></p>

<p><i><u><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></u></i></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During 2008, we averaged over 35 daily departures and offered scheduled passenger service to over 20 destinations in North America.&nbsp; We generated $43.8 million of
revenue from January through August 2008.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Delta CPA was scheduled to end on the second anniversary of each aircraft&rsquo;s in-service date (June 2009); however, Delta and ExpressJet mutually agreed in July
2008 to terminate this agreement effective September 2, 2008.&nbsp; Delta agreed to compensate us in August 2008 for costs incurred as a result of the early termination.&nbsp; On October 2, 2008, we transitioned the 10 aircraft previously operating within the Delta
CPA back to our continuing operations.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> <b><i>Contract Flying &ndash; Corporate Aviation</i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> We expanded our Corporate Aviation division to 30 aircraft in 2008.&nbsp; These aircraft are now dedicated to existing and new long-term agreements
and ad-hoc charter service arrangements.&nbsp; Our Corporate Aviation division continues to focus on corporate shuttles, entertainment / sports, and government businesses.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, our Corporate Aviation division has contracted with seven
customers with long-term agreements spanning the next 12 months<b>.</b>&nbsp; Certain Corporate Aviation customers typically prepay deposits for flights based on a percentage of estimated charges to be incurred.&nbsp; These prepayments are held in escrow and recorded
as restricted cash and deferred revenue until the flights are completed.&nbsp; At that time we recognize the associated revenue and release the funds from escrow into our cash account.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Corporate Aviation&rsquo;s goal is to provide group travelers a comfortable, cost-effective and fully customizable travel experience that is unmatched by our
competitors.&nbsp; Additionally, our objective is to make jet charter the ultimate and most satisfying solution to getting people where they need to be.&nbsp; We are providing such travel solutions to corporations, including other air carriers from time to time,
collegiate athletic departments, sports franchises, government entities, hospitality companies and others.&nbsp; Our pricing structure is based on a contracted fee plus reconciliation payments for uncontrollable costs (including items such as fuel and deicing) for
the full amount from which actual costs differ from estimates.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The aircraft are flown under Airlines&rsquo; operating certificate issued by the FAA.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We understand that every group travel situation is different.&nbsp; Therefore, we have reconfigured our aircraft and are currently offering two different
seat-configurations on our Corporate Aviation division fleet.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Our 41-seat passenger jet provides additional space for the customer.&nbsp; The seats in this configuration provide a 38-inch pitch, which is equivalent to a first class seat in a Boeing 737-800.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Our 50-seat passenger jet allows for larger groups, which helps maximize travel efficiency.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All of our seats are leather, memory foam cushioned seats and include XM Satellite Radio with over 100 channels of audio entertainment.&nbsp; In addition to our basic
amenities (such as providing blankets to each passenger and standard catering) customized flight service options give customers an opportunity to create a unique flight experience.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We generated $39.8 million in revenue as of December 31, 2008, and anticipate that revenues will continue to grow in this division as we continue to establish long-term
relationships which should result in greater predictability in this operation.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Branded Flying</i></b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i><u>ExpressJet</u></i></b> <b><i><u>Brand &amp; Delta Prorate.</u></i></b>&nbsp; Our year ended December 31, 2008 was one of transition.&nbsp; During the year we
dramatically reshaped our business in order to adapt to the unprecedented high fuel costs and other challenges facing the industry.&nbsp; As part of the transition, we suspended our Branded Flying operations.&nbsp; Furthermore, we mutually agreed with Delta to
terminate the Delta Prorate effective September 2, 2008.&nbsp; In connection with these capacity reductions and the transition of 39 aircraft back to Continental, we incurred total special charges of $22.4 million, including aircraft ($2.1 million), employee
reductions ($19.2 million) and certain other charges ($1.1 million).&nbsp; These amounts were offset by $18 million related to terminations payments and adjustments to our air traffic liability due to the cessation of Branded Flying.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aviation Services</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aviation Services includes our ground-handling services pursuant to our contracts with Continental and other airlines at airport locations across the United States, as
well as Services.&nbsp; We will continue to leverage our operational expertise developed from this business segment to cost-effectively serve our current customers and attract new customers.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><u>Our 2009 Outlook</u></b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>General</i></b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Many factors could materially affect our results of operations; 2009 will be a challenging year for us.&nbsp; Among the most significant factors outside our control are
economic conditions, possible industry consolidation and further capacity cuts from major network carriers.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The U.S. economy is in a recession.&nbsp; The airline industry is highly cyclical, and the growth in demand for air travel is correlated to the growth in the U.S. and
global economies.&nbsp; A prolonged economic recession and further capacity cuts from network carriers could have an adverse effect on our results of operations and financial condition.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2009, our focus is primarily on factors within our control, including:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr height="17">
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><b><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></b></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p align="right"><b><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></b></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">controlling our internal costs, such as crew, wages and outside services costs;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr height="17">
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><b><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></b></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p align="right"><b><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></b></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">managing our working capital through partnering with our suppliers and pursuing receivable collections diligently;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr height="17">
<td height="17" valign="top"></td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p align="right"><b><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></b></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">managing our existing charter customers and promoting additional services;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr height="17">
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><b><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></b></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p align="right"><b><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></b></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">negotiating additional longer-term contracts for our corporate charters; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr height="17">
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><b><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></b></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p align="right"><b><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></b></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">continuing to deliver consistent and reliable services in our capacity flying with Continental.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Absent a combination of adverse factors outside of our control, such as a significant further deterioration of the U.S. economy, Continental&rsquo;s inability to pay us
pursuant to the terms of the existing capacity purchase agreement, or industry consolidation, which could result in the formation of one or more airlines with greater financial resources than ours to compete more aggressively in the markets we operate, we expect to
breakeven or have slight positive cash contribution from our operations in 2009.&nbsp; We continue to seek to stimulate demand for our charter flying with corporations, entertainment entities, casinos and other frequent group travelers.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, our available liquidity, including restricted and unrestricted cash, and our ARS, was $119.4 million.&nbsp; In early 2008, we invested
approximately $65 million in ARS which are primarily backed by student loans that are guaranteed by the U.S. government and have AAA long-term ratings from Moody&rsquo;s and Standard &amp; Poor&rsquo;s.&nbsp; The fair value of our ARS was $41.4 million as of December
31, 2008.&nbsp; For a detailed list of our current ARS, please see Exhibit 10.14.&nbsp; The securities are held at Citigroup Global Markets, Inc., Banc of America Securities, LLC and Royal Bank of Canada Capital Markets.&nbsp; While the contractual maturities of the
underlying securities within these ARS fall primarily in years maturing after 2030, each security has a reset period of either seven or 28 days.&nbsp; Beginning February 11, 2008, auctions for these securities were not successful, resulting in our continuing to hold
them and the issuers paying interest.&nbsp; Additionally, during the fourth quarter 2008, two of our ARS holdings were sold at nominal discounted rates, resulting in approximately $9.9 million being reclassified as unrestricted cash.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Subsequent to year-end, we monetized $4.2 million of our ARS holdings for 87.5% of the securities face value.&nbsp; We continue to monitor the ARS market and will
aggressively pursue monetizing the assets at or near face value through additional market transactions and recently initiated litigation against Royal Bank of Canada related to such investments brokered by the firm.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We believe that our existing liquidity, projected 2009 cash flows, including the incremental sources of liquidity described above, if needed, will be sufficient to fund
current operations and our financial obligations through the year ending December 31, 2009.&nbsp; However, as noted above, factors outside our control may dictate that we alter our current plans and expectations.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Future Costs</font></b></p>

<p><u><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></u></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We remain committed to providing competitively priced services by controlling our costs; however, we believe that our costs are likely to increase in the future due
to:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">changes in wages, salaries and related fringe benefit costs, including changes to our self-insured medical and workers compensation costs;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">aging of our fleet, resulting in higher aircraft maintenance costs;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">changes in the costs of materials and outside services, including our information technology costs;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">changes in governmental regulations, insurance and taxes affecting air transportation and the costs charged for airport access, including new security requirements; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">financing costs in order to satisfy any operating and/or financial obligations.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the long term, failure to control our costs would prevent us from remaining competitive and reduce our ability to limit losses including the opportunities to attract
additional corporate customers or to survive a prolonged economic downturn.</font></p>

<p><b><u><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></u></b></p>

<p><b><u><font size="2" face="Arial">Critical Accounting Policies and Estimates</font></u></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our consolidated financial statements have been prepared in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles.&nbsp; The preparation of these financial
statements requires us to make estimates and judgments that affect reported amounts and related disclosures.&nbsp; We have identified the accounting policies and estimates below as critical to our business operations and understanding of our results of
operations.&nbsp; The SEC has defined critical accounting policies and estimates as the ones that are most important to the presentation of a Company&rsquo;s financial condition and results and require the Company to make its most difficult and subjective judgments,
often as a result of the need to make estimates of matters that are inherently uncertain.&nbsp; For all of these estimates, we caution that future events rarely develop exactly as forecasted, and the best estimates routinely require judgment.&nbsp; The discussion
below is not intended to be a comprehensive list of our accounting estimates and policies.&nbsp; For a detailed discussion on the application of our accounting policies, see Item 8.&nbsp; &ldquo;Financial Statements and Supplementary Data &ndash; Notes to
Consolidated Financial Statements &ndash; Note 1.&rdquo;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="720">
<tr>
<td valign="bottom">
<p align="center"><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Description</font></b></p>
</td>
<td valign="bottom">
<p align="center"><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Judgments and Uncertainties</font></b></p>
</td>
<td valign="bottom">
<p align="center"><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Effect if Actual Results Differ from Assumptions</font></b></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Revenue Recognition</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">Contract Revenues.&nbsp;</font></i></b> We recognize our operating revenue under contractual arrangements, such as the Continental CPA and Delta CPA, pursuant to the terms of the contracts.&nbsp; Operating revenues from these
contracts have been classified as passenger revenue.&nbsp; Under the Amended Continental CPA, we derive our revenue based on fixed block hour rates multiplied by the block hours flown for the period thereby reducing or eliminating the risk of misinterpretation of the
agreement.&nbsp;</p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
<br />
 <b><i>Contract Revenues.</i></b>&nbsp; We recognize as revenue compensation received from Continental for reimbursement of our fixed costs as such amounts are deemed non-refundable, nor subject to credit risk.</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
<br />
 <b><i>Contract Revenues.</i></b>&nbsp; Related to the Amended Continental CPA, we also entered into a settlement agreement with Continental to release the parties&rsquo; claims at the time of the agreement to amend the then existing capacity purchase agreement,
relating to certain identified payments under such capacity purchase agreement, including disputes previously disclosed as possible matters for arbitration.&nbsp;&nbsp; As such, the revenue recognized under the Continental CPA through June 30, 2008 is not subject to
dispute.&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Spare Parts and Supplies</font></b></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Inventories, expendable parts and supplies relating to flight equipment are carried at average acquisition cost and are expensed when used.&nbsp; Inventories are carried at the lower of amortized cost or net realizable value.&nbsp; The
adequacy of our allowance for obsolescence requires a high degree of judgment.</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
<br />
 Our allowance for obsolescence related to inventory is provided over the remaining useful life of the related aircraft, plus allowance for spare parts currently identified as excess.&nbsp; Part of the calculation for this reserve is based on historical
experience.&nbsp; In addition, we may reserve for additional obsolescence when current available market data indicate a decline in the fair value of parts or if we deem parts as excess inventory.</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
<br />
 As of December 31, 2008, our allowance for obsolescence related to our spare parts and supplies was approximately $12.9 million.&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<div align="center"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman"></font></p>

<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="720">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Goodwill and Intangible Assets</font></b></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Under Statement of Financial Accounting Standard No. 142&ndash;&ldquo;Goodwill and Other Intangible Assets&rdquo; (&ldquo;SFAS 142&rdquo;), intangible assets can have either finite or indefinite useful lives.&nbsp; Our critical
accounting estimate is related to our &ldquo;Reorganization Value in Excess of Amounts Allocable to Identifiable Assets,&rdquo; which has indefinite useful life.&nbsp; Under SFAS 142, goodwill and intangible assets with indefinite useful lives should be tested at
least annually for impairment.&nbsp; Factors considered important when determining the impairment of reporting segments under SFAS 142 include items affecting the cash flows of the reporting segments; the reporting segments&rsquo; operational performance versus
market expectations; the reporting segments&rsquo; performance compared to peers within the industry; the marketplace for and identification of the intangible asset of the reporting segments; significant changes in the underlying business strategy or operational
environment; material ongoing industry or economic trends; or other factors specific to the asset or reporting segments being evaluated.&nbsp; Any changes in the key assumptions about the business and its prospects, or changes in market conditions or other
externalities could result in an impairment charge.</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
<br />
 For our SFAS 142 analysis, we have identified that our &ldquo;Reorganization Value in Excess of Amounts Allocable to Identifiable Assets&rdquo; is associated with our Contract flying business segment.&nbsp; Additionally, we employed a discounted cash flow approach,
a market multiple approach and an acquisition approach for Contract flying.&nbsp; The discounted cash flow approach considers our expected cash generation capabilities, and the market&ndash;multiple approach and the acquisition approach analyzes similar companies or
transactions within the industry to derive multiples for the Company.</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
<br />
 Reorganization Value in Excess of Amounts Allocable to Identifiable Assets is allocated to our Contract flying segment.&nbsp; Due to the changed economics associated with the Amended Continental CPA, we performed an impairment analysis under SFAS 142 in 2008 and
concluded that the Reorganization Value in Excess of Amounts Allocable to Identifiable Assets was fully impaired and we recorded a non-cash charge of $12.8 million.&nbsp; The impairment charge is reflected in the line &ldquo;Impairment of fixed assets and
goodwill&rdquo; on our consolidated statement of operations for the year ended December 31, 2008.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<div align="center"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman"></font></p>

<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="720">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Fair Value Measurements</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">Cash and Short-term Investments.</font></i></b> Statement of Financial Accounting Standard No. 157, <i>Fair Value Measurements</i> (SFAS 157) provides a consistent definition of fair value which focuses on exit price and
prioritizes, within a measurement of fair value, the use of market based inputs over entity-specific inputs.&nbsp; SFAS 157 also establishes a three-level hierarchy for fair value measurements based on the transparency of inputs to the valuation of an asset or
liability as of the measurement date.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008 we held cash equivalents and short-term investments in ARS that were required to be measured at fair value.&nbsp; We determine the fair value of our cash equivalents using a market approach.&nbsp;
The market approach used prices and other relevant information generated by market transactions involving identical assets.&nbsp; We determine fair value for our ARS based on inputs which are unobservable and significant to the fair value measurement such as the
timing of expected future cash flows, underlying collateralization, creditworthiness of the counterparties, and a discount rate that accounts for relevant market conditions.</p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
<br />
 <b><i>Cash and Short-term Investments.</i></b> Currently, there is not an active market for our ARS, accordingly; we determine fair value using a discounted cash flow model. Our model contains uncertainties because it requires management to make assumptions and to
apply judgment to estimate discount rates, anticipated maturity, industry and economic factors and other key metrics.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
<br />
 <b><i>Cash and Short-term Investments.</i></b> In February 2008, we invested $65 million in ARS which are classified as available-for-sale securities and are held at fair value.&nbsp; In accordance with SFAS 157, we recorded an other-than-temporary impairment of
$13.7 million. A 10% change in our impairment assessment would have decreased net loss for the year ended December 31, 2008 by $1.4 million.&nbsp; We consistently applied the fair value approach to our ARS throughout 2008 and recorded $0.5 million in net unrealized
loss to other comprehensive income.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
 <b><i>Convertible Secured Notes.&nbsp;</i></b> Our 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023 were recorded at fair value at the date of issuance in accordance with EITF 96-19, &ldquo;Debtor&rsquo;s Accounting for a Modification or Exchange of Debt
Instruments&rdquo;&nbsp; as the expected cash flows of the new instrument were 10% greater than the cash flows of our 4.25% Convertible Notes due 2023.</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
 <b><i>Convertible Secured Notes.&nbsp;</i></b> We determine fair value using quoted market prices for identical assets in a market that has limited trading and is stressed due to the current credit crisis.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
 <b><i>Convertible Secured Notes.&nbsp;</i></b> In 2008, we amended the indenture governing the Convertible Secured Notes which triggered us to record a gain from debt discount of $27.8 million that will be amortized over the life of the new instrument up to the
first date at which we may be required to repurchase the notes in August 2011, resulting in a decrease to non-operating income.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<div align="center"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman"></font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman"></font></p>

<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="720">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">Long-Lived Assets</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Long-lived assets, primarily consisting of investments in other entities and flight and ground equipment assets are evaluated for impairment whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate that the carrying value may not be
recoverable.&nbsp; When evaluating long-lived assets for potential impairment, we first compare the carrying value of the asset&rsquo;s estimated future undiscounted cash flows.&nbsp; If the estimated future cash flows are less than the carrying value of the asset,
we calculate an impairment loss.&nbsp; The impairment loss calculation compares the carrying value of the asset to the asset&rsquo;s estimated fair value.&nbsp; We recognize an impairment loss if the amount of the asset&rsquo;s carrying value exceeds the
asset&rsquo;s estimated fair value.&nbsp; If we recognize an impairment loss, the adjusted carrying amount of the asset becomes its new cost basis and, if applicable, will be depreciated over the remaining useful life of that asset.</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">Long-Lived Assets</font></i></b> &nbsp;</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Our impairment loss calculations contain uncertainties as they require management to make assumptions and to apply judgment to estimate future cash flows and asset fair values.</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">Long-Lived Assets</font></i></b> &nbsp;</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">We have consistently applied our impairment loss methodology during the past three fiscal years.&nbsp;&nbsp; As a result of our impairment tests in 2008 we recorded impairment charges of $15.8 million to write the long-lived assets to
their estimated fair values.&nbsp; The assets impaired were determined to have no value so no portion of the impairment charge will result in future cash expenditures.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
 Income Taxes</font></b></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">We record a valuation allowance against our deferred tax assets when we conclude it is more likely than not that we will be unable to generate adequate taxable income of the appropriate character, to utilize such assets.&nbsp; The
tender offer and partial redemption in August 2008 of the 4.25% Convertible Notes due 2023 caused us to trigger a change in ownership limitation under Section 382 of the Internal Revenue Code in August 2008.&nbsp; Due to the decrease in our market capitalization, the
Section 382 change triggered in August 2008 resulted in our conclusion that it was more likely than not that we would not be able to utilize our deferred tax assets due to this limitation and therefore we recorded an increase of $19.3 million to the valuation
allowance.</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
 Income Taxes</font></b></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">This determination requires management to make judgments regarding expectations of future taxable income.&nbsp; The Section 382 limitation may impact payments due or refundable under the tax agreement with Continental because the
certain deductions that are limited under Section 382 are the same tax attributes that drive our payment obligations under the tax agreement.</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
 Income Taxes</font></b></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">If amounts are deemed recoverable under the tax agreement, then an adjustment may be required to reduce our valuation allowance.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In addition to our critical accounting estimates and policies described above, we made other estimates that, while not involving the same degree of judgment, are
important to understanding our financial statements.&nbsp; In general, we base our estimates on historical experience, information from third-party professionals and various other assumptions that we believe are reasonable under the circumstances.&nbsp; We
continually evaluate our accounting policies and the estimates used to prepare our consolidated financial statements.&nbsp; Our estimates as of the date of the financial statements reflect our best judgment after giving consideration to all currently available facts
and circumstances.&nbsp; As such, actual results may differ significantly from these estimates and may require adjustment in the future as additional facts become known or as circumstances change.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We have discussed the development and selection of these critical accounting policies and estimates with the Audit Committee of our Board of Directors, and the Committee
has reviewed the disclosures presented above.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>Recently Issued Accounting Standards</u></font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In May&nbsp;2008, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB) affirmed the consensus of FASB Staff Position APB 14-1 (FSP APB 14-1), &ldquo;Accounting for
Convertible Debt Instruments That May Be Settled in Cash upon Conversion (Including Partial Cash Settlement)&rdquo;, which applies to all convertible debt instruments that have a &lsquo;&lsquo;net settlement feature&rsquo;&rsquo;, which means that such convertible
debt instruments, by their terms, may be settled either wholly or partially in cash upon conversion. FSP&nbsp;APB 14-1 requires issuers of convertible debt instruments that may be settled wholly or partially in cash upon conversion to separately account for the
liability and equity components in a manner reflective of the issuers&rsquo; nonconvertible debt borrowing rate. FSP APB 14-1 is effective for financial statements issued for fiscal years beginning after December&nbsp;15,&nbsp;2008 and interim periods within those
fiscal years.&nbsp;&nbsp;Early adoption is not permitted and retroactive application to all periods presented is required.&nbsp;&nbsp;The adoption of FSP APB 14-1 will affect the historical accounting for our Original 4.25% Convertible Notes and our 11.25%
Convertible Secured Notes due 2023. &nbsp;We are continuing to evaluate the impact of this standard to our results of operations and financial position however; we expect that the ultimate application of FSP APB 14-1 will result in an increase in interest expense for
the years presented.&nbsp; In addition, the company is evaluating the impact this standard will have on our 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="ops2"></a><b><u><font size="2" face="Arial">Operations Review</font></u></b></p>

<p><u><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></u></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Under the terms of the Amended Continental CPA, we are not reimbursed for certain costs, primarily fuel, aircraft rent and certain ground handling services, which were
previously recorded as revenue.&nbsp; Accordingly revenues from July 1, 2008 forward under our contract flying with Continental are different than prior to the Amended Continental CPA.&nbsp; Additionally in September 2008, we ceased our Branded Flying which began in
April 2007.&nbsp; Accordingly, results between 2008 and 2007 are not comparable.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
</font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="697">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(1)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Revenue passenger miles are the number of scheduled miles flown by revenue passengers.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(2)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Available seat miles are the number of passenger seats available multiplied by the number of scheduled miles those seats are flown.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(3)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Passenger load factor equals revenue passenger miles divided by available seat miles.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(4)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Operating cost per available seat mile is operating costs divided by available seat miles.&nbsp; The reimbursable expenses are different under the terms of the Amended Continental CPA versus the Original Continental CPA, and therefore
costs are inconsistent with prior periods, beginning July 2008.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(5)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Block hours are the hours from gate departure to gate arrival.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(6)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Operating cost per block hour is operating costs divided by block hours.&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(7)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Under the Amended Continental CPA, Continental is responsible for the cost of providing fuel for all flights and, therefore, effective July 1, 2008, fuel expense is no longer included in our statements of operations for our Continental
Express flying.&nbsp; Prior to July 1, 2008 fuel cost used in calculations includes cost of fuel and related fuel tax.&nbsp; Airlines incurred fuel expense and fuel tax equal to the lower of the actual cost or the agreed-upon caps of 66.0 cents and 5.2 cents per
gallon, respectively, based on our fuel purchase agreement with Continental.&nbsp; In 2007, our fuel activity included purchases to support our various business platforms outside of the Continental CPA.&nbsp; These purchases were executed through an agreement with an
independent third party at an average price per gallon of $2.43, which represents 16.7% of our total fuel consumption for 2007.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(8)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Average daily utilization of each aircraft is the average number of block hours per day that an aircraft is operated.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We monitor the statistical information above closely to ensure that we are continually focused on our operational efficiencies and cost control.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The following discussion provides an analysis of our results of operations and reasons for any material changes for the periods indicated.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i><u>Comparison of 2008 to 2007</u></i></b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Operating Revenue and Segment Profit / (Loss)</font></b></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The table below (in millions, except percentage data) sets forth the changes in revenue, direct segment costs and segment profit (loss) from 2008 to 2007.&nbsp; Before
2007 we did not have any segments that were deemed material.&nbsp; As such, revenues and costs are shown in Contract Flying only.&nbsp; A significant portion of our operating expenses and infrastructure is integrated across segments (e.g., for maintenance,
non-airport facility rentals, outside services, general and administrative expenses) in order to support our entire fleet of 244 aircraft; therefore, we do not allocate these costs to the individual segments identified above, but evaluate them for our consolidated
operation.&nbsp; We believe that the presentation of our consolidated shared costs and transition costs is consistent with the manner in which these expenses are reviewed by our chief operating decision makers.&nbsp; These costs are included as a part of the analysis
of our operating expenses below.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Contract Flying.</i></font></b> &nbsp; The decrease in operating revenue and expenses within our Contract Flying segment is primarily due to new terms under the
Amended Continental CPA which became effective July 1, 2008.&nbsp; Prior to July 1, 2008, Airlines was entitled to receive payment for each block hour that Continental scheduled it to fly and was based on a formula designed to provide Airlines with a target operating
margin of 10%.&nbsp; The Amended agreement provides payments to us at a pre-determined rate based on block hours flown that are considerably lower than the rates under the original agreement.&nbsp; Likewise, under the Amended Continental CPA, Continental is
responsible for the cost of providing fuel for all flights and for paying aircraft rent for all aircraft covered by the Amended Continental CPA and, therefore, these items are not included in our statements of operations for the quarter-ended September 30, 2008 and
thereafter.&nbsp; In addition, Delta and ExpressJet mutually agreed in July 2008 to terminate their CPA effective September 2, 2008.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></b> <b><i><font size="2">Branded Flying</font></i></b><b><i><font size="2">.</font></i></b><b><font size="2">&nbsp;</font></b> <font size="2">We began Branded
Flying on April 2, 2007 and ended operations September 2, 2008.&nbsp; In July 2008, we announced we would suspend flying under the ExpressJet brand and Delta Prorate agreement effective September 2008 due to record high fuel prices that made the Branded Flying
operations impossible to sustain.&nbsp; We were not profitable in this operation in 2008 or 2007.&nbsp; Revenues from this flying were approximately 17% of our total operating revenue for 2008 and slightly less than 11% of our total operating revenue for 2007.&nbsp;
Average load factor within this segment was 69.1% in 2008 versus 55.7% in 2007.&nbsp; In spite of seeing improvements in operations in 2008 over 2007, unprecedented high fuel costs continued to be the driving force in determining Branded Flying&rsquo;s profitability
and as such we chose to suspend the operations.&nbsp; We recognized $18 million in revenue as a result of the suspension of operations due to adjustments to our air traffic liability, frequent flier plan and certain termination payments.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Aviation Services.</i></font></b> &nbsp; In 2008, Aviation Services had a segment profit margin of 45.6%, up from 38% in 2007.&nbsp; This increase is due primarily
to additional ground handling contracts secured at more favorable rates than in 2007.</p>
