<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Wages, salaries &amp; related costs</i></font></b> decreased 9.2% from 2007 to 2008 primarily due to head count reduction in our work force related to the
suspension of Branded Flying operations.&nbsp; Additionally certain wage concessions were agreed to in 2008 under some of Airlines&rsquo; collective bargaining agreements and bonus plans were trimmed for 2008 due to our continuing losses.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the future, we anticipate that our wages, salaries and related costs may be affected by the following factors:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">wage increases to incentivize key personnel to remain with us as we continue to stabilize our Company;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">wage rate increases in accordance with our collective bargaining agreements as a result of higher seniority of our work force; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">projected increases in health and medical benefit costs.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Aircraft fuel and related taxes</i> </font></b>decreased 29.5% primarily due to new terms under the Amended Continental CPA which became effective July 1,
2008.&nbsp; Prior to July 1, 2008, our fuel price, including related fuel taxes, was capped at 71.20 cents per gallon under the original Continental CPA.&nbsp; Under the Amended Continental CPA, Continental is responsible for the cost of providing fuel for all
aircraft covered by the Amended Continental CPA and, therefore, the related expense is no longer included in our statements of operations.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Aircraft rentals</i></font></b>&nbsp; decreased 42.7% primarily due to new terms under the Amended Continental CPA which became effective July 1, 2008.&nbsp; Under
the Amended Continental CPA, Continental is responsible for paying aircraft rent for all aircraft under that arrangement and, therefore, the related expense is no longer included in our statements of operations.&nbsp; In addition, lease payments for the 30 aircraft
operating outside of the Amended Continental CPA are contracted at significantly lower rates than previous years.</p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Other rentals and landing fees</font></i></b> decreased 19.3% from 2007 to 2008.&nbsp; Airport facilities and landing fees expense was down due to decrease in
contract flying in 2008 and changes due to new CAL CPA effective July 1, 2008.&nbsp; Outside simulator rent was significantly higher in 2007 due to the start-up of the new lines of business and the need to train additional staff.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ground Handling</font></i> </b>decreased 38.7% primarily due to new terms under the Amended Continental CPA which became effective July 1, 2008.&nbsp; Under the
Amended Continental CPA, Continental is responsible for ground handling for all Continental managed stations.&nbsp; In addition, under the Amended Continental CPA, Continental is responsible for the cost of providing fueling services for all aircraft covered by the
Amended Continental CPA and, therefore, the related ground handling and aircraft servicing expense is no longer included in our statements of operations.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Outside services</font></i></b> decreased 16.6% from 2007 to 2008 primarily due to a decrease in expenses incurred to support our diversification strategy in 2007
and a reduction of approximately 50% in CAL admin fees earned in 2008.&nbsp; This fee was cancelled in the Amended Continental CPA.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Marketing and distribution</font></i> </b>decreased 18.2% primarily due to the suspension of flying under our ExpressJet brand and Delta pro-rate arrangement
effective September 2, 2008.&nbsp; All marketing and distribution cost for aircraft operating within the Continental CPA is incurred by Continental.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Depreciation and amortization&nbsp;</font></i></b> increased 11.3% from 2007 to 2008.&nbsp; This increase is primarily due to the full year impact of capital
additions and improvements incurred in prior years as we ramped up for new operations.&nbsp; The increase was partially offset by the reduced depreciation associated with our suspension of Branded Flying as we impaired $8 million of capital assets used to support
these operations,</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Impairment charges on fixed assets and goodwill</font></i></b>&nbsp;increased $20.8 million primarily due to a $12.8 million non-cash impairment of goodwill
related to the Continental CPA, and a $8.0 million non-cash impairment to write-off certain capital assets, primarily non-moveable equipment, building and aircraft improvements.&nbsp; Similar impairment charges did not occur in 2007.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Special charges</font></i> </b>increased $22.4 million primarily due to the suspension of flying under our branded commercial passenger flight operations and our
capacity purchase and pro-rate agreements with Delta Airlines in September 2008.&nbsp; In connection with these capacity reductions and the transition of up to 39 aircraft back to Continental, we incurred special charges of $21.7 million related to aircraft, employee
reductions and certain other charges in addition to a $0.7 million non-cash charge related to previously disputed base closure costs associated with the original Continental CPA.&nbsp; Similar impairment charges did not occur in 2007.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Other operating expenses</font></i></b> decreased by 27.4% in 2008 as compared to 2007 primarily due to the suspension of operations announced July 2008 for
certain business lines.&nbsp; Employee related expenses such as per diem, travel &amp; relocation, and hotels declined in relation to the reduction in employee head count.&nbsp; Passenger services and catering related expenses declined as the suspended business
operations wound down.</p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>

</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><b><br clear="all" />

</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Gain from debt discount</i></font></b> was $27.8 million as we recorded, in accordance with EITF 96-19 &ldquo;Debtor&rsquo;s Accounting for a Modification or
Exchange of Debt Instruments,&rdquo; our $68.5 million 11.25% Convertible Notes due 2023 to a fair value of $40.7 million, net of a debt discount that was recorded as a non-recurring gain under non-operating income for 2008.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Settlement of fuel contracts</i></b> $23.1 million as we recorded the sale of our fixed forward purchase contracts for periods subsequent to September 2,
2008.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Impairment charge on investments</font></i></b> was $21.5 million for 2008 as compared to $7.0 million for 2007.&nbsp; A $13.7 million impairment was recorded on
our ARS investment in 2008.&nbsp; The need to record an other-than-temporary decline in valuation was caused by the uncertainty in the ARS market and the fact we may need to liquidate these investments before it recovers. Impairments on our equity investments of $7.8
million and $7.0 million were recognized during 2008 and 2007, respectively.&nbsp; We review our investments in unconsolidated affiliates for impairment whenever events or changes in business circumstances indicate that the carrying amount of the investments may not
be fully recoverable. See Item 8&nbsp; &ldquo;Financial Statements and Supplementary Data&rdquo; &ndash; Note 1 - &ldquo;Summary of Significant Accounting Policies&rdquo; for further information on our ARS and Note 6 &ndash; &ldquo;Investments in Other
Entities&rdquo; for further discussion of the equity impairments.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Amortization of debt discount&nbsp;</font></i></b> represents amortization of the fair value adjustment of $27.8 million recorded as a gain that will be recognized
to non-operating income until August 2011, the next put date of our 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Interest income</font></i></b> decreased primarily due to the volume of cash invested as well as decreases in the rate of interest earned.</p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><font size="2"><br clear="all" />

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><u><font size="2" face="Arial">Comparison of 2007 to 2006</font></u></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Operating Revenue and Segment Profit / (Loss)</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The table below (in millions, except percentage data) sets forth the changes in revenue, direct segment costs and segment profit (loss) from 2007 to 2006.&nbsp; Before
2007 we did not have any segments that were deemed material.&nbsp; As such, revenues and costs are shown in Contract Flying only.&nbsp; A significant portion of our operating expenses and infrastructure is integrated across segments (e.g., for maintenance,
non-airport facility rentals, outside services, general and administrative expenses) in order to support our entire fleet of 274 aircraft; therefore, we do not allocate these costs to the individual segments identified above, but evaluate them for our consolidated
operation.&nbsp; Additionally, due to the transition of our 69 aircraft released from the Continental CPA in 2007, we incurred approximately $13.6 million in transition expenses associated with painting, maintenance modifications and training to ready our operation
for flying outside of the Continental CPA.&nbsp; These costs were not included in our measurement of segment profitability as they are expected to be nonrecurring.&nbsp; We believe that the presentation of our consolidated shared costs and transition costs is
consistent with the manner in which these expenses are reviewed by our chief operating decision makers.&nbsp; These costs are included as a part of the analysis of our operating expenses below.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

did not have segments that were deemed material.&nbsp; As such, a similar table for 2006 is not presented.</p>

</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Contract Flying.</i></font></b> &nbsp; Our decrease in operating revenue for contract flying is primarily due to the withdrawal of 69 aircraft from the Continental
CPA.&nbsp; This decrease was partially offset by commencing contract flying under the Delta CPA and charter flying in 2007.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Since a substantial portion of Airlines&rsquo; costs under the Continental CPA are reconciled for differences between actual costs and estimated costs included in block
hour rates at a 10.0% operating margin (see Item 1. Business &ndash; Continental Capacity Purchase and Other Agreements for further discussion of the details related to this cost reconciliation), if Airlines&rsquo; prevailing margin (before any reconciliation
payments) fell outside its margin band of 8.5% to 10.0% for 2007 and 2006, Airlines&rsquo; revenue would have been adjusted to bring it back to its floor or cap.&nbsp; Reconciliation payments from Continental in 2007 netted $4.2 million to us.&nbsp; The 2007
reconciliation payment was primarily caused by the lower rates resulting from arbitration with Continental in 2007.&nbsp; Reconciliation payments to Continental totaled $7.3 million for 2006.&nbsp; The 2006 reconciliation payment was primarily driven by lower actual
wages, salaries and related costs and maintenance, materials and repair expenses as compared to the estimated costs in the agreements block hour rates.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On July 27, 2007, the three-member arbitration panel issued its decision relating to the 2007 block hour rates that Continental paid Airlines for regional jet service in
2007.&nbsp; The panel considered various components related to the proposed rates that we charge Continental in connection with regional jet service, including the costs that formed the basis for our 2007 rate proposal and the allocation of certain costs between the
parties.&nbsp; The panel did not make any changes to the costs included in our 2007 budgeted rates except as those costs related to allocation.&nbsp; The panel determined that the annual 2007 budgeted rates originally presented by Airlines should be reduced in the
aggregate by $14.2 million, which includes the 10% operating margin.&nbsp; As a result of the panel&rsquo;s decision, we recorded our passenger revenue pursuant to the terms of the Continental CPA using the block hour rates determined by the panel for the year ended
December 31, 2007.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Branded Flying.</i>&nbsp;</font></b> We began Branded Flying on April 2, 2007.&nbsp; Although passenger revenue from such flying was less than 11% of our total
operating revenue for 2007, we believed that our passenger revenue would continue to grow contingent upon our ability to use marketing and promotion programs to shift our traffic mix from heavily leisure travel to more business/corporate travel.&nbsp;</p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><b><br clear="all" />
</b></font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></b> We were not profitable in this operation in 2007.&nbsp; Our results of operations were impacted by record high fuel prices, similar to the rest of the
airline industry and an average load factor for 2007 being 55.7%.&nbsp; Therefore for fuel, we implemented a strategy by entering into fixed forward price contracts with our fuel provider using a systematic method for determining the volume and the price for which to
enter into the contracts for a rolling 12-month period on a quarterly basis.&nbsp; Our average load factor primarily resulted from several factors including a lack of brand awareness and a very aggressive redeployment of aircraft to Branded driven by the pace of the
aircraft coming out of the Continental CPA.&nbsp; As outlined above, to increase our load factor we tried to shift our traffic mix from heavily leisure to more business/corporate travel.&nbsp; Although our fixed forward price fuel contracts partially mitigated our
exposure to fuel price fluctuation, fuel continued to be a driving force in determining Branded Flying&rsquo;s profitability along with our ability to shift our traffic mix from leisure to more business travel.&nbsp; Additionally, we incurred marketing and
distribution costs related to supporting the revenues for this segment.&nbsp; Under the terms of our contractual flying, these costs were incurred by the major airline with which we contracted.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Aviation Services.&nbsp;</i></font></b> Aviation Services was included in Contract Flying in 2006 as it was not deemed material for segment reporting
purposes.&nbsp; In 2007, Aviation Services had a segment profit margin of 38.0%.&nbsp; This segment profit margin and increases in operations for aviation services was related to additional fixed-rate contracts for ground handling which began in
2007<b><i>.</i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Wages, salaries &amp; related costs</i></font></b> increased 13.2% from 2006 to 2007 due to our growth in our work force to support changes in our flight
operations and our corporate infrastructure and increases in wage rates under some of Airlines&rsquo; collective bargaining agreements.&nbsp; In conjunction with the increases in base wages, we incurred approximately $13.3 million higher employee benefit costs, such
as medical coverage, workers&rsquo; compensation costs and 401(k) expenses in 2007.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Aircraft fuel and related taxes</i></font></b> increased 42.3% from 2006 to 2007.&nbsp; This increase was primarily due to the diversification of our operations
into other business platforms.&nbsp; Our fuel price, including related fuel taxes, was capped at 71.20 cents per gallon by the Continental CPA while the average price of our fuel, included related fuel taxes, for our operations outside of the Continental CPA was
$2.43 per gallon.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Outside services</i></font></b> increased 13.6% from 2006 to 2007 primarily due to increased weather events resulting in higher deicing expenses and increased
expenses to support our diversification strategy.</p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Marketing and distribution</i></font></b> increased 100.0% to $31.4 million during 2007. This increase resulted from the need to re-brand our Company and diversify
our customer base to support and promote our diversification into other lines of business through advertising and promotion, loyalty programs, global distribution systems and reservation call centers.&nbsp;</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Depreciation and amortization</i></font></b> increased 16.3% from 2006 to 2007.&nbsp; This increase was primarily due to capital additions and improvements
necessary to run our new operations.&nbsp;</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Other operating expenses</i></font></b> increased 34.4% from 2006 and 2007 primarily caused by passenger services and catering-related expenses incurred to support
our operations outside of the Continental CPA.&nbsp; Additionally, crew related charges, such as per diem, hotel cost and relocation expenses, increased due to higher rates and increased flight operations partially resulting from our transition activities.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Interest expense</i></font></b> was primarily related to our Original 4.25% Convertible Notes and the EDC Loans.&nbsp; Interest expense related to these long-term
debts increased in 2007 by approximately $1.3 million as a result of increased amortization of the financing fees related to our convertible note.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Equity Investment losses</i></font></b> of $8.3 million and $2.0 million were recognized during 2007 and 2006, respectively.&nbsp; We review our investments in
unconsolidated affiliates for impairment whenever events or changes in business circumstances indicate that the carrying amount of the investments may not be fully recoverable.&nbsp; See Item 8.&nbsp; &ldquo;Financial Statements and Supplementary Data &ndash; Note 6
&ndash; Investments in Other Entities&rdquo; for further discussion of this impairment.&nbsp; The remaining $1.3 million in 2007 is our proportionate share of the earnings and losses of all equity investments we currently hold.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="liquidity"></a><b><u><font size="2" face="Arial">Liquidity, Capital Resources and Financial Position</font></u></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i><u>Sources and Uses of Cash</u></i></b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; For the years ended December 31, 2008 and 2007, our operations used $56.1 million and $39.9 million, respectively, in cash flow.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008 and 2007,
we also had $20.5 million and $24.8 million of restricted cash, respectively, which is comprised of collateral for our workers&rsquo; compensation coverage, customer deposits for future charter flights, letters of credit, and holdbacks required under our credit card
processing agreements.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2008 and 2007, we spent $10.3 million and $48.9 million, respectively, on capital expenditures.&nbsp; A majority of the expenditures for 2008 and 2007 were spent on
flight and ground equipment to support the expansion of our operations to new lines of business and building our information technology infrastructure to support these new businesses and the increase in our flight schedules under the Continental CPA.&nbsp; Of the
$10.3 million spent in 2008, approximately $1.9 million was spent on capital expenditures for our strategic business ventures which are outside of the Continental CPA.</font></p>

<p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In light of the current economic recession, coupled with the Amended Continental CPA that pays us at lower block hour rates and is currently operating at record low
utilization levels, we believe strict budgeting and cash preservation are crucial to sustain our liquidity and meet our financial obligations through 2009.&nbsp; Our focus on execution of all cost savings initiatives launched in 2008 is essential to generate positive
cash flow and preserve our current cash balance.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our 2008 cash flows have included the following sources of cash outside of normal operating revenues:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We believe that our existing liquidity, projected 2009 cash flows, including the incremental sources of liquidity described above, if needed, will be sufficient to fund
current operations and our financial obligations through the year ending December 31, 2009.&nbsp; However, as noted above, factors outside our control may dictate that we alter our current plans and expectations.</font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>Long-term Debt</u></font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Although we did amend the terms of Original 4.25% Convertible Notes we did not enter into any new financing transactions in 2008.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008,
long-term debt, including current maturities, totaled $70.2 million (par value), which consisted of the 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023 and the EDC Loans.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In July 2003, we completed an offering of $137.2 million aggregate principal amount of Original 4.25% Convertible Notes due 2023 with interest payable
semi-annually.&nbsp; Holders of this debt had the right to require that we repurchase their notes on August 1, 2008, 2013 and 2018 (&ldquo;Repurchase Dates&rdquo;) at a repurchase price equal to 100% of the principal amount of the notes to be repurchased plus accrued
and unpaid interest, if any.&nbsp; &nbsp; Under the indenture governing the convertible notes, we were able to satisfy the obligation with either cash, shares of our common stock, or a combination of cash and shares.&nbsp; During 2008, we took the following actions
after consulting with our independent financial advisors:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr height="16">
<td height="16" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="16" valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="16" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Received stockholders approval for two proposals that provided us greater flexibility in satisfying our repurchase obligations with respect to the Original 4.25% Convertible Notes, which included the ability to issue such number of
shares of our common stock as necessary to repurchase all outstanding convertible notes that were tendered on August 1, 2008, and increased our authorized common stock from 200 million shares to 400 million shares;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr height="17">
<td height="17" valign="top"></td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Commenced our repurchase offer for the Original 4.25% Convertible Notes and provided written notice to the trustee of our intention to pay the repurchase price wholly in shares of our common stock;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr height="17">
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">Unilaterally amended the indenture</font> <font size="2">governing the notes to increase the coupon from 4.25% to 11.25% over the remaining note term, to provide security based on a pro-rata amount of collateral and to
provide for an additional repurchase date on August 1, 2011, in order to provide improved terms and additional flexibility for the noteholders; a<font color="black">nd</font></font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr height="17">
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Issued 16.4 million shares (Reverse Split adjusted) of our common stock in payment of the repurchase price for the $59.7 million principal amount of the notes validly tendered and to settle accrued and unpaid interest due August 1,
2008.&nbsp; Because the common stock was issued in exchange for the Original 4.25% Convertible Notes exclusively with the existing holders of the notes, and no commission or other compensation was paid in soliciting the exchange, the securities were exempt from
registration under Section 3(a)(9) of the Securities Act of 1933.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Following the completion of the tender offer in August 2008 for our Original 4.25% Convertible Notes due 2023, $68.5 million aggregate principal (prior to $7.6 million
subsequently repurchased by us) of our convertible notes remained outstanding.&nbsp; Additionally, as provided in the amended indenture governing the notes, such notes have become our 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023.&nbsp; In accordance with EITF 96-19
&ldquo;Debtor's Accounting for a Modification or Exchange of Debt Instruments,&rdquo; we accounted for this exchange as an extinguishment of debt, since the net present value of the cash flows under the exchanged terms was more than 10% of the net present value of
the cash flows under the terms of the original instrument.&nbsp; As required by accounting rules, we recorded the convertible notes to a fair value of $40.7 million, net of a debt discount of $27.8 million that will be amortized over the life of the new instrument up
to the first date at which we may be required to repurchase the notes in August 2011.&nbsp; The required adjustment was recorded as a non-recurring gain under non-operating income for 2008.&nbsp; The net balance of the 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023 as of
December 31, 2008 was $39.7 million, net of repurchases made by us.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We estimated fair value of our convertible notes based on an average of market trading activity for the convertible notes subsequent to the exchange in August
2008.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Other than the 11.25% Convertible Notes due 2023, we do not have any material long-term borrowings or available lines of credit.&nbsp; Pursuant to the terms of the
amended indenture governing the 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023, we granted a security interest, with a pro-rata portion, (based on the portion that the remaining notes represent of the total convertible notes that were issued) of assets with an appraised
value of approximately $181 million, including approximately $96 million in spare parts and $85 million of spare engines.&nbsp; Based on the principal amount of notes remaining outstanding on August 2, 2008, the pledged collateral for the notes totals approximately
$51.5 million in spare parts and $45.3 million in spare engines.&nbsp; We agreed that we will not as of any fiscal year end permit the aggregate outstanding principal amount of the Notes divided by the fair market value of the pledged collateral to be greater than
certain percentages outlined in the amended indenture.&nbsp; If such collateral ratios are greater than the applicable maximum, we will pledge additional spare parts, spare aircraft engines and / or cash and cash equivalents.&nbsp; Pursuant to the terms of the
amended indenture, we are required to deliver a certificate from our appraiser dated not later than 15 business days after January 1 of each year certifying the value as of January 1 or such later date.&nbsp; We delivered such certificate from our appraiser in
January 2009 and the appraised values of $180.4 million have not changed materially from the initial appraisal of $181 million at the amendment date.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The notes are guaranteed by Airlines.&nbsp; Except as otherwise specified in the indenture pursuant to which the notes were issued, there are no restrictions on
Airlines&rsquo; ability to transfer funds to Holdings in the form of cash dividends, loans or advances.&nbsp; General provisions of applicable state law, however, may limit the ability of any subsidiary to pay dividends or make distributions to its parent in certain
circumstances.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; If we elect to use shares of common stock to repurchase any notes on the Repurchase Dates, the number of shares will be equal to the repurchase price divided by 97.5% of
the average closing sales price of our common stock for the five consecutive trading days ending on the third business day prior to the applicable Repurchase Date (adjusted to take into account the occurrence of certain events that would require adjustment of the
conversion rate).&nbsp; In certain circumstances, the notes are convertible into our common stock, at a ratio of 54.9451 shares of common stock per $1,000 principal amount of notes, which was equivalent to an initial conversion price of approximately $18.20 per
common share; however, following the Reverse Split the ratio is now 5.49451, which is equivalent to a price of approximately $182.00 per share.&nbsp; The ratio is subject to adjustments if certain events take place, and holders may convert only if the closing sale
price per common share exceeds 120% of the conversion price for at least 20 trading days in the 30 consecutive trading day period ending on the last trading day of the preceding calendar quarter.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The EDC Loans consist of $10.7 million loaned to us in May 2003 and $6.6 million loaned to us in September 2003.&nbsp; The EDC Loans are secured by certain of our flight
simulators, flight data software and other equipment related to the simulators.&nbsp; We used all the proceeds from the EDC Loans to reduce the principal under a note payable to Continental.&nbsp; The amount due to EDC accrues interest at the six-month LIBOR plus
1.75% per annum.&nbsp; Each of the EDC Loans has a term of 96 months and each contains customary representations, warranties and covenants.&nbsp; Additionally, Continental is the guarantor of the EDC Loans, and a default under the guarantee would cause an
acceleration of the loan.&nbsp; In 2008, we made payments in the amount of $4.2 million on the EDC Loans, of which $3.5 million related to principal.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, the balance of the EDC Loans was $9.3 million.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008 and 2007,
the fair value of the EDC Loans was approximately $7.2 million and $12.4 million, respectively.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i><u>Securities Repurchase Program</u></i></b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In July 2005, our Board of Directors authorized the expenditure of up to $30 million to repurchase shares of our common stock.&nbsp; In February 2006, the Board
authorized the inclusion of our Original 4.25% Convertible Notes&nbsp;&nbsp; now our 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023 within the previously announced $30 million program.&nbsp; Additionally, during the fourth quarter of 2008, the Board authorized an
additional $15 million for this program.&nbsp; Purchases have been made from time to time in the open market; the timing of any repurchases under the program depends on a variety of factors, including market conditions, and may be suspended or discontinued at any
time.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, we had a balance of $10.1 million remaining within the program for additional purchases.&nbsp; As discussed In Note 11 &ndash; &ldquo;Earnings / (Loss) Per Share&rdquo;,<b></b>stockholders approved to effect a Reverse Split of our
common stock in 2008.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our other employees are not covered by collective bargaining agreements.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During 2008, we executed new agreements with our four unions resulting in approximately $20 million in labor savings.&nbsp; In addition, we realized $10 million in
concessions through reductions provided by management and clerical employees.&nbsp; Furthermore, an additional $5 million was contributed by the airport services division through wage and benefit reductions as well as productivity improvements.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i><u>Income Taxes&nbsp;</u></i></b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The tender offer and partial redemption in August 2008 of the 4.25% Convertible Notes due 2023 caused Holdings to trigger a change in ownership limitation under Section
382 of the Internal Revenue Code in August 2008. &nbsp;Section 382 limits a taxpayer's ability to utilize certain carryover tax attributes after a substantial cumulative change in ownership of their stock. The regulation mandates a three-year &ldquo;look back&rdquo;
requiring Holdings to evaluate its position related to Section 382 beginning in 2005. &nbsp;The results of the look back analysis indicated that Holdings triggered Section 382 changes in ownership in April 2005 and in August 2008. &nbsp;The April 2005 change resulted
in an after tax charge of $1.6 million primarily related to interest on the timing of certain tax obligations. Due to the decrease in our market capitalization, the Section 382 change triggered in August 2008 resulted in our conclusion that it was more likely than
not that we would not be able to utilize our deferred tax assets due to this limitation and therefore we recorded an increase of $19.3 million to the valuation allowance.&nbsp; We recorded the effects of this adjustment in 2008 as any impact to previously reported
financial statements was not deemed to be material.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Also during 2008 we recorded $8.5 million in income tax expense to record a valuation allowance for certain deferred tax assets related to capital losses and,
international and state tax net operating losses as it was concluded more likely than not that adequate income would not be generated to utilize these deferred tax assets based on their characterization and/or carryforward period.</font></p>

<p align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial">2016 to 2018</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="bottom" bgcolor="#e0e0e0"></td>
</tr>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In conjunction with our initial public offering in April 2002, the tax basis of our tangible and intangible assets was adjusted to fair value.&nbsp; This adjustment to
tax basis should result in additional tax deductions being available to us through 2017.&nbsp; In October 2006, Continental entered into a final settlement agreement with the IRS that included periods during which we were included in its consolidated federal income
tax return.&nbsp; Our taxable income was not adjusted, but the amount of net operating losses allocated to us was increased by approximately $31.2 million.&nbsp; In accordance with our tax agreement with Continental, to the extent we generate taxable income
sufficient to realize the additional tax deductions and tax attributes allocated to us, we are required to pay Continental a percentage of the amount of tax savings actually realized, excluding the effect of any loss carrybacks.&nbsp; We are required to pay
Continental 100% of the first third of the anticipated tax benefit, 90% of the second third and 80% of the last third.&nbsp; However, if the tax benefits are not realized by the end of 2018, we will be obligated to pay Continental 100% of any benefit realized after
that date.&nbsp; Since these payments are solely dependent on our ability to generate sufficient taxable income to realize these deferred tax assets, they are recorded as an obligation to Continental within the deferred tax asset accounts, and the portion we may
retain in the future is offset by a valuation allowance.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; At the time of the initial public offering, the valuation allowance and the obligation to Continental offset the step-up in basis of assets in our long-term deferred tax
asset account.&nbsp; There were no payments made to Continental under the tax agreement during 2008 and 2007.&nbsp; We made approximately $24.8 million and $25.3 million of net payments to Continental under the tax agreement related to the additional tax deductions
during 2006 and 2005, respectively.&nbsp; Because of the April 2005 Section 382 change in ownership, our ability to utilize some of the tax attributes flowing from Continental has been limited.&nbsp; Our losses in 2007 and 2008 carryback to offset the tax shortfall,
but result in an interest charge recorded in current tax expense and discussed above.&nbsp; Our August 2008 Section 382 ownership change limits our ability to realize the gross deferred tax assets recorded at December 31, 2008.&nbsp; Federal and many state net
operating loss carryovers are subject to substantial annual limitations over their remaining life, while our regular federal tax deductions for our tax amortizable intangible assets are limited for the five year period after this ownership change.&nbsp; We are
currently assessing the impact of this limitation including any amounts that may be owed to us by Continental.&nbsp; If amounts are recoverable from Continental, it may decrease the valuation allowance recorded as of December 31, 2008.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our tax agreement increases our dependence on Continental&rsquo;s financial condition.&nbsp; If it is determined that any of the tax benefits related to the basis
increase should not have been available at the time of utilization and, as a result, we are required to pay additional taxes, interest and penalties, then we could be adversely affected if Continental were unable to indemnify us under the agreement.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; For further disclosures related to income taxes, please refer to Note 10 &ndash; Income Taxes in the Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements in Item 8.
&ldquo;Financial Statements and Supplementary Data.&rdquo;</font></p>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><b><i><br clear="all" />
</i></b></font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>Purchase Commitments</u></font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, we have options for 50 ERJ-145XR aircraft that may be exercised for other types of aircraft within the ERJ-145 Family.&nbsp; Our next option
exercise date is April 1, 2009.&nbsp; If we do not exercise or extend our option as of this date, 25 options will expire.&nbsp; During 2005, Continental declined the right to include any of the option aircraft under the Continental CPA.&nbsp; We retain the right to
exercise the option and fly these aircraft for other airlines or under our own code, subject to some restrictions; however, we will have to finance our acquisition of these aircraft independently.&nbsp; Currently, we do not have any firm commitments for aircraft
purchases.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Prior to December 2005, under our power-by-the-hour agreement with Rolls Royce, we were obligated to acquire up to three spare engines to support our existing aircraft
and the remaining eight aircraft then on firm order.&nbsp; In December 2005, we negotiated the sale of eight engines to Rolls Royce and, in exchange, entered into seven new engine leases with a Rolls Royce subsidiary.&nbsp; The engines leased have greater
interchangeability than the engines sold. As a result, we have satisfied our engine obligations and are no longer obligated to purchase the three engines.&nbsp; These leases are classified as operating leases; hence they are not reflected as assets and liabilities on
our balance sheet.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We also have other contractual obligations of approximately $0.8 billion under our power-by-the-hour contracts with various service providers.&nbsp; The
power-by-the-hour contracts dictate the method by which we pay a vendor based on our actual level of operations in exchange for vendor coverage on specific parts and equipment on our aircraft when those parts and equipment are in need of repair or replacement.&nbsp;
Each contract varies in term and payment procedure.&nbsp; The estimated amount of our future commitment is based on assumptions related to future level of operations and forecasted payment rates.&nbsp; Our level of operations is determined based on
Continental&rsquo;s most recent operating plan for us, which can be altered at Continental&rsquo;s sole discretion, and our estimates for the 30 aircraft we have re-deployed.&nbsp; Forecasted payment rates are based on actual rates as of January 1, 2009 and increased
annually according to the particular inflation indices detailed in each contract.&nbsp; Contractual rate increases at actual time of occurrence may be different than the forecasted rates.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; For the year ended December 31, 2008, we spent $10.3 on capital expenditures.&nbsp; In 2009, we anticipate spending between $2 million and $5 million in capital
expenditures of which approximately $1.5 million relate to the rollover of 2008 capital projects.&nbsp; We expect to fund our future capital commitments substantially through internally generated funds.&nbsp; However, there can be no assurance that sufficient
financing will be available for all aircraft and other capital expenditures not covered by firm financing commitments.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> Off-Balance Sheet Arrangements</b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> In the ordinary course of business, we enter into operating leases related to our aircraft, spare engines and facilities.&nbsp; In accordance with U.S.
generally accepted accounting principles, these arrangements are not reflected on our balance sheet; however, they are reasonably likely to have a material effect on our future financial statements and financial outlook.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We enter into these arrangements to gain access to aircraft, equipment and facilities without requiring significant capital up front.&nbsp; Since these assets are used
in connection with our consolidated operations, these assets are required to generate substantially all of our passenger revenue.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; If Continental terminated the Continental CPA for cause, it would have the right to terminate our leases or subleases for aircraft covered by the agreement and take
possession of them.&nbsp; In addition, Continental would have the ability to reject the leases and subleases on our aircraft if it filed for bankruptcy protection.&nbsp; Moreover, with the reduction notice and Continental&rsquo;s ability to terminate the Continental
CPA, we could lose access to some or substantially all of our airport facilities. See Item 1A. &ldquo;Risk Factors&rdquo; for additional information.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Aircraft Leases.</i></b>&nbsp; Our aircraft leases and subleases expire between 2013 and 2022.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, our 2009 expected total minimum
annual rental payments under current and future non-cancelable aircraft operating leases for aircraft used in our Corporate Aviation division are approximately $21.9 million.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Continental is responsible for the remaining lease payments on the 214 aircraft we operate for them under the terms of the Amended Continental CPA.&nbsp; Over 90% of our
aircraft are leased directly by Continental from third parties and subleased by Continental to us.&nbsp; If Continental were to default under these leases, our ability to retain access to the aircraft could be adversely affected.&nbsp; See more detailed description
of our risks related to our aircraft leases under Item 1A. "Risk Factors."</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Other Leases.</i></b>&nbsp; Other leases and subleases are primarily related to ground facilities (airport and maintenance) spare engines, and a flight training
device.&nbsp; These leases have greatly varying terms, which we expect, in most cases, to be renewed or replaced.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, our expected total minimum annual, non-aircraft rental payments for 2009 under current and future non-cancelable operating
leases are approximately $14.2 million. The expected total minimum rental payments for 2009, by category, are as follows (in millions):</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(1)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Following the completion of the tender offer related to our convertible debt in August 2008 and subsequent bond repurchases in the fourth quarter of 2008, $60.8 million aggregate principal of our then 4.25% Convertible Notes due 2023
remained outstanding.&nbsp; As provided in the amended indenture governing the notes, such notes have become our 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023 with an additional repurchase date on August 1, 2011.&nbsp; The expected impact of our 11.25% Convertible
Secured Notes due 2023 on our future cash flows assumes the current principal balance of the notes will be redeemed on August 1, 2011, the earliest date the holders of the notes may require us to repurchase the notes.&nbsp; If the notes are held until August 1, 2023,
the maturity date, our obligations outlined above would increase by $82.1 million as a result of additional interest expense related to these notes.&nbsp; See Item 8.&nbsp; &ldquo;Financial Statements and Supplementary Data &ndash; Note to Consolidated Financial
Statements &ndash; Note 9 &ndash; Long-term Debt&rdquo; for a detailed description of these notes.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(2)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Other long-term debt represents our obligation for the advances received under the EDC Loans.&nbsp; See detailed discussion of our financing arrangement with EDC in Item 8. &rdquo;Financial Statement and Supplementary Data &ndash; Notes
to Consolidated Financial Statements &ndash; Note 9 &ndash; Long-term Debt.&rdquo;&nbsp; The expected effect of our financing arrangement with EDC on our future cash flows is calculated based on the six-month LIBOR plus 1.75% per annum and includes principal payments
of $9.3 million and estimated interest payments of $0.7 million.&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(3)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Aircraft operating lease obligations are the estimated lease payments for the 30 aircraft under long-term operating leases and subleases from Continental as of December 31, 2008. These agreements with Continental have substantially the
same terms as the lease agreements between Continental and the third-party lessors, and expire between 2013 and 2022, however, lease obligations are only assumed through the end of the Amended Continental CPA on June 30, 2015.&nbsp; Consistent with the Amended
Continental CPA, lease payments for the 214 covered aircraft will be incurred directly by Continental.&nbsp; Lease obligations for the remaining 30 aircraft operating outside of the CPA are reflected above at reduced rental rates.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(4)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Other operating lease obligations represent the estimated lease payments for our ground service equipment, spare engines and substantially all of our ground facilities, including facilities at public airports, from Continental or the
municipalities or agencies owning and controlling such airports that are under operating leases.&nbsp; Other operating lease obligations also include the lease payments related to a flight training device.&nbsp; Continued operations are assumed through normal lease
renewals.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(5)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Other contractual obligations primarily include our power-by-the-hour agreement with Rolls Royce.&nbsp; We expect to fund this commitment with cash generated from operations.&nbsp; The estimated amount of future commitments for Rolls
Royce is based on assumptions related to anticipated future levels of operations and forecasted payment rates.&nbsp; The level of operations inherent in the estimated amounts for Rolls Royce is based on Continental&rsquo;s most recent operating plan for Airlines,
which can be altered at Continental&rsquo;s sole discretion and includes our 30 aircraft that are operating in our other lines of business.&nbsp; Contractual rate increases at actual time of occurrence may be different than the forecasted rate inherent in the amounts
for Rolls Royce.&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The actual effects that the listed obligations above may have on our future cash flow may differ materially from our estimates.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> Other Contingent Liabilities or Commitments</b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We are a party to many contracts in which it is common for us to agree to indemnify third parties for tort liabilities that arise out of or relate to the subject matter
of the contract. &nbsp; In some cases, this indemnity extends to related liabilities arising from the negligence of the indemnified parties, but usually excludes any liabilities caused by gross negligence or willful misconduct.&nbsp; We cannot estimate the potential
amount of future payments under these indemnities until events arise that would trigger a liability under the indemnities.&nbsp; However, we expect that we would be covered by insurance for any such liabilities, subject to deductibles.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We are a defendant in various lawsuits and proceedings arising in the ordinary course of our business.&nbsp; While the outcome of these lawsuits and proceedings cannot
be predicted with certainty, we do not believe that the ultimate disposition of these proceedings will have a material adverse effect on our financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="item7a"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Item 7A.&nbsp; Quantitative and Qualitative Disclosure About Market Risk</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We have been and are subject to market risks, including commodity price risk (such as, to a limited extent, aircraft fuel prices) and interest rate risk.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="aircraftfule"></a><b><u><font size="2" face="Arial">Aircraft Fuel</font></u></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> <font size="2">Prior to July 1, 2008, Continental provided all of our aircraft fuel needs for the aircraft covered by the original Continental CPA, and we
incurred fuel expense and fuel tax equal to the lower of the actual cost of the fuel and the related taxes or agreed-upon caps of 66.0 cents and 5.2 cents per gallon, respectively.&nbsp; As a result, our cost of fuel was 71.2 cents per gallon for the six months ended
June 30, 2008.&nbsp; Under the Amended Continental CPA, Continental is responsible for the cost of providing fuel for all flights and, therefore, effective July 1, 2008, fuel expense is no longer included in our statements of operations for aircraft flying within
this arrangement.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; For the</font> <font size="2">year</font> <font size="2">ended</font> <font size="2">December</font> <font size="2">3</font><font size="2">1</font><font size="2">, 2008,
Airlines&rsquo; consolidated fuel cost, including related fuel taxes, was $1.32 per gallon.&nbsp; This is due primarily to the changes stated in the Amended Continental CPA.&nbsp; See fuel discussion at &ldquo;2008 Amended Continental CPA&rdquo; above.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="interestrates"></a><b><u><font size="2" face="Arial">Interest Rates</font></u></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> <font size="2">We have potential interest rate exposure with respect to our loan agreement with Export Development Canada, which bears interest at the six-month
LIBOR plus 1.75% per annum.&nbsp; The interest rate applicable to this variable rate note may rise, increasing our interest expense.&nbsp; The impact of market risk is estimated using a hypothetical increase in interest rates by 100 basis points for our variable rate
long-term debt.&nbsp; Based on this hypothetical assumption, any additional amounts incurred in interest expense for 2008 would not be material.&nbsp; For 2007 and 2006, we would have incurred an additional $0.1 million and $0.2 million in interest expense,
respectively.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008 and December 31, 2007, we estimated the fair value of our $60.8 million and $134.7 million (carrying values) convertible notes to be $38.9
million and $130.7 million, respectively, based upon a fair valuation model that considered quoted market prices.&nbsp; Changes in the fair market value of our fixed-rate debt could be affected by a variety of factors including general investor behavior, industry
specific risks and interest rate risks.&nbsp; Holders of this debt had the right to require that we repurchase their notes on August 1, 2008.&nbsp; On that date we satisfied $59.7 million in aggregate principal of outstanding notes that had been validly tendered.
Following the completion of the tender offer, $68.5 million aggregate principal of our then 4.25% Convertible Notes due 2023 remained outstanding.&nbsp; Additionally, as provided in the amended indenture governing the notes, the coupon associated with the notes
increased from 4.25% to 11.25% which results in an approximate $2.3 million increase in interest expense on an annual basis.&nbsp; In accordance with EITF 96-19, we recorded a discount $27.8 million to reflect the $68.5 million aggregate principal of our convertible
notes at their fair market value of $40.7 million.&nbsp; The $27.8 million discount is being accreted to interest expense until the first available repurchase date on August 1, 2011 in conjunction with $2.0 million of capitalized fees associated with the convertible
debt refinancing.&nbsp; In 2008 we purchased $6.5 million par value of our Original 4.25% Convertible Notes due 2023 and $7.6 million par value (book value of $4.5 million) of our 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023 for $10.8 million resulting in a net realized
gain of $.2 million.&nbsp; Subsequent to these repurchases our interest expense related to the debt discount described above will be $8.2 million annually through August 2011.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p align="center"><a name="reportofmanagement"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">REPORT OF MANAGEMENT<br />
</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">The Board of Directors and Stockholders of<br />
ExpressJet Holdings, Inc.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Management is responsible for the preparation and fair presentation of the financial statements included in this report.&nbsp; The financial statements have been
prepared in conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles and reflect management&rsquo;s judgments and estimates concerning effects of events and transactions that are accounted for and disclosed.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Management is also responsible for establishing and maintaining adequate internal control over financial reporting as defined in Rules 13a -15(f) and 15d - 15(f) under
the Securities Exchange Act of 1934.&nbsp; The internal control over financial reporting of ExpressJet Holdings, Inc. (the &ldquo;Company&rdquo;) is designed to provide reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the preparation of
financial statements for external purposes in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles.&nbsp; The Company&rsquo;s internal control over financial reporting includes those policies and procedures that:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(i)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">pertain to the maintenance of records that, in reasonable detail, accurately and fairly reflect the transactions and dispositions of assets of the Company;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(ii)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">provide reasonable assurance that transactions are recorded as necessary to permit preparation of financial statements in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles, and that receipts and expenditures of the Company
are being made only in accordance with authorizations of management and directors of the Company; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(iii)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Provide reasonable assurance regarding prevention or timely detection of unauthorized acquisition, use or disposition of the Company&rsquo;s assets that could have a material effect on the financial statements.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Management recognizes that there are inherent limitations in the effectiveness of any internal control over financial reporting, including the possibility of human error
and the circumvention or overriding of internal control.&nbsp; Accordingly, even effective internal control over financial reporting can provide only reasonable assurance with respect to financial statement preparations and may not prevent or detect
misstatements.&nbsp; Also, projections of any evaluation of effectiveness to future periods are subject to the risk that controls may become inadequate because of changes in conditions, or that the degree of compliance with the policies or procedures may
deteriorate.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Under the supervision and with the participation of our management, including our Chief Executive Officer and Chief Financial Officer, we conducted an evaluation of the
effectiveness of our internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2008 based on the framework in Internal Control &mdash; Integrated Framework issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission.&nbsp; Based on that
evaluation, our management concluded that our internal control over financial reporting was effective as of December 31, 2008.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Management&rsquo;s assessment of the effectiveness of our internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2008 has been audited by Ernst &amp; Young, LLP,
an independent registered public accounting firm, as stated in their report which is included elsewhere herein.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p align="center"><a name="reportofindependentpublicacctg"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">REPORT OF INDEPENDENT REGISTERED PUBLIC ACCOUNTING FIRM<br />
</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">The Board of Directors and Shareholders of<br />
ExpressJet Holdings, Inc.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We have audited the accompanying consolidated balance sheets of ExpressJet Holdings, Inc. (the &ldquo;Company&rdquo;) as of December 31, 2008 and 2007, and the related
consolidated statements of operations, stockholders&rsquo; equity and cash flows for each of the three years in the period ended December 31, 2008. These financial statements are the responsibility of the Company&rsquo;s management. Our responsibility is to express
an opinion on these financial statements based on our audits.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We conducted our audits in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States). Those standards require that we plan and
perform the audit to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements are free of material misstatement. An audit includes examining, on a test basis, evidence supporting the amounts and disclosures in the financial statements.&nbsp; An audit also
includes assessing the accounting principles used and significant estimates made by management, as well as evaluating the overall financial statement presentation. We believe that our audits provide a reasonable basis for our opinion.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In our opinion, the financial statements referred to above, present fairly, in all material respects, the consolidated financial position of the Company as of December
31, 2008 and 2007, and the consolidated results of its operations and its cash flows for each of the three years in the period ended December 31, 2008, in conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles<b>.</b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We have also audited, in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States), the Company&rsquo;s internal control over
financial reporting as of December 31, 2008, based on criteria established in Internal Control &ndash; Integrated Framework issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission and our report dated February 27, 2009 expressed an unqualified
opinion thereon.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>
