<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="reportofindependentpublicacctg2"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">REPORT OF INDEPENDENT REGISTERED PUBLIC ACCOUNTING FIRM</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">The Board of Directors and Shareholders of<br />
 ExpressJet Holdings, Inc.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">We have audited ExpressJet Holdings, Inc.&rsquo;s internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2008, based on criteria established in Internal Control&mdash;Integrated Framework issued by the Committee of Sponsoring
Organizations of the Treadway Commission (the COSO criteria). ExpressJet Holdings Inc.&rsquo;s management is responsible for maintaining effective internal control over financial reporting, and for its assessment of the effectiveness of internal control over
financial reporting included in the accompanying Report of Management. Our responsibility is to express an opinion on the company&rsquo;s internal control over financial reporting based on our audit.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">We conducted our audit in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States). Those standards require that we plan and perform the audit to obtain reasonable assurance about whether effective
internal control over financial reporting was maintained in all material respects. Our audit included obtaining an understanding of internal control over financial reporting, assessing the risk that a material weakness exists, testing and evaluating the design and
operating effectiveness of internal control based on the assessed risk, and performing such other procedures as we considered necessary in the circumstances. We believe that our audit provides a reasonable basis for our opinion.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">A company&rsquo;s internal control over financial reporting is a process designed to provide reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the preparation of financial statements for external purposes in
accordance with generally accepted accounting principles. A company&rsquo;s internal control over financial reporting includes those policies and procedures that (1) pertain to the maintenance of records that, in reasonable detail, accurately and fairly reflect the
transactions and dispositions of the assets of the company; (2) provide reasonable assurance that transactions are recorded as necessary to permit preparation of financial statements in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles, and that receipts and
expenditures of the company are being made only in accordance with authorizations of management and directors of the company; and (3) provide reasonable assurance regarding prevention or timely detection of unauthorized acquisition, use, or disposition of the
company&rsquo;s assets that could have a material effect on the financial statements.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Because of its inherent limitations, internal control over financial reporting may not prevent or detect misstatements.&nbsp; Also, projections of any evaluation of effectiveness to future periods are subject to the risk that controls
may become inadequate because of changes in conditions, or that the degree of compliance with the policies or procedures may deteriorate.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">In our opinion, ExpressJet Holdings, Inc. maintained, in all material respects, effective internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2008, based on the COSO criteria.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">We also have audited, in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States), the consolidated balance sheets of ExpressJet Holdings, Inc. as of December 31, 2008 and 2007, and the related
consolidated statements of operations, stockholders&rsquo; equity, and cash flows for each of the three years in the period ended December 31, 2008 of ExpressJet Holdings, Inc. and our report dated February 27, 2009 expressed an unqualified opinion
thereon.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

"Times">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p align="center"><b><font size="2" face="Arial">EXPRESSJET HOLDINGS, INC<br />
<a name="notestoconsolidatedfinancialstatements"></a>NOTES TO CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> <font size="2">ExpressJet Holdings, Inc. (&ldquo;Holdings&rdquo;) is engaged in the business of transporting people.&nbsp; Our principal asset is all of the
issued and outstanding shares of stock of XJT Holdings, Inc., the sole stockholder of ExpressJet Airlines, Inc. (referred to in this report as &ldquo;Airlines&rdquo; and, together with Holdings, as &ldquo;ExpressJet&rdquo;, &ldquo;we&rdquo; or
&ldquo;us&rdquo;).&nbsp; Airlines currently operates a fleet of 244 aircraft.&nbsp; <font color="black">As of December 31, 2008, our fleet was assigned as follows:</font></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">214 aircraft for Continental Airlines (&ldquo;Continental&rdquo;) as Continental Express pursuant to a capacity purchase agreement (the &ldquo;Continental CPA&rdquo;); and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">30 aircraft in our Corporate Aviation division, which is dedicated to charter contracts and ad-hoc charter service;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> Our primary business is flying 244 aircraft under contractual arrangements for network carriers or entities desiring cost-effective and fully
customizable group travel.&nbsp; <font color="black">During 2008 we dramatically reshaped our business in order to adapt to the unprecedented high fuel costs, recessions in the global economy, reduction in air-travel capacity, and other uncertainties facing the
regional airlines, including execution of an agreement with Continental to amend the existing Continental CPA, effective July 1, 2008, (the &ldquo;Amended Continental CPA&rdquo;) at lower block hour rates.&nbsp;</font> Under the terms of the Amended Continental CPA,
we are not reimbursed for certain costs, primarily fuel, aircraft rent and certain ground handling services, which were previously recorded as revenue.&nbsp; <font color="black">We completed most of our transition to the contractually-arranged flying during the
fourth quarter ended December 31, 2008.&nbsp; Additionally, we strengthened our balance sheet through the completion of the refinancing of our convertible debt, reducing the debt obligation from $134.7 million as of December 31, 2007, to $60.8 million as of December
31, 2008.&nbsp; We stabilized the use of operating cash, as a result of the suspension of our Branded Flying operations.</font> &nbsp; Furthermore, we mutually agreed with Delta Air Lines (&ldquo;Delta&rdquo;) to suspend our capacity purchase agreement (the
&ldquo;Delta CPA&rdquo;) and pro-rate flying agreements (the &ldquo;Delta Prorate&rdquo;) effective September 2, 2008. With the suspension of these flying, we anticipate generating cash from our contractual arrangements with Continental and other entities for group
travel.&nbsp; As a result of these changes, and the different basis in reimbursable costs under the Amended Continental CPA, the financial statements between periods are not comparable.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We also provide aviation services, such as ground-handling at airport locations across the United States, as well as aircraft repair, overhaul, interior
refurbishments and paint, through our three wholly-owned subsidiaries, which include ExpressJet Services, LLC (&ldquo;ExpressJet Services&rdquo;), American Composites, LLC (&ldquo;American Composites&rdquo;) and InTech Aerospace Services, LP (&ldquo;InTech&rdquo;)
and our, and majority owned subsidiary, Saltillo Jet Center (&ldquo;Saltillo&rdquo;).&nbsp; During the first half of 2007, we rebranded American Composites, InTech and Saltillo resulting in each doing business under the &ldquo;ExpressJet Services&rdquo; trade
name.&nbsp; These entities are collectively referred to herein as &ldquo;Services.&rdquo;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Holdings was incorporated in Delaware in August 1996.&nbsp; Airlines is one of the largest regional airlines in the world, based on 2008 available seat miles, number of
regional jets and passengers transported.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<b><font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font></b>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Note 1 &ndash; Summary of Significant Accounting Policies</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>(a) Principles of Consolidation</i> &ndash;</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The accompanying consolidated financial statements have been prepared in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles and include the accounts of
Holdings and its subsidiaries.&nbsp; All material intercompany transactions have been eliminated in consolidation.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On August 31, 2006, ExpressJet purchased the remaining 51% interest in American Composites, an aviation maintenance business in Miami, Florida, for $0.8 million in cash
and the results of operations were consolidated in our financial statements beginning on September 1, 2006.&nbsp; Prior to this date, we accounted for this investment under the equity method of accounting as prescribed by Accounting Principles Board Opinion No. 18
&ndash; &ldquo;The Equity Method of Accounting for Investments in Common Stock.&rdquo;&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During 2006, we invested $1.5 million for an 80% interest in Saltillo, an aircraft paint facility located in Saltillo, Mexico.&nbsp; We invested $9.2 million for the
construction of the hangar and office facilities from which the company conducts its operations.&nbsp; As a result, we consolidated Saltillo beginning on August 1, 2006.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>(b) Use of Estimates</i> &ndash;</b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The preparation of financial statements in conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles requires us to make estimates and assumptions that affect the
amounts reported in the financial statements and accompanying notes.&nbsp; Actual results could differ from those estimates.&nbsp;</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><b><br clear="all" />
</b></font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>(c) Cash and Cash Equivalents</i> &ndash;</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cash and cash equivalents consist of cash and short-term, highly liquid investments that are readily convertible into cash and have maturities of three months or less
when purchased.&nbsp; Restricted cash is our collateral for estimated future workers&rsquo; compensation claims, letters of credit, charter deposits and holdbacks with our credit card processors.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cash flows provided by or used in operations for the years ended December 31, 2008, 2007 and 2006 are as follows:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>(d) Short-term Investments &ndash;</i></b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Short-term investments are comprised of auction-rate securities (&ldquo;ARS&rdquo;) which are primarily backed by student loans that are guaranteed by the U.S.
government.&nbsp; Our ARS are reflected at fair value using a discounted cash flow valuation model.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008 we estimated the fair value of our ARS to be $41.4 million.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (e) Accounts Receivables, net &ndash;</font></i></b></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Accounts receivable are stated at the historical carrying amount net of write-offs and allowance for uncollectible accounts.&nbsp; Our allowance for uncollectible
accounts at the end of 2008 and 2007 was $0.7 million and $0.4 million.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>(f) Spare Parts and Supplies, net &ndash;</i></font></b></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> Inventories, expendable parts and supplies relating to flight equipment are carried at average acquisition cost and are expensed when used.&nbsp; An
allowance for obsolescence is provided over the remaining estimated useful life of the related aircraft, plus allowances for spare parts currently identified as excess to reduce the carrying costs to the lower of amortized cost or net realizable value.&nbsp; These
allowances are based on our estimates, which are subject to change.&nbsp; Our allowance for obsolescence as of December 31, 2008 and 2007 was $12.9 million and $11.5 million, respectively.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>(g) Property and Equipment &ndash;</i></font></b></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> Property and equipment are recorded at cost and are depreciated to estimated residual values over their estimated useful lives using the straight-line
method.&nbsp; Property and equipment acquired under capital leases are recorded at the lower of the present value of the future minimum lease payments or the fair value of the asset at the inception of the lease.&nbsp; The estimated useful lives and residual values
for our property and equipment are as follows:</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Amortization related to assets under capital leases and operating leasehold improvements is included in our depreciation and amortization expense on the income
statement.&nbsp; We amortize assets under capital leases and operating leasehold improvements over the shorter of the asset life or lease term.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In accordance with Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No. 144 &ndash; &ldquo;Accounting for the Impairment or Disposal of Long-Lived Assets,&rdquo; we record
impairment losses on long&ndash;lived assets used in operations when events and circumstances indicate that the assets might be impaired and the undiscounted cash flows estimated to be generated by those assets are less than the carrying amount of those assets.&nbsp;
The net carrying value of assets not recoverable is reduced to fair value.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>

<td valign="bottom" bgcolor="#e0e0e0">
<p align="right"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">244</font></p>
</td>

<td valign="bottom"></td>

<td valign="bottom">
<div align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All 244 aircraft were placed in service prior to 2007.&nbsp; Our next option exercise date is April 1, 2009.&nbsp; If we do not exercise or extend our option as of this
date, 25 options will expire.&nbsp; Pursuant to our agreement with Embraer, the 50 options may be exercised for any type of aircraft within the ERJ-145 line of aircraft, which include the ERJ-145 Family, at our discretion.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>(h) Intangible and Other Assets &ndash;</i></font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> Reorganization Value in Excess of Amounts Allocable to Identifiable Assets (&ldquo;goodwill&rdquo;) represents primarily the amount that arose from
Continental&rsquo;s emergence from bankruptcy reorganization in 1993.&nbsp; Effective January 1, 2002, we adopted and began to account for this asset in accordance with Statement of Financial Accounting Standard No. 142&ndash;&ldquo;Goodwill and Other Intangible
Assets&rdquo; (&ldquo;SFAS 142&rdquo;).&nbsp; SFAS 142 requires testing of goodwill and intangible assets with indefinite lives for impairment rather than amortizing them.&nbsp; Our goodwill is related to our Contract Flying segment.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We evaluate the carrying value of this asset each reporting period to determine whether events and circumstances continue to support an indefinite useful life.&nbsp; We
perform an impairment review on an annual basis, or more frequently if events or changes in circumstances indicate that the asset may be impaired.&nbsp; Our annual impairment test, which is performed as of June 30 of each year, includes the acquisition,
market-multiple and income approaches to valuation.&nbsp; If this review indicates that our goodwill will not be recoverable, the carrying value is reduced to the fair value.&nbsp; During 2008 we determined our goodwill was fully impaired due to the restructuring of
our agreement with Continental and recorded a non-cash charge of $12.8 million.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Airport operating rights, the rights to use certain take-off and landing slots and gates, are amortized on a straight-line basis over the life of the related airport
facility lease, which approximates 20 years, with no residual value.&nbsp; During 2008 we sold the Airport operating rights at net book value.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Capitalized costs related to our senior convertible notes is amortized on a straight-line basis through August 2011, the first date at which we may be required to
repurchase the notes, with no residual value.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><b><br clear="all" />
</b></font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>(i) Investments in Other Entities &ndash;</i></font></b></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Investments in unconsolidated companies are accounted for by the equity method of accounting when we have significant influence over the operation of the companies as
prescribed by Accounting Principles Board Opinion No. 18 &ndash; &ldquo;The Equity Method of Accounting for Investments in Common Stock&rdquo; (&ldquo;ABP 18&rdquo;).&nbsp; We review our investments in unconsolidated affiliates for impairment whenever events or
changes in business circumstances indicate that the carrying amount of the investments may not be fully recoverable. Evidence of a loss in value that is other than temporary might include the length of time and extent to which the fair value of the investment has
been less than the carrying amount of the equity investment, the near and longer-term operating and financial prospects of the entity and our longer-term intent of retaining the investment in the entity. Management&rsquo;s assessment as to whether any decline in
value is other than temporary is based on our ability and intent to hold the investment and whether evidence indicating the carrying value of the investment is recoverable within a reasonable period of time outweighs evidence to the contrary.&nbsp; If the fair value
of the investment is determined to be less than the carrying value and the decline in value is considered to be other than temporary, an appropriate write-down is recorded based on the excess of the carrying value over the best estimate of fair value of the
investment.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>(j) Deferred Credits &ndash;</i></font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our spare part and flight training credits are primarily derived from our purchase agreement with Embraer.&nbsp; All spare part credits are used to offset the purchase
price of initial spare parts provisioning for our newly delivered aircraft.&nbsp; Similarly, the flight training credits are used to pay for the initial simulator rent costs for our pilots.&nbsp; These credits are recorded in long-term liabilities, with an offsetting
entry to prepayments and other current assets or current accrued liabilities if we used more credits than the amount we are entitled to at year-end.&nbsp; The deferred credits are amortized as a reduction to our aircraft rent expense over the life of the associated
aircraft lease.&nbsp; Amortization totaled $0.5 million and $0.9 million for 2008 and 2007, respectively.&nbsp; The prepayments and other current assets or current accrued liabilities are reduced as the credits are used or as the remaining firm order aircraft are
delivered.&nbsp; Due to the transition in our business model, we wrote off $7.9 million in deferred credits in 2008.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>(k) Operating Revenue &ndash;</i></font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Passenger Revenue.&nbsp;</font></i></b> <font size="2">Prior to July 1, 2008, we were entitled to receive payment for each block hour that Continental scheduled us
to fly pursuant to the terms of the Continental CPA.&nbsp; Payment was based on a formula designed to provide Airlines with a target operating margin of 10% before taking into account variations in certain costs and expenses that were generally within our
control.&nbsp; We had exposure for most labor costs and some maintenance and general administrative expenses if actual costs were higher than those budgeted in our block hour rates.&nbsp; For the first six months of 2008, we recognized revenues using 2007 block hour
rates, pursuant to our agreement with Continental reached in June 2008.&nbsp; Under the Amended Continental CPA, certain costs are no longer reimbursable (primarily fuel, rent and certain ground handling costs), and therefore such items are presented net in the
accompanying Consolidate Results of Operations from the periods July 1, 2008 forward.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In June 2008, we reached an agreement with Continental to amend the existing Continental CPA.&nbsp; Under the Amended Continental CPA, which became effective July 1,
2008, we recognize revenue based on fixed contractual rates.&nbsp; See &ldquo;&ndash; Note 2 &ndash; Contract Flying&rdquo; for further details regarding the Continental CPA.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Under the Delta CPA, <font color="black">we received a base rate for each completed block hour and departure and were reimbursed for certain pass-through costs.&nbsp; We
recorded the base rate and the reimbursements for pass-through costs as passenger revenue.&nbsp; Effective September 2, 2008, we mutually agreed with Delta to terminate this agreement.</font></font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Effective September 2, 2008, we terminated our branded flying operations.&nbsp; Prior to September 2, 2008, tickets for Branded Flying were sold and processed
internally, with amounts due settled either by cash payments up front or pursuant to the terms of our agreements with various credit card service vendors.&nbsp; Additionally, we accepted flight coupons to carry passengers on our aircraft from other air carriers,
which were then processed internally and settled on a monthly basis through an airline clearing house, as appropriate, or pursuant to the terms of various industry or codeshare agreements, such as the Delta Prorate Agreement.&nbsp; <font color="black">We recognized
passenger revenue when transportation was provided or when an unused ticket expired.&nbsp; Nonrefundable tickets expired on the date of the intended flight, unless the date was extended by notification from the customer in advance of the intended flight.&nbsp; As of
December 31, 2008, obligations related to our branded flying air traffic liability have been satisfied.&nbsp; For the year ended December 31, 2007, the amount of passenger ticket sales not yet recognized as revenue is included in our consolidated balance sheets as
air traffic liability</font>. &nbsp; Amounts receivable from other air carriers under interline agreements were $1.3 million and $2.6 million as of December 31, 2008 and 2007, respectively.&nbsp; We recognized $18 million in revenue as a result of the cessation of
operations due to the adjustments to our air traffic liability, frequent flier liability and certain termination payments.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our Corporate Aviation customers typically prepay flights based on estimated charges to be incurred.&nbsp; Such prepayments are held in escrow and recorded as restricted
cash and deferred revenue until the flights have operated.&nbsp; At that time we recognize the associated revenue and release the funds from escrow.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We are also required to collect certain taxes and fees from the passengers on behalf of government agencies and remit these back to the applicable agency on a periodic
basis.&nbsp; These taxes and fees include U.S. federal transportation taxes, federal security charges, and airport passenger facility charges.&nbsp; These items are collected from our customers at the time they purchase their tickets, but are not included in
passenger revenue.&nbsp; We record a liability upon collection from the customer and release the liability when payments are remitted to the applicable governmental agency.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ground Handling and Other</font></i></b>.&nbsp; We recognize our non-passenger revenue, ground handling and other revenues as services are provided.&nbsp;</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (l) Segment Reporting</font></i> &ndash;</b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> Statement of Financial Accounting Standard No. 131, &ldquo;Disclosures about Segments of an Enterprise and Related Information,&rdquo; (&ldquo;Statement
131&rdquo;) requires disclosures related to components of a company for which separate financial information is available if that segregated information is evaluated regularly by the company&rsquo;s chief operating decision makers in deciding the allocation of
resources and assessing performance.&nbsp; ExpressJet has three major reportable segments:&nbsp; Contract Flying, Branded Flying and Aviation Services.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>(m) Wages, Salaries and Related Expenses &ndash;</i></b></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> As our collective bargaining agreements become amendable, we accrue for anticipated retroactive pay that we estimate will be due under the new
contract.&nbsp; We have three stock-based compensation plans:&nbsp; the ExpressJet Holdings, Inc. 2002 and 2007 Stock Incentive Plans and the ExpressJet Holdings, Inc. 2003 Employee Stock Purchase Plan.&nbsp; The Company accounts for stock-based compensation
utilizing the fair value recognition provisions of SFAS&nbsp;No.&nbsp;123R, &ldquo;Share-Based Payment.&rdquo;&nbsp; See &ldquo;&ndash; Note&nbsp;13 Stock-Based Compensation Plans&rdquo; for further details.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> We are currently self-insured for a portion of our healthcare costs and have a large deductible for our workers compensation liability.&nbsp; Consequently,
reserves for the cost of claims that have not been paid or benefit costs that have been incurred but not yet reported (&ldquo;IBNR&rdquo;) as of a given date are estimated.&nbsp;</p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<b><font size="2" face="Arial"><i><br clear="all" />
</i></font></b>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (n) Aircraft &amp; Facilities Leases &ndash;</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All of our aircraft are either leased or sub-leased from Continental.&nbsp; The Amended Continental CPA changed the way we pay rent for aircraft covered under the
Continental CPA.&nbsp; Effective July 1, 2008, we no longer pay aircraft lease rent to Continental for the 214 aircraft covered under the Amended CPA with Continental.&nbsp; Lease payments to Continental relating to the 30 aircraft removed from the Continental CPA
are at reduced rates.&nbsp; We also have airport and maintenance facility leases that are leased from airport authorities or other municipal authorities.&nbsp; In order to determine the proper classification of a lease as either an operating lease or a capital lease,
we must make certain estimates at the inception of the lease relating to the economic useful life and the fair value of an asset, as well as select an appropriate discount rate to be used in discounting future lease payments. The assumptions used in our lease
classification analyses are based on our interpretation of available market data and specific contract terms.&nbsp; See&rdquo;- Note 8 Leases&rdquo; for further details.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (o) Maintenance and Repair Costs &ndash;</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> Maintenance and repair costs for owned and leased flight equipment, including the overhaul of aircraft components, are charged to operating expense as
incurred, except for those maintenance costs covered by power-by-the-hour agreements, which are expensed based on contractual terms.&nbsp; In 2008 and 2007, power-by-the-hour arrangements represented approximately 71% and 75%, respectively, of our maintenance,
materials and repairs costs.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>(p) Income Taxes &ndash;</i></font></b></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> Deferred income taxes, which are provided under the liability method, are determined based on differences between the financial reporting and income tax
basis of assets and liabilities and are measured using enacted tax rates and laws.&nbsp; Operating losses which are dependent on the generation of future taxable income are recorded as a deferred tax asset. &nbsp; A valuation allowance is provided on deferred tax
assets if, based on available evidence, it is more likely than not that future tax benefits will not be realized.&nbsp; Operating losses for 2007 recorded as a receivable represent the amount which was carried back and applied against previous years&rsquo;
income.&nbsp; See &ldquo;&ndash; Note 10 Income Taxes&rdquo; for further information on income taxes.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>(q) Fair Value Measurements &ndash;</i></font></b></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></b></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i></b> In September 2006, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (&ldquo;FASB&rdquo;) issued FASB Statement No. 157, <i>Fair Value Measurements</i>
(&ldquo;Statement 157&rdquo;), which is effective for fiscal years beginning after November 15, 2007.&nbsp; Statement 157 defines fair value, establishes a framework for measuring fair value and expands disclosures about assets and liabilities measured at fair
value.&nbsp; We adopted the provisions of Statement 157 as of January 1, 2008 for our financial assets and liabilities.&nbsp; The FASB deferred the effective date of Statement 157 for one year as it relates to fair value measurement requirements for nonfinancial
assets and liabilities that are not recognized or disclosed at fair value on a recurring basis until 2009, which we do not expect to impact the Company.&nbsp;</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Statement 157 provides a consistent definition of fair value which focuses on exit price and prioritizes, within a measurement of fair value, the use of market-based
inputs over entity-specific inputs.&nbsp; The standard also establishes a three-level hierarchy for fair value measurements based on the transparency of inputs to the valuation of an asset or liability as of the measurement date.&nbsp;</font> The three tiers of fair
value input are defined below:</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Level 1 &ndash; inputs to the valuation methodology which are quoted prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Level 2 &ndash; inputs to the valuation methodology which are quoted prices in active markets for similar assets or liabilities, quoted prices in markets that are not active; or other inputs that are observable, either directly or
indirectly, for substantially the full term of the assets or liabilities; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Level 3 &ndash; inputs to the valuation methodology which are unobservable and significant to the fair value measurement.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Helvetica"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Helvetica">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, we held cash equivalents and short-term investments of ARS that were required to be measured at fair value.&nbsp; See &ldquo;-Note 5 Fair
Value Measurements&rdquo; for further information on fair value measurements.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (r) Financial Instruments and Risk Management &ndash;</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Financial Instruments.</i></b>&nbsp; Our financial instruments consist of cash and cash equivalents, short-term investments, accounts receivable, accounts payable,
long-term secured debt to Export Development Canada (&ldquo;EDC&rdquo;), note payable to Continental (which has been repaid in full) and 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023.&nbsp; The carrying amount of cash and cash equivalents, short-term investments,
accounts receivable and accounts payable approximate fair value due to the highly liquid nature of these short-term instruments.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008 and 2007, the fair value of the EDC Loans was approximately $7.2 million and $12.4 million,
respectively.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008 and December 31, 2007, we estimated the fair value of our $60.8 million and $134.7 million (carrying value) fixed-rate debt to be $38.9 million and $130.7 million, respectively, based upon quoted market
prices.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Credit Risk Due to Certain Concentrations.</i></b>&nbsp; We provide Continental the majority of its regional jet capacity at its hub airports, as well as
additional non&ndash;hub service.&nbsp; We are economically dependent upon Continental as most of our revenue and cash flows are received from Continental.&nbsp; See Item 1A. &ldquo;Risk Factors&rdquo; for a detailed discussion of this and other risks.&nbsp; If
Continental defaults on the payment obligations it has to us under the Continental CPA or other agreements, then in addition to any other remedies we may have, we can offset the amount of the defaulted payments against the amounts we owe to Continental under any
agreements in an amount corresponding to its defaulted payments.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>(s) Recently Issued Accounting Standards</i> &ndash;</b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In May&nbsp;2008, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB) affirmed the consensus of FASB Staff Position APB 14-1 (FSP APB 14-1), &ldquo;Accounting for
Convertible Debt Instruments That May Be Settled in Cash upon Conversion (Including Partial Cash Settlement)&rdquo;, which applies to all convertible debt instruments that have a &lsquo;&lsquo;net settlement feature&rsquo;&rsquo;, which means that such convertible
debt instruments, by their terms, may be settled either wholly or partially in cash upon conversion.&nbsp; FSP&nbsp;APB 14-1 requires issuers of convertible debt instruments that may be settled wholly or partially in cash upon conversion to separately account for the
liability and equity components in a manner reflective of the issuers&rsquo; nonconvertible debt borrowing rate. FSP APB 14-1 is effective for financial statements issued for fiscal years beginning after December&nbsp;15,&nbsp;2008 and interim periods within those
fiscal years.&nbsp;&nbsp;Early adoption is not permitted and retroactive application to all periods presented is required.&nbsp;&nbsp;The adoption of FSP APB 14-1 will affect the historical accounting for our Original 4.25% Convertible Notes and our 11.25%
Convertible Secured Notes due 2023. &nbsp;We are continuing to evaluate the impact of this standard to our results of operations and financial position however; we expect that the ultimate application of FSP APB 14-1 will result in an increase in interest expense for
the years presented.&nbsp; In addition, the Company is evaluating the impact this standard will have on our 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>(t) Reclassifications &ndash;</i></b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Certain reclassifications have been made in prior years&rsquo; financial statements to conform to the current year presentation, including adjustments to common stock,
additional paid-in capital, and share amounts due to our reverse split (&ldquo;Reverse Split&rdquo;) of our common stock in 2008.&nbsp; In addition, $2.5 million of operating revenue as of December 31, 2006 was reclassed to other operating expenses on the
consolidated statement of operations and a $2.0 million increase in restricted cash was reclassed from net cash provided by operating activities to net cash used in investing activities on the consolidated statement of cash flows for the year ended December 31,
2006.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Note 2 &ndash; Contract Flying&nbsp;</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, we averaged over 950 daily flights in our Contract Flying, offering passenger service to over 130 scheduled destinations in North America,
including Mexico as well as the Caribbean.&nbsp; We generated $1.1 billion of revenue (80.3% of our total consolidated revenue) in this segment.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Continental Capacity Purchase and Other Agreements</i></font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>General</u>.</font></i></b>&nbsp; A significant portion of our revenue and cash flows is attributable to the Continental CPA.&nbsp; Under the Continental CPA,
Airlines operates flights on behalf of Continental as Continental Express.&nbsp; Continental controls and is responsible for scheduling, pricing and managing seat inventories and is entitled to all revenue associated with the operation of the aircraft.&nbsp; We also
have various other agreements with Continental that govern our relationship.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Under the Continental CPA, all marketing-related costs normally associated with operating an airline are borne by Continental.&nbsp; These costs include:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">reservations and
sales;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>

</td>
</tr>

<td valign="top">

</td>
</tr>

<tr>

</td>

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">food and beverage service.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>2008 Amended Continental CPA</u></font></i></b><font size="2">.&nbsp; Prior to July 1, 2008, Airlines was entitled to receive payment for each block hour that
Continental scheduled it to fly pursuant to the terms of the Continental CPA.&nbsp; Payment was based on a formula designed to provide Airlines with a target operating margin of 10% before taking into account variations in certain costs and expenses that were
generally within our control.&nbsp; We had exposure for most labor costs and some maintenance and general administrative expenses if actual costs were higher than those budgeted in our block hour rates.&nbsp; For the first six months of 2008, we recognized revenues
using 2007 block hour rates, pursuant to our agreement with Continental reached in June 2008.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> <font size="2">At such time, we also reached an agreement with Continental to amend the existing Continental CPA.&nbsp; The Amended Continental CPA,
which became effective July 1, 2008, allows us to continue flying, at minimum, 205 aircraft for Continental for seven years while providing Continental the right after one year to reduce the number of aircraft to a minimum of 190 aircraft.<b><i>&nbsp;</i></b> <i>(It
should be noted going forward in our document, we will use the designation, &ldquo;the Continental CPA,&rdquo; for matters that remained same between the original CPA and the Amended Continental CPA; where matters differed between the original CPA and the Amended
Continental CPA, they will be specifically identified to &ldquo;the Amended Continental CPA.&rdquo;)<b></b></i>The Amended Continental CPA significantly reduces Continental&rsquo;s governance rights under the original CPA, including easing change-of-control
limitations on ExpressJet, reducing restrictions on our flying into Continental&rsquo;s hub airports, and removing the most-favored-nation clause, allowing us the option to fly for other carriers and to consider other strategic alternatives.&nbsp; The Amended
Continental CPA also removes Continental&rsquo;s ability to terminate the agreement without cause.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Amended Continental CPA provides payments to us at a pre-determined rate based on block hours flown and reimburses us for various pass-through expenses including
passenger liability insurance, hull insurance, war risk insurance, landing fees and substantially all regional jet engine expenses under current long-term third-party contracts with no margin or mark-up.&nbsp; Under the Amended Continental CPA, Continental is
responsible for the cost of providing fuel for all flights and for paying aircraft rent for all aircraft covered by the Amended Continental CPA and, therefore, these items are not included in our statements of operations for the three month period ended September 30,
2008 and thereafter.&nbsp; The fixed block hour rates are considerably lower than the rates under the original agreement and will be subject to annual escalations tied to a consumer price index (capped at 3.5%) at each anniversary date, July 1.&nbsp; During 2008, we
returned as part of the Amended Continental CPA negotiations, 30 aircraft, with Continental bearing the expense related to the aircraft following their return.&nbsp; <font color="black">We will continue to operate at least 205 aircraft through July 1, 2009.&nbsp;
Beginning on July 1, 2009, Continental can remove up to 15 aircraft making the new minimum aircraft requirement under the agreement 190.&nbsp; Therefore, we will continue to focus on aggressively managing costs in response to the Amended Continental CPA and the
economic difficulties facing the entire airline industry.&nbsp;</font></font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We also entered into a settlement agreement with Continental to release the parties&rsquo; claims at the time of the agreement to amend the then existing capacity
purchase agreement, relating to certain identified payments under such capacity purchase agreement, including disputes previously disclosed as possible matters for arbitration.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In September 2008, we agreed with Continental on the first amendment to the Amended Continental CPA in order to compensate us for our fixed costs, considered in the
calculation of the pre-determined block hour rates, that cannot be reduced as a result of the unanticipated reduction in aircraft utilization by Continental&rsquo;s scheduling. We also agreed that if Continental, beginning in year two, increases its aircraft
utilization above a predetermined threshold, then it may receive discounts on the agreed, pre-determined block hour rates.&nbsp; For the last six months of 2008, we recognized an additional $3.4 million in contract revenues as compensation for shortfalls in aircraft
utilization.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In December 2008, we agreed with Continental on the first second amendment to the Amended Continental CPA in order to clarify certain issues related to our revenue
recognition, the fuel efficiency program in place in connection with the Amended Continental CPA and depreciation related to the aircraft we operate for Continental and excess inventory related thereto.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i><u>Prior Years&rsquo; Settlement of the Continental CPA.</u></i></b>&nbsp; Airlines was entitled to receive payment for each block hour that Continental scheduled
it to fly.&nbsp; Payment was based on a formula designed to provide Airlines with a target operating margin before taking into account variations in certain costs and expenses that were generally within our control.&nbsp; We had exposure for most labor costs and some
maintenance and general administrative expenses if actual costs were higher than those budgeted in our block hour rates.&nbsp; Prior years&rsquo; payment methodologies are described in the following paragraphs.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b>2005-2007.</b> &nbsp; As part of the 2005 rate negotiations, we agreed to cap Airlines&rsquo; prevailing margin at 10.0% in an attempt to ensure the long-term
stability of the Continental CPA.&nbsp; Airlines also began including previously unreconciled costs, as discussed above, within the margin band, although it was not reimbursed if these costs are higher and cause its prevailing margin to fall below the 8.5% margin
floor.&nbsp; Airlines remained entitled to receive incentive payments from Continental if its rate of controllable cancellations was lower than its historical benchmark, but was no longer required to pay Continental a penalty for controllable cancellations unless the
rate rises above 0.5%. &nbsp; Airlines continued to receive a small per-passenger fee and incentive payments for certain on-time departure and baggage handling performance.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

Continental CPA from January 1, 2005 to June 30, 2008.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2007, the fully reconciled costs and costs within the margin band under the Continental CPA represented approximately 59% and 40% of operating costs associated with
Continental CPA flying, respectively, in addition to 1% of costs related to the Continental CPA which could not be included in either reimbursable grouping such as certain labor and arbitration costs.&nbsp; In 2006, the fully reconciled costs and costs within the
margin band under the Continental CPA represented approximately 63% and 35% of operating costs associated with Continental CPA flying, respectively.&nbsp; The remaining 2% of operating costs in 2006 were incurred outside of the Continental CPA in order to support our
diversification strategies for the 69 aircraft released from the Continental CPA as well as the administrative operations we assumed from Continental in 2007.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />

the prevailing margin to be greater than 10.0%.&nbsp; However, if the differences cause the prevailing margin to be less than 8.5%, they remain unreconciled.&nbsp; These costs are:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> 2007 Arbitration<i>.</i></b>&nbsp; In 2006, Continental challenged our interpretation of the Continental CPA and sought to impose rates for 2007 that we
believed were inconsistent with the methodology established in the agreement.&nbsp; We were unable to agree on the 2007 rates and, in accordance with the terms of the Continental CPA, we submitted our dispute to binding arbitration.&nbsp; The arbitration panel
determined that the annual 2007 budgeted rates originally presented by Airlines should be reduced in the aggregate by $14.2 million (or less than 1.0% of our total Continental CPA operating revenue), which included the 10% target operating margin.&nbsp; Although we
believe our original rates were appropriate, we were pleased with the panel&rsquo;s decision.&nbsp; The 2007 scheduled block hour rates were finalized in October 2007, and w<font color="black">e recorded our passenger revenue under the Continental CPA using the block
hour rates determined by the panel for all of 2007.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Note 3- Restructuring and Related Special Charges</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Effective July 1, 2008, we entered into a new seven-year capacity purchase agreement with Continental by amending and restating the existing Continental CPA.&nbsp; The
amended agreement is based on fixed block hour rates that are considerably lower than the rates under the original agreement, which was designed to achieve an approximate 10% margin.&nbsp; Additionally, we suspended flying under our branded flying operations and
terminated the Delta CPA and the Delta Prorate in September 2008.&nbsp; In connection with these capacity reductions and the transition of 30 aircraft back to Continental, we incurred special charges of $22.4 million related to aircraft, employee reductions and
certain other charges.&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Special Charges</font></b></p>

thousands):</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Wages and Fringe.</font></b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp; As a result of our restructuring we implemented a reduction in workforce and recorded $19.2 million in
severance and continuing medical coverage and other fringe benefits for employees accepting early retirement.&nbsp; We do not expect additional charges related to the reduction in workforce to be significant.&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lease Return Costs.</font></b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp; We incurred $2.2 million in costs during 2008 to retrofit 39 returned aircraft to comply with the
return conditions specified in the subleases.&nbsp; These costs included labor and materials to repair, paint, and modify the interiors to prelease conditions.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b>Deferred Credits.</b>&nbsp; We wrote off $7.9 million in deferred credits in 2008.&nbsp; The credits were from the aircraft manufacturer to cover training and spare
parts purchases and were being amortized against aircraft rent expense over the lives of the underlying aircraft leases.&nbsp; Due to the transition in our business model, we no longer are charged aircraft rent and accordingly wrote off the deferred
credits.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b>Contract Termination Costs.</b>&nbsp; During 2008, we incurred $1.7 million in early termination payments to sever contractual relationships that supported our
Branded Flying operations.&nbsp; We are currently in negotiation with other parties to settle early contract terminations so there may be additional contract termination charges in 2009, however we do not expect the charges to be significant.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Unused Facility Costs and Other.&nbsp;</font></b> <font size="2">We recorded a charge of $6.3 million in 2008 for the future rent obligations related to facility
leases at locations that supported our suspended operations.&nbsp; Payments remaining on these lease obligations will continue through 2010.&nbsp; In addition, we incurred $0.9 million in 2008 to redeploy certain general service equipment from our unused facilities
to our other lines of business.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The above costs are reflected in the line &ldquo;Special charges&rdquo; on our consolidated statements of operations.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008 our accruals for special charges we expect to pay in cash are as follows (in thousands):</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Payments related to the wages and fringe accrual and contract termination costs will be made in 2009.&nbsp; Payments remaining on our lease obligations for unused
facilities will continue through 2010.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In accordance with Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No. 144 Accounting for the Impairment of Long-Lived Assets (SFAS 144) we record impairment charges on
long-lived assets used in operations when events and circumstances indicate that the assets may be impaired, the undiscounted cash flows estimated to be generated by those assets are less than the carrying amount of those assets and the net book value of the assets
exceeds their estimated fair value.&nbsp; As a result of our impairment test, we concluded the carrying values of certain of our long-lived assets, primarily leasehold improvements in our at-risk flying segment were no longer recoverable.&nbsp; Consequently, during
2008, we recorded impairment charges of $8.0 million to write these long-lived assets down to their estimated fair values.&nbsp; Fair values were determined based on estimated future cash flows for Branded Flying which were considered nominal.&nbsp; No portion of the
impairment charge will result in future cash expenditures.&nbsp; All other long-lived assets for our other reportable segments were tested for impairment but were concluded to be recoverable with projected undiscounted cash flows.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Goodwill of $12.8 million represents an amount associated with Continental&rsquo;s bankruptcy restructuring and was recorded on our books prior to ExpressJet&rsquo;s IPO
from Continental in 2002.&nbsp; In accordance with SFAS No. 142 <i>Goodwill and Other Intangible Assets</i> (SFAS 142), we apply a fair value based impairment test to the net book value of goodwill on an annual basis and if certain events or circumstances indicate
that an impairment loss may have been incurred on an interim basis.&nbsp; The analysis of potential impairment of goodwill requires a two-step process.&nbsp; The first step is the estimation of fair value.&nbsp; If step one indicates that impairment potentially
exists, the second step is performed to measure the amount of impairment, if any.&nbsp; Goodwill impairment exists when the estimated fair value of goodwill is less than our carrying value.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Goodwill is allocated to our contract flying reportable segment.&nbsp; We estimated fair value based on a discounted projection of future cash flows, supported with
market based valuation.&nbsp; During 2008, we determined goodwill was impaired and recorded a non-cash charge of $12.8 million.&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The impairment charges for both long-lived assets and goodwill total $20.8 million.&nbsp; These charges are reflected in the line &ldquo;Impairment of fixed assets and
goodwill&rdquo; on our consolidated statement of operations for the year ended December 31, 2008.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b>Fuel.</b>&nbsp; Under the Amended Continental CPA, Continental is responsible for the cost of providing fuel for all flights and, therefore, effective July 1, 2008,
fuel expense is no longer included in our statements of operations for aircraft flying within this arrangement.&nbsp; Upon the decision to suspend operations for Airlines&rsquo; Branded Flying on July 8, 2008, we sold our fixed forward purchase contracts for periods
subsequent to September 2, 2008, which resulted in a non-operating gain of approximately $23 million.&nbsp; To date, we have received $21 million in cash from World Fuel Services with the remaining $2 million held in deposit for future fuel purchases within our
Corporate Aviation division.&nbsp; The funds held in deposit by World Fuel Services earn interest.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Note 4 <i>&ndash;</i> Segment Reporting</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The following business discussion is based on the three reportable segments, Contract Flying, Branded Flying and Aviation Services, as they were structured during the
year ended December 31, 2008.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A significant portion of our operating expenses and infrastructure is integrated across segments (e.g., for maintenance, non-airport facility rentals, outside services,
general and administrative expenses) in order to support our entire fleet of aircraft; therefore, we do not allocate these costs to the individual segments identified above, but evaluate them for our consolidated operation.&nbsp; The presentation of our consolidated
shared costs is consistent with the manner in which these expenses are reviewed by our chief operating decision makers.&nbsp; Consequently, the tables below present (in thousands) our operating revenues, including inter-segment revenues, and segment profit / (losses)
generated per reportable segment for the years ended December 31, 2008 and 2007.&nbsp; We also included our reconciliation of the consolidated operating revenue to consolidated net loss before taxes and of our total assets as of December 31, 2008 and 2007.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Note 5 &ndash; Fair Value Measurements.</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> <font size="2" face="Arial">In September 2006, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (&ldquo;FASB&rdquo;) issued FASB
Statement No. 157, Fair Value Measurements (&ldquo;Statement 157&rdquo;), which is effective for fiscal years beginning after November 15, 2007.&nbsp; Statement 157 defines fair value, establishes a framework for measuring it and expands disclosures about assets and
liabilities measured at fair value.&nbsp; We adopted the provisions of Statement 157 as of January 1, 2008 for our financial assets and liabilities.&nbsp; However, the FASB deferred the effective date of Statement 157 for one year as it relates to fair value
measurement requirements for nonfinancial assets and liabilities that are not recognized or disclosed at fair value on a recurring basis until 2009, which we do not expect to materially impact the Company.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The new standard provides a consistent definition of fair value which focuses on exit price and prioritizes, within a measurement of fair value, the use of market-based
inputs over entity-specific inputs. The standard also establishes a three-level hierarchy for fair value measurements based on the transparency of inputs to the valuation of an asset or liability as of the measurement date.&nbsp; The three tiers of fair value input
are defined below:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Level 1 &ndash; inputs to the valuation methodology which are quoted prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Level 2 &ndash; inputs to the valuation methodology which are quoted prices in active markets for similar assets or liabilities, quoted prices in markets that are not active; or other inputs that are observable, either directly or
indirectly, for substantially the full term of the assets or liabilities; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Level 3 &ndash; inputs to the valuation methodology which are unobservable and significant to the fair value measurement.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In February 2008, we invested in approximately $65 million in ARS which are classified as available-for-sale securities and reflected at fair value.&nbsp; The fair value
of our ARS is estimated using a discounted cash flow valuation model as of December 31, 2008.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, we continue to earn interest at an average rate of 1.72% on all of our ARS.&nbsp; At the end of each quarter we record any changes in fair
value related to these instruments that we deem to be temporary to accumulated other comprehensive income.&nbsp; If we determine that any future decline in value was other than temporary, it would be recognized as a charge to earnings as appropriate.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our valuation model considers, among other items, the collateralization underlying the ARS, the creditworthiness of our counterparties, the timing of expected future
cash flows, and a discount rate which accounts for the liquidity issue associated with the current market conditions.&nbsp; These securities were also compared, where possible, to other observable market data with similar characteristics, however, due to the
contraction in the credit markets and other factors, the market for ARS is currently trading at minimal volumes.&nbsp; As we could not predict when the market would recover and needed to avail ourselves the flexibility to sell our ARS in the next 12 months, we
evaluated and classified, in accordance with accounting guidance our ARS as short-term investments and recognized in the first quarter of 2008 an other-than-temporary impairment of $13.7 million.&nbsp; This impairment charge was recognized as &ldquo;Impairment
charges on investments&rdquo; in our consolidated statement of operations.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, we estimated the fair value of our ARS investment to be $41.4 million and recorded net unrealized gains or losses to other comprehensive income,
accordingly.&nbsp; Our total net comprehensive loss for the year ended December 31, 2008 was $0.5 million.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Subsequent to year-end, we monetized $4.2 million of our ARS for 87.5% of the face value of the securities.&nbsp; We continue to monitor the ARS market and will
aggressively pursue monetizing the assets at or near face value through additional market transactions and will also pursue litigation if necessary to recoup full value.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Assets that we measure at fair value on a recurring basis are shown below (in thousands):&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>
