<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></b> We determine the cost basis for our ARS sold using the specific identification method.</p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Following the completion of the tender offer in August 2008 for our Original 4.25% Convertible Notes due 2023, $68.5 million aggregate principal of our convertible notes
remains outstanding.&nbsp; Additionally, as provided in the amended indenture governing the notes, such notes have become our 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023.&nbsp; In accordance with EITF 96-19 &ldquo;Debtor's Accounting for a Modification or Exchange of
Debt Instruments,&rdquo; we accounted for this exchange as an extinguishment of debt, since the net present value of the cash flows under the exchanged terms was more than 10% of the net present value of the cash flows under the terms of the original
instrument.&nbsp; As required by accounting rules, we recorded the convertible notes to a fair value of $40.7 million, net of a debt discount of $27.8 million that will be amortized over the life of the new instrument up to the first date at which we may be required
to repurchase the notes in August 2011.&nbsp; Such adjustment was recorded as a non-recurring gain under non-operating income in 2008.&nbsp; The net balance of the 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023 as of December 31, 2008 was $39.7 million.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We estimated fair value of our convertible notes based on an average of market trading activity for the convertible notes subsequent to the exchange in August
2008.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Note 6 &ndash;&ndash; Investments in Other Entities</font></b></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Investments in unconsolidated companies are accounted for by the equity method of accounting when we have significant influence over the operation of the companies as
prescribed by Accounting Principles Board Opinion No. 18 &ndash; &ldquo;The Equity Method of Accounting for Investments in Common Stock&rdquo; (&ldquo;ABP 18&rdquo;).&nbsp; The following table details our current non-controlling interests that are accounted for under
the equity method of accounting:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="528">
<tr>
<td valign="bottom"></td>
<td valign="bottom"></td>
<td colspan="3" valign="bottom">
<p align="center"><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Carrying Amount of Investment at<br />
 December 31,<br />
 (in millions)</font></b></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="bottom">
<p align="center"><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Company</font></b></p>
</td>
<td valign="bottom"></td>
<td valign="bottom">
<p align="center"><b><font size="2" face="Arial">2008</font></b></p>
</td>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="bottom">
<p align="center"><b><font size="2" face="Arial">2007</font></b></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<div align="right"><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b>
<hr size="1" width="100%" align="right" />
</div>
</td>

<tr>
<td valign="top" bgcolor="#e0e0e0">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Wing Holdings, LLC (&ldquo;Wing&rdquo;)</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top" bgcolor="#e0e0e0">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">$</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="bottom" bgcolor="#e0e0e0">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&mdash;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="bottom" bgcolor="#e0e0e0"></td>
<td valign="top" bgcolor="#e0e0e0">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">6.5</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Flight Services and Systems, Inc. (&ldquo;FSS&rdquo;)</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">1.6</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">3.3</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We purchased a 49% interest in Wing for $16.0 million in June 2005.&nbsp; The carrying amount of our investment exceeded the amount of the company&rsquo;s underlying
equity by approximately $8.5 million at the time of our investment.&nbsp; We evaluated the net book value of the company&rsquo;s fixed assets as of June 30, 2005 and identified approximately a $1.9 million difference between net book value and fair value.&nbsp; The
majority of the difference is being amortized over the remaining average life of the assets identified.&nbsp; During fourth quarter 2007, we evaluated and determined that the carrying value of our investment in Wing was other-than-temporarily impaired due to
continuing net losses through 2007 and the projections of growth were no longer as aggressive as anticipated when we purchased this entity.&nbsp; Therefore, we recognized an impairment charge of $7.0 million comprised primarily of the inherent goodwill.&nbsp; During
the second quarter of 2008, we impaired the remaining investment balance in Wing due to continuing losses.&nbsp; Additionally, on July 18, 2008, we received notification that Wing was closing their main facility which represents approximately 64% of projected
revenues.&nbsp; These impairment charges were recognized as decreases to our investment balance and the corresponding equity losses are presented in the line &ldquo;Impairment charges on investments&rdquo; in our consolidated statements of operations.</font><font
size="2"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In January 2006, we purchased a 44% interest in FSS for $3 million.&nbsp; At the same time, we loaned FSS $1 million which was originally classified in Other Assets,
net, on the consolidated balance sheet.&nbsp; The note was due and payable in full on September 30, 2007, and provided that interest was due and payable quarterly on the 15th day following the close of each calendar quarter.&nbsp; <font color="black">The note
provided that if International Total Services, Inc. (&ldquo;ITS&rdquo;) (also owned by the non-ExpressJet owners of FSS) emerged from bankruptcy and FSS could utilize ITS&rsquo;s federal income tax attributes through a transaction or series of transactions, then any
unpaid balance of the note would be deemed paid in full as a contribution by us to the capital of FSS.&nbsp;</font> The loan interest rate was equal to the lesser of 7% per annum or the three-month LIBOR plus 150 basis points.&nbsp; In 2008, we determined that FSS
had satisfied its obligation on the note and we reclassified it from &ldquo;Other Assets, net&rdquo; to &ldquo;Investments in Other Entities&rdquo; on our consolidated balance sheets.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, we evaluated and determined that the carrying value
of our investment in FSS was other-than-temporarily impaired due to our decision to fully reserve for the value of FSS&rsquo;s share of ITS&rsquo;s federal income tax attributes due to the uncertainty of their ultimate realizability.&nbsp; As such, we recorded an
impairment charge of $2.6 million in 2008.&nbsp; This impairment charge was recognized as a decrease to our investment balance and corresponding equity loss presented in the line &ldquo;Impairment charges on investments&rdquo; in our consolidated statements of
operations.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our proportionate shares of the results of operations from these entities are included in the line &ldquo;Equity investment income (loss), net&rdquo; on our consolidated
statements of operations.&nbsp;</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>

</div>

<b><font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font></b>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Note 8 &ndash;&ndash; Leases</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> <font size="2" face="Arial">Under the Amended Continental CPA, Continental will be responsible for paying aircraft rent on all aircraft covered by such
agreement, therefore, these items are not included in our statements of operations for periods after June 30, 2008.&nbsp; Under the original CPA we leased or subleased all our aircraft under operating leases with lease terms ranging from 16 to 16.5 years from
Continental at the same terms as the lease agreements between Continental and the third-party lessors.&nbsp; Therefore, the 214 aircraft operating under the Amended Continental CPA are excluded from the table below as we no longer have future minimum lease
commitments related to these aircraft.&nbsp; Lease payments relating to the 30 aircraft removed from the Continental CPA are at reduced rental rates. This rate decrease is reflected in the tables below.&nbsp; Rental payments for each aircraft are fixed upon lease
execution with no escalation clauses.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We also lease or sublease, under various operating leases, ground equipment and substantially all of our ground facilities, including facilities at public airports from
Continental or the municipalities or agencies owning and controlling such airports.&nbsp; Though the duration and terms of these leases vary greatly, we expect, in most cases, leases to be renewed or replaced by new leases as required in the normal course of
business.&nbsp; Our leases do not include residual value guarantees.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><font size="2"><br clear="all" />
</font></font>

under operating leases that have initial or remaining non-cancelable lease terms in excess of one year are as follows (in millions):</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Amortization of capital leases is included with depreciation expense as disclosed in the financial statements.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Total rent expense was approximately $236.1 million, $400.4 million and $377.4 million for the years ended December 31, 2008, 2007 and 2006, respectively, which includes
non-aircraft rent expense of approximately $39.0 million, $56.2 million and $45.0 million.&nbsp;&nbsp; Under subleases or leases within the Continental CPA, total rent expense was $145.0 million, $277.2 million and $349.5 million in 2008, 2007 and 2006,
respectively.&nbsp; Under subleases with Continental, total rental expense was $189.5 million, $326.6 million and $315.1 million for 2008, 2007 and 2006, respectively.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; If we defaulted on our payment obligations under our aircraft and facility leases or subleases with Continental, Continental would be entitled to reduce future payments
to us under the Continental CPA by the amount of the defaulted payment.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Note 9 &ndash;&ndash; Long-term Debt</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> <font size="2">As of December 31, 2008, long-term debt, including current maturities, totaled $49.0 million (net of discount of $21.1 million), which consisted of
our 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023 and the EDC Loans.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In July 2003, we completed an offering of $137.2 million aggregate principal amount of Original 4.25% Convertible Notes due 2023 with interest payable
semi-annually.&nbsp; Holders of this debt had the right to require that we repurchase their notes on August 1, 2008, 2013 and 2018 (&ldquo;Repurchase Dates&rdquo;) at a repurchase price equal to 100% of the principal amount of the notes to be repurchased plus accrued
and unpaid interest, if any.&nbsp; On August 1, 2008, holders of our Original 4.25% Convertible Notes due 2023 had the right to require us to repurchase their notes at a price equal to 100% of the principal amount of the notes plus any accrued and unpaid
interest.&nbsp; Under the indenture governing the convertible notes, we were able to satisfy the obligation with either cash, shares of our common stock, or a combination of cash and shares.&nbsp; During 2008, we took the following actions after consulting with our
independent financial advisors:</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr height="16">
<td height="16" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="16" valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="16" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Received stockholders approval for two proposals that provided us greater flexibility in satisfying our repurchase obligations with respect to the Original 4.25% Convertible Notes, which included the ability to issue such number of
shares of our common stock as necessary to repurchase all outstanding convertible notes that were tendered on August 1, 2008, and increased our authorized common stock from 200 million shares to 400 million shares;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr height="17">
<td height="17" valign="top"></td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Commenced our repurchase offer for the Original 4.25% Convertible Notes and provided written notice to the trustee of our intention to pay the repurchase price wholly in shares of our common stock;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr height="17">
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">Unilaterally amended the indenture</font> <font size="2">governing the notes to increase the coupon from 4.25% to 11.25% over the remaining note term, to provide security based on a pro-rata amount of collateral and to
provide for an additional Repurchase Date on August 1, 2011, in order to provide improved terms and additional flexibility for the noteholders; a<font color="black">nd</font></font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr height="17">
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td height="17" valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Issued 16.4 million shares (Reverse Split adjusted) of our common stock in payment of the repurchase price for the $59.7 million principal amount of the notes validly tendered and to settle accrued and unpaid interest due August 1,
2008.&nbsp; Because the common stock was issued in exchange for the Original 4.25% Convertible Notes exclusively with the existing holders of the notes, and no commission or other compensation was paid in soliciting the exchange, the securities are exempt from
registration under Section 3(a)(9) of the Securities Act of 1933.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Following the completion of the tender offer in August 2008 for our Original 4.25% Convertible Notes due 2023, $68.5 million aggregate principal of our convertible notes
remains outstanding.&nbsp; Additionally, as provided in the amended indenture governing the notes, such notes have become our 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023.&nbsp; In accordance with EITF 96-19 &ldquo;Debtor's Accounting for a Modification or Exchange of
Debt Instruments,&rdquo;&nbsp;we accounted for this exchange as an extinguishment of debt, since the net present value of the cash flows under the exchanged terms was more than 10% of the net present value of the cash flows under the terms of the original
instrument.&nbsp; As required by accounting rules, we recorded the convertible notes to a fair value of $40.7 million, net of a debt discount of $27.8 million that will be amortized over the life of the new instrument up to the first date at which we may be required
to repurchase the notes in August 2011.&nbsp; Such adjustment was recorded as a non-recurring gain under non-operating income for 2008.&nbsp; The net balance of the 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023 as of December 31, 2008 was $39.7 million.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We estimated fair value of our convertible notes based on an average of market trading activity for the convertible notes subsequent to the exchange in August
2008.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Other than the convertible notes, we do not have any material long-term borrowings or available lines of credit.&nbsp; Pursuant to the terms of the amended indenture
governing the 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023, we granted a security interest, with a pro-rata portion, (based on the portion that the remaining notes represent of the total convertible notes that were issued) of assets with an appraised value of
approximately $181 million, including approximately $96 million in spare parts and $85 million of spare engines.&nbsp; Based on the principal amount of notes remaining outstanding on August 2, 2008, the pledged collateral for the notes totals approximately $51.5
million in spare parts and $45.3 million in spare engines.&nbsp; We agreed that we will not as of any fiscal year end permit the aggregate outstanding principal amount of the Notes divided by the fair market value of the pledged collateral to be greater than certain
percentages.&nbsp; If such collateral ratios are greater than the applicable maximum, we will pledge additional spare parts, spare aircraft engines and / or cash and cash equivalents.&nbsp; Pursuant to the terms of the amended indenture, we are required to deliver a
certificate from our appraiser dated not later than 15 business days after January 1 of each year certifying the value as of January 1 or such later date.&nbsp; We delivered such certificate from our appraiser in January 2009 and the appraised values of $180.4
million have not changed materially from the initial appraisal of $181 million at the amendment date.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The notes are guaranteed by Airlines.&nbsp; Except as otherwise specified in the indenture pursuant to which the notes were issued, there are no restrictions on
Airlines&rsquo; ability to transfer funds to Holdings in the form of cash dividends, loans or advances.&nbsp; General provisions of applicable state law, however, may limit the ability of any subsidiary to pay dividends or make distributions to its parent in certain
circumstances.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; If we elect to use shares of common stock to repurchase any notes, the number of shares will be equal to the repurchase price divided by 97.5% of the average closing
sales price of our common stock for the five consecutive trading days ending on the third business day prior to the applicable Repurchase Date (adjusted to take into account the occurrence of certain events that would require adjustment of the conversion rate). In
certain circumstances, the notes were convertible into our common stock, at a ratio of 54.9451 shares of common stock per $1,000 principal amount of notes, which was equivalent to an initial conversion price of approximately $18.20 per common share; however,
following our Reverse Split the ratio is now 5.49451, which is equivalent to a price of approximately $182.00 per common share.&nbsp; The ratio is subject to adjustments if certain events take place, and holders may convert only if the closing sale price per common
share exceeds 120% of the conversion price for at least 20 trading days in the 30 consecutive trading day period ending on the last trading day of the preceding calendar quarter.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2008 we purchased $6.5 million of our Original 4.25% Convertible Notes due 2023 and $7.6 million par value (book value of $4.5 million) of our 11.25% Convertible
Secured Notes due 2023 for $10.8 million resulting in a net realized gain of $.2 million.&nbsp;&nbsp; Subsequent to these repurchases our interest expense related to the debt discount will be $8.2 million annually through August 2011.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008 and December 31, 2007, we estimated the fair value of our $60.8 million and $134.7 million (carrying value) fixed-rate debt to be $38.9 million
and $130.7 million, respectively, based upon quoted market prices.&nbsp; In addition, we made interest payments of $4.7 million and $5.8 million in 2008 and 2007, respectively.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The EDC Loans consist of $10.7 million loaned to us in May 2003 and $6.6 million loaned to us in September 2003.&nbsp; The EDC Loans are secured by certain of our flight
simulators, flight data software and other equipment related to the simulators.&nbsp; We used all the proceeds from the EDC Loans to reduce the principal under a note we had issued to Continental.&nbsp; The amount due to EDC accrues interest at the six-month LIBOR
plus 1.75% per annum.&nbsp; Each of the EDC Loans has a term of 96 months and each contains customary representations, warranties and covenants.&nbsp; Additionally, Continental is the guarantor of the EDC Loans, and a default under the guarantee would cause an
acceleration of the loan.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The table above assumes the 11.25% Convertible Secured Notes due 2023 will be due on August 1, 2011, the earliest date that the holders of the notes may require us to
repurchase the notes.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Other than the debt obligations described above, we do not have any other source of long-term borrowings or available lines of credit.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The following condensed consolidating balance sheets, results of operations and cash flows present separately the financial position of the parent issuer, Holdings, the
subsidiary guarantor, Airlines, and all other non-guarantor subsidiaries of Holdings on a combined basis.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The reconciliations of income tax computed at the United States federal statutory tax rates to income tax expense for the years ended December 31, 2008, 2007 and 2006
are as follows:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Deferred income taxes reflect the net tax effects of temporary differences between the carrying amounts of assets and liabilities for financial reporting purposes and
the related amounts used for income tax purposes.&nbsp; Significant components of our deferred tax liabilities and assets as of December 31, 2008 and 2007 are as follows (in millions):</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The tender offer and partial redemption in August 2008 of the 4.25% Convertible Notes due 2023 caused Holdings to trigger a change in ownership limitation under Section
382 of the Internal Revenue Code in August 2008. &nbsp;Section 382 limits a taxpayer's ability to utilize certain carryover tax attributes after a substantial cumulative change in ownership of their stock.&nbsp; The regulation mandates a three-year &ldquo;look
back&rdquo; requiring Holdings to evaluate its position related to Section 382 beginning in 2005. &nbsp;The results of the look back analysis indicated that Holdings triggered Section 382 changes in ownership in April 2005 and in August 2008. &nbsp;The April 2005
change resulted in an after tax charge of $1.6 million primarily related to interest on the timing of certain tax obligations. Due to the decrease in our market capitalization, the Section 382 change triggered in August 2008 resulted in our conclusion that it was
more likely than not that we would not be able to utilize our deferred tax assets due to this limitation and therefore we recorded an increase of $19.3 million to the valuation allowance.&nbsp; We recorded the effects of this adjustment in 2008 as any impact to
previously reported financial statements was not deemed to be material.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Also during 2008 we recorded $8.5 million in income tax expense to record a valuation allowance for certain deferred tax assets related to capital losses and,
international and state tax net operating losses as it was concluded more likely than not that adequate income would not be generated to utilize these deferred tax assets based on their characterization and/or carryforward period.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>

<p><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In conjunction with our initial public offering in April 2002, the tax basis of our tangible and intangible assets was adjusted to fair value.&nbsp; This adjustment to
tax basis should result in additional tax deductions being available to us through 2017.&nbsp; In October 2006, Continental entered into a final settlement agreement with the IRS that included periods during which we were included in its consolidated federal income
tax return.&nbsp; Our taxable income was not adjusted, but the amount of net operating losses allocated to us was increased by approximately $31.2 million.&nbsp; In accordance with our tax agreement with Continental, to the extent we generate taxable income
sufficient to realize the additional tax deductions and tax attributes allocated to us, we are required to pay Continental a percentage of the amount of tax savings actually realized, excluding the effect of any loss carrybacks.&nbsp; We are required to pay
Continental 100% of the first third of the anticipated tax benefit, 90% of the second third and 80% of the last third.&nbsp; However, if the tax benefits are not realized by the end of 2018, we will be obligated to pay Continental 100% of any benefit realized after
that date.&nbsp; Since these payments are solely dependent on our ability to generate sufficient taxable income to realize these deferred tax assets, they are recorded as an obligation to Continental within the deferred tax asset accounts, and the portion we may
retain in the future is offset by a valuation allowance.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; At the time of the initial public offering, the valuation allowance and the obligation to Continental offset the step-up in basis of assets in our long-term deferred tax
asset account.&nbsp; There were no payments made to Continental under the tax agreement during 2008 and 2007.&nbsp; We made approximately $24.8 million and $25.3 million of net payments to Continental under the tax agreement related to the additional tax deductions
during 2006 and 2005, respectively.&nbsp; Because of the April 2005 Section 382 change in ownership, our ability to utilize some of the tax attributes flowing from Continental has been limited.&nbsp; Our losses in 2007 and 2008 carryback to offset the tax shortfall,
but result in an interest charge recorded in current tax expense and discussed above.&nbsp; Our August 2008 Section 382 ownership change limits our ability to realize the gross deferred tax assets recorded at December 31, 2008.&nbsp; Federal and many state net
operating loss carryovers are subject to substantial annual limitations over their remaining life, while our federal regular tax deductions for our tax amortizable intangible assets are limited for the five year period after this ownership change.&nbsp; We are
currently assessing the impact of this limitation including any amounts that may be owed from Continental to the Company.&nbsp; If amounts are recoverable from Continental, it may decrease the valuation allowance recorded as of December 31, 2008.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our tax agreement increases our dependence on Continental&rsquo;s financial condition.&nbsp; If it is determined that any of the tax benefits related to the basis
increase should not have been available at the time of utilization and, as a result, we are required to pay additional taxes, interest and penalties, then we could be adversely affected if Continental were unable to indemnify us under the agreement.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Effective January 1, 2007, we adopted the provisions of Financial Accounting Standards Board issued Interpretation No. 48, &ldquo;Accounting for Uncertainty in Income
Taxes, an interpretation of FASB Statement No. 109&rdquo; (&ldquo;FIN 48&rdquo;), which clarifies the accounting for uncertainty in income taxes recognized in financial statements if a position is more likely than not of being sustained by a taxing authority.&nbsp;
We classify interest and penalties on tax deficiencies as charges to income tax expense.&nbsp; For the year ended December 31, 2008 we recorded a net interest charge of $1.6 million to income tax expense in the consolidated statements of operations.&nbsp; As of
December 31, 2008 and 2007, there were no material unrecognized tax benefits or associated accrued interest and penalties under FIN 48.&nbsp; The calendar tax years 2003 through 2007 remain subject to examination by the Internal Revenue Service.&nbsp;</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Note 11 &ndash; Earnings / (Loss) Per Share</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We account for earnings per share in accordance with Statement of Financial Accounting Standard No. 128 <font color="black">&mdash;</font> &ldquo;Earnings per
Share.&rdquo; Basic earnings per common share (&ldquo;Basic EPS&rdquo;) excludes dilution and is computed by dividing net income available to common stockholders by the weighted average number of common shares outstanding during the periods presented.&nbsp; Diluted
EPS reflects the potential dilution that could occur if securities or other obligations to issue common stock were exercised or converted into common stock or resulted in the issuance of common stock that then shared in the earnings of the Company.&nbsp; As discussed
below under &ldquo;Reverse Stock Split,&rdquo; our stock began trading on a split-adjusted basis when the market opened on October 2, 2008.&nbsp; As required per SEC Staff Accounting Bulletin Topic 4C, &ldquo;Changes in Capital Structure&rdquo;, the computation of
basic and diluted loss per share has been retroactively adjusted to reflect the reverse stock split for all periods presented in our consolidated statements of operations.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The following table sets forth the reconciliation of the numerator and denominator of Basic EPS to the numerator and denominator of Diluted EPS for the years ended
December 31, 2008, 2007, and 2006 (in thousands, except per share amounts):</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We excluded 55,886 and 60,849 shares of restricted stock from the weighted average shares used in computing Basic EPS for the years ended December 31, 2008 and 2007,

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Weighted average common shares outstanding for the Diluted EPS calculation also include the incremental effect of shares issuable upon the exercise of stock options and
restricted stock not yet vested.&nbsp; We excluded the following common stock equivalents from our Diluted EPS calculations, because their inclusion would have been anti-dilutive:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="624">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">options to purchase 0.4 million, 0.4 million and 0.2 million shares of our common stock for the years ended December 31, 2008, 2007 and 2006, respectively, these options&rsquo; exercise prices were greater than the average market price
of the common shares for the respective periods; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">0.3 million, 0.7 million and 0.8 million shares of common stock equivalents for the assumed conversion of convertible debt for the years ended December 31, 2008, 2007 and 2006, respectively.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As a result of our tender offer with respect to our Original 4.25% Convertible Notes due 2023, we issued 16.4 million shares (Reverse Split adjusted) of our common stock
in payment for the $59.7 million principal amount of the notes validly tendered and to settle accrued and unpaid interest that was due August 1, 2008.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b>Reverse Stock Split.</b>&nbsp; On October 1, 2008, at a special meeting of our stockholders, we received stockholder approval for a proposal to effect a one-for-ten
reverse split of our common stock, par value $0.01 per share.&nbsp; The approved proposal also reduced the number of authorized shares of the Company&rsquo;s common stock from 400,000,000 to 150,000,000.&nbsp; The Reverse Split became effective on October 2,
2008.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Reverse Split was part of our continuing efforts to return to trading on all New York Stock Exchange (&ldquo;NYSE&rdquo;) Group platforms.&nbsp; In addition, the
reverse split was a step to allow us to return to compliance with the continued listing standard of the NYSE on January 20, 2009.&nbsp; As a result of the Reverse Split, each 10 shares of our common stock was combined into and automatically became one share of our
common stock which began trading on a split-adjusted basis when the market opened on October 2, 2008, with cash paid in lieu of fractional shares.&nbsp; The reverse split affected all shares of our common stock and stock options outstanding immediately prior to the
effective time of the Reverse Split.&nbsp; The Certificate of Amendment did not change the par value of our common stock, which remains at $0.01 per share.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Each stockholder&rsquo;s percentage ownership in the Company and proportional voting power remains unchanged after the reverse split except for minor
changes and adjustments resulting from fractional shares. The rights and privileges of stockholders were substantially unaffected by the Reverse Split.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Reverse Split which began trading on a split-adjusted basis when the market opened on October 2, 2008 is currently reflected in all share information presented in
these financial statements.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Note 12 &ndash;&ndash; Preferred, Common and Treasury Stock</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Preferred Stock.</i></b>&nbsp; We have 10 million shares of authorized preferred stock, par value $0.1 per share.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Common Stock.</i></b>&nbsp; We currently have one class of common stock, par value $.01 per share, with<b></b>22.0 million shares issued and 17.7 million shares
outstanding.&nbsp; Each share of common stock is entitled to one vote.&nbsp; Common stockholders would participate ratably in any dividends or distributions on the common stock.&nbsp;</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Treasury Stock.</i></b>&nbsp; In July 2005, our Board of Directors authorized the expenditure of up to $30 million to repurchase shares of our common stock.&nbsp;
Additionally, during the fourth quarter of 2008, the Board authorized an additional $15 million for this program.&nbsp; Purchases have been made from time to time in the open market; the timing of any share repurchases under the program depends on a variety of
factors, including market conditions, and may be suspended or discontinued at any time.&nbsp; We account for our common stock repurchases using the cost method such that when shares are reissued, proceeds in excess of cost are charged to additional paid-in capital
and any deficiency is charged to accumulated earnings.&nbsp; Cost is determined using a weighted average price.&nbsp; Common stock acquired through the program is available for general corporate purposes.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, we had a balance of $10.1
million remaining within the program for additional purchases.&nbsp; As discussed In Note 11 &ndash; &ldquo;Earnings / (Loss) Per Share&rdquo;,<b></b>stockholders approved to effect a Reverse Split of our common stock in 2008.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Shares forfeited under our stock based compensation plans are held as treasury stock, which can be used to issue new restricted stock and to satisfy any exercises of
stock options.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Note 13 &ndash;&ndash; Stock-Based Compensation Plans</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> <font size="2">As of December 31, 2008, we had three stock-based compensation plans: the ExpressJet Holdings, Inc. 2002 and 2007 Stock Incentive Plans (the
&ldquo;Incentive Plans&rdquo;) and the ExpressJet Holdings, Inc. 2003 Employee Stock Purchase Plan (the &ldquo;ESPP&rdquo;).&nbsp; These Incentive Plans provide that we may grant awards in the form of stock options or restricted stock to our non-employee directors,
our employees or employees of our subsidiaries. The 2007 Incentive Plan also provides that we may grant awards in the form of performance units, stock appreciation rights, or any other right, interest or option related to shares or other property, including cash. The
aggregate number of shares of our common stock that may be issued under the Incentive Plans may not exceed 3.2 million shares, subject to adjustments as provided in these Incentive Plans.&nbsp; We have reserved 3.2 million shares of our common stock for issuance
under this plan.&nbsp; Options granted under these Incentive Plans have been awarded with exercise prices equaling the fair market value of the stock on the date of grant, vest over a four-year period for employees or a six-month period for non-employee directors and
expire seven years after the date of grant in the case of employees and ten years after the date of grant in the case of directors.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> <font size="2">The fair value of Holdings&rsquo; options granted during 2008, 2007 and 2006 was estimated at the date of grant using the Black-Scholes
option-pricing model, which requires us to make several assumptions.&nbsp; The table below summarizes the weighted-average of these assumptions for the year ended December 31, 2008, 2007 and 2006:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The risk-free interest rate is based on the U.S. Treasury yield curve in effect for the expected term of the option at the time of grant.&nbsp; The dividend yield on our
common stock is assumed to be zero since we do not pay dividends and have no current plans to pay them in the future.&nbsp; The market price volatility of our common stock was based on historical volatility since April 23, 2002, the date of our initial public
offering.&nbsp; Our methodology is consistent with prior period volatility assumptions. The expected life of the options is based upon our anticipated expectations of exercise behavior since no options have been exercised since our initial public offering to provide
relevant historical data.&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Based upon the assumptions above, the weighted-average fair value of the options granted during 2008, 2007 and 2006 was determined to be $5.03, $3.48 and
$3.23.&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> <font size="2" face="Arial">As of December 31, 2008, there was $2.9 million of total unrecognized compensation cost related to unvested share-based
compensation arrangements granted under the Plans.&nbsp; That cost is expected to be recognized over a weighted average period of 1.7 years.&nbsp; Compensation cost recognized for the years ended December 31, 2008, 2007 and 2006 was $5.4 million, $5.7 million and
$2.7 million respectively.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On May 7, 2003, our stockholders approved the ESPP, which authorized the sale of up to one million pre-split shares of our common stock.&nbsp; We have reserved 100,000
Reverse Split adjusted shares of our common stock for issuance under the ESPP.&nbsp; Under the plan, all of our employees are eligible to purchase shares of our common stock at 85% of the lower of the fair market value on the first or last day of the semi-annual
purchase period.&nbsp; Our first purchase period began on July 1, 2003.&nbsp; Employees may sell shares obtained under the ESPP six months after the end of the plan period in which the shares were purchased.&nbsp; During 2008 and 2007, 59,368 and 8,349 Reverse Split
adjusted shares, respectively, of our common stock were issued to our employees at prices ranging from $4.68 to $21.08 in 2008 and prices ranging from $51.26 to $60.18 in 2007</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In November 4, 2005, our Board of Directors approved accelerating the vesting of 669,750 unvested options currently held by employees, including executive officers, with
exercise prices greater than $11.00 per share and extended the term of 868,500 employee options that had five-year terms to seven years.&nbsp; These options were and remain out of the money, and the acceleration and extension were effective immediately.&nbsp; No
options held by non-employee directors were subject to acceleration or extension.&nbsp; The acceleration of vesting reduces compensation expense upon the adoption of SFAS 123R.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Note 14 &ndash;&ndash; Employee Benefit Plans</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Effective December 31, 2002, the ExpressJet Airlines, Inc. 401(k) Savings Plan (&ldquo;401(k) Plan&rdquo;) was adopted.&nbsp; Substantially all our domestic employees
are covered by this plan.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Effective October 1, 2004 for Airlines&rsquo; mechanics, who are represented by the International Brotherhood of Teamsters, and January 1, 2005 for all other employees,
the 401(k) Plan was amended.&nbsp; Under the amended plan, we offer the following benefits:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="624">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">a service-based retirement match depending on the years of service from 4.0% up to 6.0% of pay per person, which vests over five years; and&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">a service-based retirement contribution depending on years of service and the terms of the collective bargaining agreements, as applicable.&nbsp; Effective January 1, 2007, the retirement contribution vesting terms changed from a
five-year cliff vesting schedule to a 5-year graded vesting schedule.&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; For the years ended December 31, 2008, 2007 and 2006, our total expense for the defined contribution plan was $19.4 million, $21.5 million and $19.5 million,
respectively.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Effective January 1, 2009, the 401(k) Plan was amended such that certain matches have been reduced or eliminated depending on the terms of the collective bargaining unit
or work group, as applicable.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The ExpressJet Airlines, Inc. Profit Sharing Plan (the &ldquo;Profit Sharing Plan&rdquo;) was adopted effective January 1, 2002 and amended on February 17, 2005.&nbsp;
Under this plan, if Airlines achieves a 10% operating margin, the Profit Sharing Plan will pay out 5% of eligible base pay received during the year to our eligible employees, which excludes employees whose collective bargaining agreements provide otherwise and
employees who participate in our management bonus program or any other bonus program designated by the Human Resources Committee of our Board.&nbsp; Profit sharing expense for the year ended December 31, 2006 was $9.2 million.&nbsp; Due to our consolidated net
operating losses in 2008 and 2007, no profit sharing expense was recognized.&nbsp; Effective January 1, 2009 the Profit Sharing Plan was amended to pay out 10% of pre-tax profits.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Effective January 1, 2009, we rolled out an enhanced profit sharing plan (&ldquo;Enhanced Profit Sharing Plan&rdquo;) to all eligible employees.&nbsp; The award pool
under the Enhanced Profit Sharing Plan is 50% of pre-tax net income greater than $30 million.&nbsp; The Enhanced Profit Sharing Plan is paid out before the Profit Sharing Plan.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="black" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We also provide medical bridge coverage for employees between the ages of 60 to 65, with at least 10 years of service who have retired from the Company.&nbsp; On
December 31, 2006 we adopted the recognition and disclosure provisions of Statement 158.&nbsp; Statement 158 required the recognition of fund status (i.e., the difference between the fair value of plan assets and projected benefit obligations) of its defined benefit
plan in the December 31, 2006 statement of financial position, with a corresponding adjustment to accumulated other comprehensive income, net of tax.&nbsp; The adjustment to accumulated other comprehensive income at adoption represents the new unrecognized actuarial
gain and unrecognized prior service costs.&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2008, the plan to provide medical bridge coverage for non-pilot employees was frozen to not allow new retirees on or after January 1, 2009.&nbsp; As a result, we
recorded a reduction in our liability and a corresponding curtailment gain of $2.0 million.&nbsp; The gain is reflected in the line item &ldquo;Wages, salaries and related costs&rdquo; in our consolidated statements of operations.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In December 2007 President Bush signed the Fair Treatment for Experienced Pilots Act (H.R. 4343) into law.&nbsp; This law increased the mandatory retirement age of
commercial pilots from 60 to 65.&nbsp; As a result of this legislation we no longer are required to provide medical bridge coverage to our pilots between the ages of 60 to 65 and therefore, we have recorded a reduction in our liability and corresponding curtailment
gain of $0.8 million.&nbsp; Our liability for medical bridge coverage for employees as of December 31, 2008 and 2007 was $.9 million and $2.5 million, respectively.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Note 15 &ndash;&ndash; Commitments and Contingencies</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Capacity Purchase Agreement.</i></b>&nbsp; See Note 2 &ndash; &ldquo;Contract Flying&rdquo; for further information regarding our capacity purchase agreement with
Continental.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Purchase Commitments.</i></b>&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, we had options for 50 ERJ-145XR aircraft that may be exercised for other types of aircraft within the
ERJ-145 Family.&nbsp; Our next option exercise date is April 1, 2009.&nbsp; If we do not exercise or extend our option as of this date, 25 options will expire.&nbsp; During 2005, Continental declined the right to include any of these option aircraft in the
Continental CPA.&nbsp; We retain the right to exercise them and fly these aircraft for other airlines or under our own code, subject to some restrictions; however, we will have to finance our acquisition of these aircraft independently.&nbsp; Currently, we do not
have any firm commitments for aircraft purchases.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Prior to December 2005, under our power-by-the-hour agreement with Rolls Royce, we were obligated to acquire up to three spare engines to support our existing aircraft
and the remaining eight aircraft on firm order.&nbsp; In December 2005, we negotiated the sale of eight engines to Rolls Royce and, in exchange, entered into seven new engine leases with a Rolls Royce subsidiary.&nbsp; The engines leased have greater
interchangeability than the engines sold. As a result, we have satisfied our engine obligations and are no longer obligated to purchase the three engines.&nbsp; These leases are classified as operating leases; hence they are not reflected as assets and liabilities on
our balance sheet.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We also have other contractual obligations of approximately $0.8 billion under our power-by-the-hour contracts with various service providers.&nbsp; The
power-by-the-hour contracts dictate the method by which we pay a vendor based on our actual level of operations in exchange for vendor coverage on specific parts and equipment on our aircraft when those parts and equipment are in need of repair or replacement.&nbsp;
Each contract varies in term and payment procedure.&nbsp; The estimated amount of our future commitment is based on assumptions related to future level of operations and forecasted payment rates.&nbsp; Our level of operations, under the Continental CPA, is determined
by Continental, which has exclusive scheduling authority over our fleet under the Continental CPA.&nbsp; The level of operations inherent in the estimate is based on Continental&rsquo;s most recent operating plan for us, which can be altered at Continental&rsquo;s
sole discretion and included operations for the 30 aircraft operating outside the Continental CPA.&nbsp; Forecasted payment rates are based on actual rates as of December 31, 2008 and increased annually according to the particular inflation indices detailed in each
contract.&nbsp; Contractual rate increases at actual time of occurrence may be different than the forecasted rates.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; See a summary of all our contractual obligations in Item 7. &ldquo;Management&rsquo;s Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations &ndash;
Liquidity and Capital Commitments &ndash; Contractual Obligations and Commercial Commitments.&rdquo;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>General Guarantees and Indemnifications.</i></b>&nbsp; Pursuant to the Continental CPA, we indemnify Continental for certain of our actions and it indemnifies us
for some of its actions.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Additionally, we are party to many contracts, in which it is common for us to agree to indemnify third parties for tort liabilities that arise out of or relate to the
subject matter of the contract.&nbsp; In some cases, this indemnity extends to related liabilities arising from the negligence of the indemnified parties, but typically excludes liabilities caused by gross negligence or willful misconduct.&nbsp; We cannot estimate
the potential amount of future payments under these indemnities until events arise that would trigger a liability under the indemnities.&nbsp; However, we expect to be covered by insurance for a material portion of these liabilities, subject to deductibles, policy
terms and condition.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Employees.</i></b><i></i>&nbsp; As of December 31, 2008, approximately 77% of our employees were covered by collective bargaining agreements.&nbsp; Our contracts
with our pilots, dispatchers, flight attendants, and mechanics will be amendable in December 2010, July 2009, August 2010 and August 2009, respectively.&nbsp; Our contract with our production workers does not have a term but salaries are typically renegotiated each
year.&nbsp; Our other employees are not covered by collective bargaining agreements.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Legal Proceedings.</i></b>&nbsp; We are a defendant in various lawsuits and proceedings arising in the ordinary course of our business.&nbsp; While the outcome of
these lawsuits and proceedings cannot be predicted with certainty and could have a material adverse effect on our financial position, results of operations or cash flows, we do not believe that the ultimate disposition of these proceedings will have a material
adverse effect on our financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Note 16 &ndash; Related Party Transactions</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The following is a summary of significant related party transactions that occurred during the three years ended December 31, 2008, other than those discussed elsewhere
in the Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Continental controls the scheduling, ticket prices and seat inventories with respect to Airlines&rsquo; operations under the Continental CPA.&nbsp; In connection with
this activity, Continental performs all sales and ticketing functions for Airlines on Continental ticket stock and receives cash directly from the sale of Airlines&rsquo; tickets.&nbsp; Continental purchases or provides payment of certain items on our behalf,
including, aircraft rent, fuel, certain payroll expenditures (including related benefits) and insurance, and charges us amounts as stipulated in the agreement.&nbsp; In general, transfers or sales of assets between us and Continental are recorded at net book
value.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Continental provides various services to us and charges us amounts at rates in accordance with the Continental CPA and other agreements.&nbsp; The services provided to
us by Continental are as follows.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Under our amended master facility and ground handling agreement with Continental, rent expenses are allocated to us at the airport locations where Airlines
operates.&nbsp; Additionally, all terminal facility rents at the hub airports are now borne by Continental and Airlines pays for incremental rent at other Continental&ndash;managed locations unless Continental does not operate any aircraft there.&nbsp; In these
situations, Airlines is responsible for the rent expense.&nbsp; At locations Airlines manages, rent is allocated between Continental and Airlines based on the number of respective passengers.&nbsp; At common locations for Branded Flying and Continental, Airlines has
agreed to allocate the cost of common items based on monthly departures.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Revenue earned from Continental, including both the Continental CPA and our fixed rate ground handling revenue, was $1.0 billion, $1.4 billion and $1.7 billion for the
years ended December 31, 2008, 2007, and 2006, respectively.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="item9"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Item 9. Changes in and Disagreement with Accountants on Accounting and Financial Disclosure</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There were no disagreements on any matters of accounting principles of financial statement disclosure between us and our independent auditors.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On November 20, 2008, the Audit Committee of our Board of Directors engaged KPMG LLP (&ldquo;KPMG&rdquo;) to serve as our independent registered public accounting firm
for the fiscal year ending December 31, 2009.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="item9a"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Item 9A. Controls and Procedures</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> <i>(a) Evaluation of disclosure controls and procedures</i>.&nbsp; Based on their evaluation of our disclosure controls and procedures as of the end of the
period covered by this report, our Chief Executive Officer and Chief Financial Officer have concluded that our disclosure controls and procedures are effective.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="3" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font> <i><font size="2" face="Arial">(b) Changes in internal control over financial reporting.</font></i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp; We have not
identified any material weakness in our internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2008.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>(c)</i> <i>The Board of Directors, acting through its Audit Committee, is responsible for the oversight of our accounting policies, financial reporting and internal
control</i>.&nbsp; The Audit Committee is comprised entirely of outside directors who are independent and approves decisions regarding the appointment or removal of the Director of Internal Audit.&nbsp; It meets periodically with management, the independent auditors
and the internal auditors to ensure that they are carrying out their responsibilities.&nbsp; The Audit Committee is also responsible for performing an oversight role by reviewing the Company&rsquo;s financial reports.&nbsp; The independent auditors and the internal
auditors have full and unlimited access to the Audit Committee, with or without management, to discuss the adequacy of internal control over financial reporting, and any other matters which they believe should be brought to the attention of the Audit
Committee.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="item9b"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Item 9B. Other Information</font></b></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">None</font></p>

<p align="center"><a name="reportofindependentregistered"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">REPORT OF INDEPENDENT REGISTERED PUBLIC ACCOUNTING FIRM</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">The Board of Directors and Shareholders of</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">ExpressJet Holdings, Inc.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We have audited the consolidated financial statements of ExpressJet Holdings, Inc. (the &ldquo;Company&rdquo;) as of December 31, 2008 and 2007, and for each of the
three years in the period ended December 31, 2008, and have issued our report thereon dated February 27, 2009 (included elsewhere in this Form 10-K).&nbsp; Our audits also included the financial statement schedule listed in Item 15(a)(2) of this Form 10-K.&nbsp; This
schedule is the responsibility of the Company&rsquo;s management.&nbsp; Our responsibility is to express an opinion based on our audits.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In our opinion, the financial statement schedule referred to above, when considered in relation to the basic financial statements taken as a whole, presents fairly in
all material respects the information set forth therein.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face=
"Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
/s/ ERNST &amp; YOUNG LLP</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(1)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">The deferred tax asset valuation allowance includes the net tax agreement obligation to Continental.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(2)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&ldquo;Deductions from reserve&rdquo; related to the allowance for obsolescence consists of entries made to remove spare parts with zero net book value from our general ledger.&nbsp; &ldquo;Deductions from reserve&rdquo; related to the
deferred tax asset valuation allowance are related to payments made to Continental under the tax agreement.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(3)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&ldquo;Other&rdquo; related to the deferred tax asset valuation allowance for 2005 is related to the adjustment of the fair value of the tax basis of our tangible and intangible assets as described in Item 8. &ldquo;Financial Statements
and Supplementary Data &ndash; Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements &ndash; Note 10 &ndash; Income Taxes.&rdquo;</font></p>
